{[%evp 0,34,36,30,27,0,4,4,63,41,41,43,43,43,43,18,18,18,3,0,0,0,5,3,13,4,4,4,10,-5,26,-11,6,6,6,19,15]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d5 3. Nc3 g6 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bg5 {A rare move and deservedly so. Indeed, the e7-e5 thrust is prevented, but the real danger is coming from the other side.} (7. Ba3 {is pinning the e7-pawn from the other side, whilst trying to stop the thematic c7-c5. Black will naturally insist on the latter with the subtle} Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5]} ({For the sake of initiating counterplay the alternative} 7... O-O {can be postponed.}) 8. Nf3 (8. Qb3 c5 9. Rd1 Qa5 10. Nf3 O-O (10... cxd4 $143 $6 11. Bb4) 11. Bd3 ({it is not easy at all to find a proper place for this bishop, for example} 11. Bc4 {is met by the very imaginative pawn sacrifice} Nb6 $1 12. Bxc5 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 Qc7 {[%cal Gb7b6] , when the light-squared bishop will be very annoying after} 14. Qd3 b6 15. Ba3 a5 $15 {[%cal Gc8a6] More of this original concept can be found in Chapter 9}) (11. Be2 Nf6 12. Bxc5 $140 Nxe4 13. Bb4 Qb6 $15) 11... b5 $1 12. Bb1 Qb6 13. O-O a5 $15) (8. Bc4 c5 9. Qb3 {is going to expose these pieces to Black's actions on the queenside -} O-O 10. Nf3 (10. Ne2 $6 Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) 10... b5 $5 (10... Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) (10... Nb6) 11. Bxb5 (11. Bd5 $6 Rb8 12. O-O c4 13. Qc2 Rb6 $17 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge7e6]}) 11... Rb8 12. Qa4 Nf6 $146 (12... Nb6) 13. Bc6 (13. O-O Nxe4 14. Rac1 $11) (13. Bxc5 $6 Nxe4 14. Bb4 Bg4 $15) (13. e5 $2 Nd5 $17 {[%csl Rc3]}) 13... cxd4 14. e5 (14. cxd4 $2 Rb6 $19 {[%csl Ra3,Ra4,Rc6][%cal Gb6a6]}) (14. Nxd4 Qc7 15. O-O Rb6 $17 {[%csl Rc6,Rd4][%cal Ge7e5]}) 14... Rb6 $5 (14... Nd5 15. cxd4 Bg4 $132) 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Nxd4 (16. cxd4 Ra6 $17 {[%csl Ra3,Rc6]}) 16... Bxd4 (16... Ba6 $5) 17. cxd4 Ra6 18. Qb4 Rxc6 19. O-O $11) 8... c5 9. Qb3 (9. Bc4 cxd4 10. Qb3 O-O 11. cxd4 Nb6 ({Black can also harass the enemy pieces on the queenside in the familiar manner by} 11... Rb8 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) 12. O-O (12. Be2 Be6 13. Qb4 {in Akobian - Xiong, Saint Louis, 2018, can be countered with} Rc8 $5 {[%cal Gb6c4]} 14. Qxe7 $140 Nc4 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 $15) 12... Nxc4 13. Qxc4 Bg4 14. Ne5 Be6 15. Qb4 {created a similar battery in Stopa - Kozakov, Wroclaw, 2004, to which} Qb6 $11 {seems to be an easy equalizer}) 9... O-O {may simply transpose, let us have a look at more restrained moves by ?f1.} 10. Be2 (10. Bd3 Rb8 $1 11. O-O b5 12. Qc2 a6 13. Rfd1 Bb7 $15 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gc7a5]}) (10. Rd1 Qa5 $132) 10... cxd4 (10... Rb8 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5] deserves attention here as well, even though after} 11. O-O b5 {is coming without winning a tempo, Black has every chance to take over the initiative after} 12. Rad1 Qc7 $132) (10... a6 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) 11. cxd4 Nf6 12. e5 Be6 $5 (12... Nd5 13. O-O) 13. Qxb7 Nd5 14. O-O Rb8 $1 {and the game is about to finish in a draw by repetion after both and} 15. Qxa7 (15. Qa6 Nf4 16. Rfb1 (16. Bc5 $6 Bd5 17. Rfb1 Qd7 $15) 16... Bc8 17. Qc4 Be6 18. Qa6 $11) 15... Ra8 (15... Nf4 $6 16. Bd1) 16. Qc5 Rc8 17. Qa7 ({White cannot rely on more than a compensation for the exchange after} 17. Qb5 Nc3 18. Qb2 Nxe2+ 19. Qxe2 Bc4 20. Qd2 Bxf1 21. Rxf1 Qd7 $11) 17... Ra8 $11) 7... c5 8. Rc1 {Only this move can justify the bishop sally.} ({White's center is about to fall apart after} 8. Nf3 $6 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg7c3]}) 8... O-O {The threat against the d-pawn has been resumed and it is time for} 9. Nf3 ({The direct} 9. d5 {can be met by} Qa5 ({Black has other options for getting the e7-pawn out of the pin -} 9... Qd6 $5) ({and especially} 9... h6 $5 10. Be3 e6 11. Bxc5 Re8 $44) 10. Qd2 e6 11. d6 (11. c4 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 b6 $132) 11... b5 $146 12. h4 (12. Be7 $6 Re8 13. h4 (13. Nf3 Bb7 14. Bd3 c4 15. Bb1 Nc6 $15) 13... Nc6 14. Bg5 b4 $15 {and Black's counterplay on the queenside is much faster}) (12. Nf3 Bb7 13. Bh6 Bxe4 14. h4 {is a better version of the early wing aggression -} Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nd7 16. h5 c4 17. hxg6 hxg6 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qh6+ Kf6 {and White should probably force the perpetual with} 20. Qh4+ $11 ({, for the opponent seems to have enough resources to meet} 20. Rh4 e5 21. f4 Rh8 22. fxe5+ Nxe5 23. Qf4+ Ke6 24. Bh3+ f5 25. Kf1 Rxh4 26. Qxh4 Qd8 $11)) (12. Bh6 Bxh6 13. Qxh6 Nd7 14. h4 {is successfully parried by} f6 15. h5 g5 16. f4 Qa3 17. Rc2 Qa4 18. Re2 Qa3 $11) 12... Nd7 13. h5 (13. Bh6 Bxh6 14. Qxh6 {transposes to the line from above}) 13... b4 $1 14. Ne2 Ba6 $1 15. hxg6 fxg6 $1 (15... hxg6 $2 16. Bh6 $16) 16. f4 Rab8 $5 {can be easier labelled as a human approach - the rook is ready to operate along the b-file. Black's chances are not worse in the complicated fight -} (16... Bxe2 17. Qxe2 bxc3 (17... Bxc3+ 18. Kd1 $13) 18. Qa6 Qb4 19. Qc4 Qb2 {is leading to wild complications after} 20. Qxe6+ Rf7 21. f5 Ne5 22. d7 Rd8 $1 {, the sample line} 23. Qe8+ Rf8 24. Qe6+ Kh8 25. Rxh7+ Kxh7 26. fxg6+ Nxg6 27. Qh3+ Kg8 28. Bc4+ Rf7 {does never go beyond the equilibrium, for example} 29. Bxf7+ Kxf7 30. Qf5+ Kg8 31. Qxg6 Qxg2 32. Qe6+ $11) 17. e5 Rf5 $1 18. Rh3 bxc3 ({the tempting exchange sacrifice} 18... Rxg5 19. fxg5 Bxe5 {looks promising, e.g.} 20. cxb4 cxb4 21. Rc7 Nc5 $44) 19. Qxc3 (19. Rhxc3 Qa4 $132) 19... Qxc3+ 20. Rhxc3 Bxe5 21. Re3 Bxd6 22. Rxe6 Rb6 23. Rd1 Bxf4 24. Re8+ Nf8 25. Bxf4 Bxe2 26. Bxe2 Rxf4 27. Rd7 a5 28. Rde7 $44 {/=/}) 9... Bg4 10. d5 Nd7 $1 (10... Qd6 {e6 is coming to mind again.}) 11. Be2 (11. d6 $2 {is simply bad because of} Bf6 $17) (11. Qd2 {allows} Bxf3 12. gxf3 Ne5 {with full play for Black, for example} 13. Qe3 (13. Be2 f5 $1) 13... f5 $1 14. f4 Nf7 15. h4 Qd6 $132) ({White has trouble in keeping his center after} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 f5 $132 {as well.}) 11... c4 $1 {An instructive idea, which is like being pasted from the Benoni, including the common trade of Nf3 for establishing control over the long diagonal. True, here the enemy b-pawn has already moved to the c3-square and now it is fixed, while the own knight will be activated.} 12. Qd2 {White must give up the dreams for an advantage:} (12. O-O Nc5 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 b5 $132) (12. Bxc4 Rc8 {is definitely fine for Black, for instance} 13. Bb3 (13. Be2 Bxc3+ 14. Kf1 Bf6 $15) 13... Bxc3+ 14. Kf1 Nf6 15. h3 Bd7 $132) (12. Nd4 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 {is running into} Nc5 $15) (12. d6 $6 {is once again dubious in the view of} Bf6 $1 13. Bxf6 (13. Bh6 Re8 $15) 13... Nxf6 $1 ({a natural improvement upon} 13... exf6 14. O-O Rc8 15. Qd4 {Shankland - Ding Liren, chess.com INT, 2019} Qa5 16. Rfd1 Rfd8 $11) 14. e5 Nd7 15. Qd4 (15. O-O Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Nxe5 17. Bxb7 Rb8 $15) 15... Bxf3 16. Bxf3 {The central pawns are very shaky and Black took over the initiative -} exd6 17. exd6 (17. Bxb7 Rb8) 17... Re8+ 18. Kf1 Ne5 19. Bxb7 $2 (19. Re1 Nd3 $15) 19... Rb8 20. Be4 Rb6 21. g3 Rxd6 22. Qxa7 Rd2 $19 {Shankland - Ding Liren, chess. com INT, 2019.}) 12... Nc5 ({Indeed, Black can continue with} 12... Rc8 {at first.}) 13. Qe3 Rc8 14. O-O b5 15. Rfd1 Re8 16. h3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Qb6 $132 *

