{[%evp 0,50,30,27,27,4,45,37,68,51,51,51,51,50,50,36,36,32,26,25,50,19,49,42,65,45,57,56,49,42,44,43,43,54,54,54,37,50,53,64,66,24,29,11,47,2,14,29,32,30,33,0,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bb5+ {The idea is to prevent, at least temporarily, Black from smoothly executing the thematic advance c7-c5 and hinder the development of the knight to its usual c6-square. White's hope is to reinforce the center before the opponent gets ready to strike at it, but this plan is also time-consuming. Moreover, Bb5/a4 may soon find itself without any targets on the diagonal in front of it.} c6 8. Ba4 O-O ({The expansion} 8... b5 $5 9. Bb3 a5 {is a worthy additional opportunity.}) 9. Ne2 (9. Nf3 {is also providing Black with original ideas like} Qa5 $5 ({here} 9... b5 10. Bb3 a5 {is staying on the map as well}) 10. O-O (10. Bd2 Qa6 $1 {[%cal Ga6f1] The point - White has to find a solution to the concrete problem with the king.} 11. Bb3 (11. Rb1 Bg4) 11... c5 12. Qe2 (12. d5 $6 e6 $15) 12... cxd4 $5 ({now and then, Black is by no means obliged to} 12... Qxe2+ 13. Kxe2) 13. cxd4 Bg4 14. Qxa6 Nxa6 15. Ne5 Bxe5 16. dxe5 Nc5 17. f3 (17. Bc2 $6 Rfd8 18. f3 Be6 $15) 17... Nxb3 18. axb3 Be6 $11) 10... Bg4 $1 ({The development should never be neglected - instead,} 10... Qxc3 $6 11. Rb1 $36 {will put her Majesty in danger}) 11. Rb1 {is provoking} (11. Be3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nd7 $5 ({it is still a bit early for} 12... Qxc3 13. Rb1 {- 11.îRb1.}) 13. Rc1 Rfd8 $132) (11. Bd2 {is just protecting the hanging pawn.} e6 $5 ({A sign that Black is planning to revert to advancing the c-pawn, an alternative is} 11... Nd7 {, when the push of the e-pawn is in the air}) 12. Rb1 (12. Bb3 c5 13. d5 Nd7 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 c4 $5 {(a very ellegant solution)} 16. Bxc4 Ne5 17. Qe2 Nxc4 18. Qxc4 exd5 19. exd5 Rfd8 $11) (12. e5 c5 (12... Rc8 $5) 13. Rb1 Qa6 14. Be3 Nc6 15. Qb3 Rab8 16. Bb5 Qb6 17. dxc5 Qc7 $11) ({it is arguable to what extent} 12. Re1 {is useful in a line like} b5 13. Bb3 c5 14. a4 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qd8 16. axb5 cxd4 17. cxd4 Bxd4 $132) 12... b5 {is complex, but Black's prospects are not worse:} 13. Bb3 (13. Bc2 c5 14. a4 ({with an unprotected a-pawn} 14. c4 $6 {is not recommendable in the view of} b4 $17) 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 a6 16. e5 Nc6 {with considerable pressure along the c- and d-files after} 17. axb5 ({or} 17. Be4 Rac8 {with a probable transposition}) ({so is with} 17. f4 Rfd8 18. Be4 Rac8 $11) 17... axb5 18. Be4 Rac8 19. f4 Rfd8 {Now} 20. c4 {can radically change the character of the position -} Qa2 $5 (20... b4 21. Ra1 Qb6 22. d5 Nd4 23. Be3 Nf5 24. d6 f6 $13) 21. cxb5 (21. Bxc6 Rxc6 22. cxb5 Rcc8 $11) 21... Nxd4 22. b6 Rb8 23. b7 Bh6 {with mutual chances, for example} 24. Ra1 Qb2 25. Ra8 (25. Rb1 $11) 25... Rf8 $1 26. Rxb8 Rxb8 27. Be3 Ne2+ 28. Kh1 Nc3 29. Qd7 Nxe4 30. Qc8+ Kg7 31. Qxb8 Qe2 $11) 13... Nd7 (13... c5 $5 14. c4 Qc7 15. cxb5 Bxd4 16. h3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nd7 $11) 14. c4 (14. a4 a6) 14... b4 {and the game can take an unexpected turn after} 15. d5 Ne5 16. Nxe5 $1 Bxd1 17. Nxc6 Qb6 18. Rfxd1 exd5 19. cxd5 ({the powerful passed pawn after} 19. exd5 {seems to guarantee White enough compensation -} Rfe8 20. c5 Qxc5 21. Bxb4 Qb6 22. Ba5 Qb5 23. a4 Qa6 $11) 19... a5 20. Be3 Qa6 $132) 11... Bxf3 12. gxf3 b5 13. Bb3 Qxc3 {and now:} 14. Be3 (14. e5 Na6 15. Be3 (15. e6 f5 16. Bg5 Rae8 17. Rc1 Qxd4 18. Rxc6 Nc5 $11) 15... c5 16. Rc1 Qb4 17. dxc5 Rad8 18. Qe2 Bxe5 {may end in an original perpetual after} 19. Bh6 Bxh2+ 20. Kg2 Qh4 21. Qe3 Rd3 $1 22. Qxd3 Qxh6 23. Rh1 Qg5+ 24. Kxh2 Qh6+ 25. Kg2 Qg5+ $11) 14... a5 15. Qe2 (15. a4 bxa4 16. Bxa4 Rd8 17. Rc1 Qb4 $11) 15... a4 16. Rfc1 Qa5 17. Bd1 (17. Bc2 Nd7 $5 ({an attempt to improve on} 17... e6 18. e5 Qd8 19. Be4 Ra6 $13 {White has compensation, but not more, Moroni - Kovchan, Trieste, 2022}) 18. e5 f5 $1 19. d5 (19. Bd1 Rfc8) 19... Nxe5 20. dxc6 Nxc6 21. Rxb5 Qa6 22. Bd3 Nd4 23. Bxd4 Bxd4 24. Qxe7 Qf6 $11) 17... e6 18. d5 exd5 19. exd5 Qa6 20. dxc6 Nxc6 21. Qxb5 Qxb5 22. Rxb5 Rfd8 23. Kg2 Nd4 24. Rb4 a3 25. Bg5 Rd5 $11) 9... c5 {Now the game is back to the standard Gruenfeld structure.} ({With a pawn on the c6-square} 9... e5 {is worth considering.}) ({Black has one more opportunity for} 9... b5 $5 10. Bb3 (10. Bc2 c5) 10... a5) 10. O-O (10. d5 e6 11. O-O a6 $132 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) ({It is hard to believe in} 10. h4 $6 {, when the bishop is on the a4-square - such broad strategy is unlikely to bring any dividents, for example} cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc6 12. Be3 (12. Bb2 Be6 {[%cal Ge6c4]} 13. h5 Bc4 14. hxg6 hxg6 $15) 12... Qa5+ $1 13. Kf1 (13. Bd2 Qa6 $15) 13... Rd8 14. Bb3 (14. h5 Qa6 $1 15. hxg6 hxg6 16. d5 Bd7 17. Kg1 Ne5 18. Bxd7 Nxd7 $15) 14... Qa6 15. Kg1 h5 {(a radical measure against the marching pawn, after which Black can entirely concentrate on the opposite flank)} 16. Rc1 Na5 $15) 10... cxd4 $5 ({A step towards a concrete operation against the queenside pawns. Alternatively,} 10... Nc6 11. Be3 Na5 {is a typical manoeuvre for chasing the light-squared bishop, while here Black can try to make use of its absence from the c4-square.}) 11. cxd4 Bg4 $1 ({In case of} 11... Nc6 12. Be3 Bg4 13. f3 {the bishop is practically deprived of the e6-square, so Black is left in a cramped situation after} Bd7 14. Rc1 $14) 12. f3 (12. Be3 Bxd4 $1 {is giving rise to exciting complications -} 13. Qxd4 Bxe2 14. Qb2 (14. Rfc1 Qxd4 15. Bxd4 Na6 $11) 14... Bxf1 15. Bh6 f6 16. Qxb7 (16. Rxf1 Na6) 16... Na6 17. Bb3+ (17. Rd1 Bd3 $1 18. Bxf8 Nc5 19. Qb4 Qb6 20. Qxb6 axb6 21. Bxe7 Rxa4 22. Bxc5 bxc5 23. Rxd3 $11) 17... Kh8 18. Bxf8 Qxf8 19. Kxf1 Nc5 $11) 12... Be6 $1 13. Be3 {Resuming the positional threat 14.d5.} (13. Bb3 Bxb3 14. axb3 Nc6 15. Be3 e6 16. Qd2 Qd6 $11 {[%cal Gf8d8]}) (13. Rb1 Bxa2 14. Rxb7 Bc4 $11) 13... Bc4 $1 14. Re1 $146 ({In reply to} 14. Rb1 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Bxd4 {should gradually equalize -} 16. Rxb7 Qd6 ({there is also} 16... Qc8 17. Rb3 Qc5 $11) 17. Re1 Na6 18. Rd7 Bxe3+ 19. Qxe3 Qb4 20. Rd4 Qb6 $11 {Bernasek - Plat, Czech Republic, 2009}) ({The textmove is an attempt to improve on} 14. Rf2 Nd7 (14... Na6) (14... b5) 15. Rc1 Nb6 16. Bb3 Rc8 17. d5 Qd6 $11 {Peev - Stean, Lublin, 1975.}) 14... Nc6 $1 (14... Nd7 15. Rc1 Nb6 16. Bb3 Rc8 17. d5 Qd6 18. Qd2 $14) (14... b5 15. Bb3) 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Rc1 {In the next Chapters we are going to see many examples with the same pawn structure, but without the queens. As a rule, in such positions Black is ready to sacrifice the isolated c-pawn, relying on the bishops and timely counterplay with the help of f7-f5. Here White is simply unable to defend simultaneously the a2- and d4-pawns, the full equality is within reach.} (16. Nf4 $6 e5 $1 {spells danger only for White}) (16. Qd2 Bxe2 17. Rxe2 c5 $11) (16. Qa4 Bxe2 (16... Bb5 $5 17. Qb4 Qd6) 17. Rxe2 c5 18. Rd1 cxd4 19. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 20. Rxd4 Qb6 $11) 16... Bxa2 17. Rxc6 ({After} 17. Qa4 Be6 18. Nf4 Bd7 19. Rc5 {White can claim compensation for the missing pawn, but hardly more, for instance} a5 20. Nd3 Qc7 $11) 17... Be6 ({Once again Black should watch for the advance of the d4-pawn, it is therefore early for him to relax, as shown by} 17... a5 $6 18. d5 a4 19. Nc1 $1 {[%csl Ra2]} Bb1 20. Rb6 Rb8 21. Rxb8 Qxb8 22. Qxa4 Be5 $14) 18. d5 Bd7 19. Ra6 (19. Rc1 $6 a5 $15 {[%csl Ga5]}) 19... e6 $1 {A well-timed counterstrike, which should liquidate to a draw.} 20. dxe6 (20. Rxa7 Rxa7 21. Bxa7 Qa5 22. Bd4 Bxd4+ 23. Nxd4 exd5 24. exd5 Qxd5 $11) (20. d6 Bb5 21. Rxa7 (21. Ra2 Bc4 $11) 21... Rxa7 22. Bxa7 Be5 $11 {should also restore the material balance in few more moves}) (20. Bc5 Re8 {is helpful only for Black.}) (20. Nf4 Bb5 $1 21. Rxa7 Rxa7 22. Bxa7 Qa5 (22... Bc3 $5) 23. Bf2 Bc3 24. dxe6 (24. Re3 $2 e5 25. Ne2 Bd2 $17) 24... fxe6 (24... Bxe1 25. Bxe1 Qa4 26. Qd2 Qa1 27. exf7+ Rxf7 28. Nd5 Rd7 $11) 25. Nxe6 (25. Qd6 Bxe1 26. Qxe6+ Rf7 27. Qc8+ $11) 25... Bxe1 26. Bxe1 Qb6+ 27. Nd4 Bc4 {and Black should hold, especially without the queens. Moreover, after} 28. h4 Qb2 29. Bf2 Ra8 {White is obliged to offer that exchange -} 30. Qc2 Ra1+ 31. Kh2 Qxc2 32. Nxc2 Ra2 33. Ne3 Rxf2 34. Nxc4 $11) (20. Qd2 Bb5 21. Rxa7 Rxa7 22. Bxa7 exd5 23. Qxd5 (23. exd5 Re8 $11) 23... Qxd5 24. exd5 Re8 25. Kf2 Re5 26. d6 Rd5 27. Rb1 Be5 $11) 20... Bxe6 21. Qxd8 (21. Nf4 Bc4 22. Rc6 Qxd1 23. Rxd1 Rfc8 24. Rxc8+ Rxc8 25. Bxa7 Ra8 {and, in spite of being a pawn down, Black should hold without much trouble after} (25... Be5 $5) 26. Be3 Ra1 27. Rxa1 Bxa1 $11) 21... Rfxd8 22. Rxa7 Bh6 $5 (22... Rxa7 23. Bxa7 h5 {is similar to the previous note, so is with the text.}) 23. Bb6 Rxa7 24. Bxa7 Bc4 25. Ng3 Bd2 $44 {/=/} *

