{[%evp 0,44,27,13,26,4,37,42,68,50,50,50,50,50,49,16,8,26,17,4,14,42,51,50,50,47,24,3,-2,1,24,55,60,26,29,35,32,0,16,15,0,0,0,0,0,0,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 {The tricky check} 7. Qa4+ {will be the last of White's minor alternatives on move 7.} Nd7 $5 ({More flexible than} 7... Qd7 {, Black will try to harass Qa4 on the next moves.}) 8. Nf3 (8. Be3 {with developing the queenside at first is likely to transpose after} O-O) 8... O-O 9. Be2 (9. Be3 c5 10. Rc1 a6 ({Black can also prepare this queenside expansion by} 10... Qc7) 11. Be2 (11. dxc5 Qc7 12. Qc4 Nf6 $44 {[%cal Gc8e6]}) 11... b5 12. Qc2 Bb7 13. O-O Qc7 {with mutual chances -} 14. d5 c4 15. a4 Nf6 ({a curious gambit idea is} 15... e6 $5 16. dxe6 Nc5 17. exf7+ $140 Rxf7 18. Nd2 Be5 19. g3 Rd8 $44) 16. axb5 axb5 17. Nd4 Qe5 $1 18. Nxb5 (18. Bf3 e6) 18... Qxe4 19. Qxe4 Nxe4 20. Rfd1 $11) (9. Bg5 c5 10. Rc1 ({a drawback of the more active devlopment of Rc1 can be seen in} 10. Qa3 Nf6 $1 11. e5 Ne4 12. Be3 Bf5 $132) ({it makes sense to move Ra1 away from the scope of Bg7, but} 10. Rd1 Qc7 {seems to be an inferior version of the text}) 10... Qc7 11. Bd3 (11. Be2 a6 12. O-O b5 13. Qc2 Bb7 {is double-edged, an original temporary pawn sacrifice is shown by} 14. d5 c4 $5 15. Bxe7 Rfe8 16. d6 Qc6 $132) 11... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} ({here is the first opportunity for} 11... e5 {, but in fact this pawn is not really hanging yet}) 12. Qa3 (12. O-O b5 13. Qd1 e5 $132) 12... b5 ({here too,} 12... e5 $5 {is possible, though Black does not need to give a passed pawn to the opponent}) 13. Bxb5 (13. Bxe7 $143 $6 Re8 14. Bxc5 Nxc5 15. Qxc5 Qxc5 16. dxc5 Bb7 {with plenty of initiative, Degtiarev - Kasimdzhanov, Douglas, 2017, a sample line is} 17. Nd2 Bh6 18. Ke2 f5 19. f3 fxe4 20. Bxe4 Rac8 $11) 13... axb5 14. Qxa8 Bb7 15. Qa3 Bxe4 $44) (9. Qa3 {is a bit slow and Black can show his cards in the center -} e5 $5 ({or the usual strike} 9... c5) 10. Bd3 (10. Bg5 Bf6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Bd3 exd4 {transposes to 10.î?d3}) 10... exd4 11. cxd4 c5 12. Bg5 Bf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. e5 Qe7 15. O-O Re8 16. Rac1 ({the ambitious} 16. e6 $5 fxe6 17. Rfe1 cxd4 18. Qb2 Nc5 19. Bc4 d3 20. Ne5 {took place in Koneru - Tokhirjonova, Chennai, 2022, when Black's best seems to be} b6 $11 {, mobilizing the queenside as quickly as possible}) 16... cxd4 17. Qxe7 Rxe7 18. Rc7 Kf8 19. Rfc1 Nb6 20. Rxe7 Kxe7 21. Nxd4 (21. Rc7+ Nd7 {[%cal Ge7d8]}) 21... Bd7 22. f4 Nd5 23. g3 Rc8 24. Rxc8 Bxc8 $11 {[%cal Gf7f6] A. Lenderman - R. Perez, New York, 2021.}) ({the bizarre} 9. h4 {should not confuse Black, for example} e5 10. Ba3 (10. h5 exd4 11. cxd4 Nc5 $5 12. Qc2 Ne6 13. Bb2 c5 $132) (10. Bg5 Qe8) 10... Re8 11. d5 c6 12. dxc6 Nb6 13. Qb3 Qc7 $132) 9... c5 (9... Nb6 10. Qb4 $140 Qd6 {seems playable, though most of the Gruenfeld devotees would prefer the thematic push in the main text.}) 10. O-O (10. Qa3 $5 {is quite typical, though White is not at all obliged to hurry with it and provide the opponent with additional opportunities.} cxd4 $5 ({Worth checking is} 10... b6 11. e5 Bb7 12. h4 b5 $5 $13) 11. cxd4 Nf6 {reveals such a difference:} 12. Qe3 (12. e5 Nd5 13. O-O (13. h4 $6 Bg4) 13... Bf5 $11) 12... Bd7 (12... b5 $5 13. h3 Qb6 14. O-O a5 15. a3 Bb7 16. Bd3 Rfc8 17. Re1 e6 $11 {Baciak - Tylecek, ICCF email, 2020}) 13. Rb1 $5 ({White's center was mercilessly destroyed after} 13. O-O $6 Bc6 14. Bd3 Ng4 $1 15. Qe2 Bxd4 16. Nxd4 Qxd4 17. Bb2 Qd6 $15 {Aronian - Vachier Lagrave, chess24.com INT, 2021}) 13... Qa5+ 14. Bd2 Qxa2 15. O-O a5 $5 16. Bd3 a4 17. Bb4 Rfc8 $13) 10... Nb6 $1 ({Black should not be tempted by} 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc5 $6 {because of} 12. dxc5 $1 Bxa1 13. e5 $36 {- a nasty positional trap, which is worth remembering!}) 11. Qa3 {The retreat to this common square for the queen is definitely the most challenging continuation.} (11. Qd1 {can hardly pretend for much. Indeed, Black's knight has been lured to the b6-square, but the usual pressure against the d4-pawn is present -} cxd4 (11... Bg4 12. Be3 e6 $11) 12. cxd4 Bg4 13. Be3 Rc8 {[%cal Gb6c4]} 14. Rb1 Qd6 $11 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gb6c4]}) (11. Qb3 $146 {is exposing the queen to} cxd4 12. cxd4 Be6 $1 13. Qb1 (13. Qb4 {is well countered with} Qd6 $1 {, not fearing} 14. Qxd6 exd6 15. Bf4 {, when 15...?c4 is reasonable and good, it can be even preceded by} Rfe8 $11 16. Bxd6 Bc4) (13. Qb2 Qd6 $11) 13... Bc4 $5 ({Black may not force the events -} 13... Rc8) ({or the preliminary} 13... Qd7) 14. Bxc4 Nxc4 15. Qxb7 Bxd4 16. Nxd4 Qxd4 17. Bf4 Qf6 $11) (11. Qb5 cxd4 12. cxd4 {leaves Black with a choice of how to take the central pawn: the insertion of} Bg4 ({here} 12... Bxd4 $5 {is objectively risky -} 13. Nxd4 (13. Rd1 $2 Bd7 $17) 13... Qxd4 14. Bb2 (14. Bh6 Bd7 15. Qg5 Rfe8 $11) 14... Qxe4 15. Bf3 Qf5 16. Qb4 Be6 $1 {It is necessary to complete the development even at the cost of the extra pawns.} 17. Rfe1 Rac8 18. Qxe7 (18. Qd4 Qf6) 18... Bd5 19. Qh4 (19. Re5 Qc2) 19... h5 20. Bxd5 Nxd5 21. Qd4 f6 22. Qxa7 Rc2 $11) 13. Rd1 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 {before} Bxd4 {looks more solid due to some tactical intricacies -} 15. e5 (15. Bb2 e5 $11) (15. Ba3 Rc8 16. Rac1 Rxc1 17. Rxc1 Re8 18. e5 Qd7 19. Qxd7 Nxd7 20. Rd1 Bc5 $11) 15... Bxa1 16. Rxd8 Rfxd8 17. Bg5 {and Black is just in time for} Rac8 18. h4 Rc7 19. h5 Nc4 20. hxg6 hxg6 21. e6 f6 22. Qb1 $11) 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Bg4 13. Rd1 (13. Be3 $6 {is pointless in the view of} Bxf3 14. Bxf3 (14. gxf3 Bxd4) 14... Nc4 (14... Bxd4 {is less demanding, we can expect more exchanges and equality after} 15. Rad1 e5) 15. Qb3 Nxe3 16. fxe3 e5 {and, regarding the opposite-coloured bishops, Black is on the better half of the draw, Lalith - Gupta, Port Elizabeth, 2013.}) (13. Bg5 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 (14. gxf3 Qxd4 15. Rad1 (15. Bxe7 $143 Qd2 $1) 15... Qe5 (15... Qa4) 16. Qxe7 (16. Bxe7 Rfc8) 16... Qxe7 17. Bxe7 Rfc8 18. Bg5 ({in case of} 18. Rd2 Bh6 19. Rb2 {Chabanon - Gledura, Brest, 2019, the simplest is} Bf4 $11) 18... Rc2 (18... Na4 19. Rd7 b5 $11) 19. Rd2 Rxd2 20. Bxd2 Rc8 21. Rc1 (21. Rd1 Rc2 22. Bb4 Be5 $11) 21... Rxc1+ 22. Bxc1 Na4 $11 {and forty more moves of play did not shake the balance in Sumets - Alsina Leal, Hastings, 2013.}) 14... Qxd4 15. Rad1 ({the elimination of the a-pawn after} 15. Qxe7 Qa4 {is going to be a sign of Black's success in the opening phase -} 16. Rac1 ({after} 16. Rad1 Qxa2 17. Qxb7 Rab8 18. Qc6 {Matlakov - Artemiev, Sochi, 2015, my preference is for} Nc4 $11) 16... Rab8 $5 (16... Qxa2 17. Qxb7 Rab8 18. Qc6 $11 {is almost the same, Lenic - Tari, Warsaw, 2013,}) 17. Rc7 (17. a3 Rfe8 18. Qb4 Bf8 $11) (17. Bf4 Nd5 18. exd5 Qxf4 $11) 17... Qxa2 18. Rxb7 Rxb7 19. Qxb7 Bd4 $11) (15. Bxe7 Nc4 16. Qb4 a5 17. Qb5 {in Khenkin - Illingworth, Cammeray, 2013, is best answered with} Rfc8 $11) 15... Qe5 $5 (15... Qb2 16. Bxe7 Rfe8 {is palyable either -} 17. Qxb2 Bxb2 18. Bc5 {So far Shen Yang - Soumya, Astana, 2019, when} Nc4 19. Rd7 b6 $11 {looks safe enough}) (15... Qa4 16. Qxe7 {-15.Qe7}) 16. Bxe7 Rfe8 (16... Rfc8 17. Bd6 Qe8 $11) 17. Bd6 (17. Bh4 Qc3 $11) 17... Qe6 18. e5 (18. Bc5 $143 Nc4 $132) 18... Bxe5 (18... Nc4 $143 19. Qb3 Nxe5 20. Bd5 $1 $36) 19. Bxe5 Qxe5 20. Bxb7 Rab8 21. Bf3 Qe7 $11 {A. Lenderman - G. Jones, Astana, 2019.}) 13... Bxf3 14. gxf3 (14. Bxf3 {has been the choice of the World Champion, the critical position arises after} Bxd4 {, when Black seems to have antidots all over the place:} 15. e5 (15. Bh6 Re8 {and Black is ready to trade the queen for the rooks}) (15. Be3 Nc4 $1 {(the key resource for Black in order to hold after14.?:f3)} 16. Qb4 Nxe3 17. Rxd4 Nc2 18. Rxd8 Nxb4 19. Rd7 e6 $11) (15. Bg5 Nc4 $1 ({here we are again; until the e7-pawn is hanging, it is not recommended to enter} 15... Bxa1 $6 16. Rxd8 Rfxd8 17. Qxe7 Rd7 18. Qb4 $14) 16. Qb4 (16. Qa4 b5 $1) (16. Qb3 b5 $1) 16... b5 $1 {The point!} 17. Bxe7 (17. a4 {is running into} Qb6) (17. Qxb5 Nd6 18. Qe2 Bxa1 19. e5 Bxe5 20. Qxe5 Rc8 21. Bh6 (21. Qxe7 $143 $6 Qa5) 21... f6 22. Qe6+ {and White should be able to win the exchange back even after} Rf7 {, but more than equality cannot be expected}) 17... Qb6 {is arriving at another key crossroads:} 18. Bxf8 {leaves Black with an interesting choice, perhaps the best of these options is the intermediate advance} (18. Rxd4 Qxd4 19. Rd1 Qe5 ({the textmove is solid, but Black can safely force the exchange of the queens by means of} 19... Qb2) 20. Bxf8 Rxf8 21. a4 a6 22. axb5 axb5 $11) 18... a5 $1 (18... Bxa1 $6 19. Bc5) 19. Qe7 (19. Bc5 axb4 20. Bxb6 Bxa1 21. Rd8+ Rxd8 22. Bxd8 $11) 19... Bxa1 20. Rxa1 ({no better is} 20. Bh6 {, when} Bf6 {will chase the queen back to its camp}) 20... Rxf8 21. Rd1 Qb8 $11) 15... Nc4 $1 (15... Bxa1 $6 16. Rxd8 Rfxd8 17. e6 Bf6 18. exf7+ Kxf7 19. h4 $16) 16. Qb4 ({an essential concrete line goes on with} 16. Qa4 b5 $1 17. Qxb5 Rc8 18. Bf4 Bxa1 19. Rxd8 Rfxd8 20. e6 fxe6 $11) 16... Rc8 17. Bh6 (17. Rb1 $6 Qb6 $15) (17. e6 a5 18. exf7+ Rxf7 19. Qxb7 Nd6 $132) (17. Bf4 b5 $1 18. Qxb5 Bxa1 19. Rxd8 Rfxd8 20. e6 fxe6 $11) 17... Bxa1 18. Rxd8 Rfxd8 19. e6 Ne5 (19... Nd6 $5 {is about to transpose}) 20. exf7+ Nxf7 21. Be3 Bd4 22. Qxe7 Re8 23. Qa3 b6 $11 {Carlsen - Nepomniachtchi, Saint Louis, 2019.}) (14. Qxf3 {is the least pretending of all the options, Black can confidently go for} Bxd4 15. Rb1 (15. Bh6 Bxa1 16. Rxd8 Rfxd8 $15) (15. Bg5 Qd6 $15) (15. Bb2 e5 $11) 15... e5 16. Bh6 Re8 17. a4 a5 (17... Re6 $5 18. a5 Na4 19. Rxb7 Rf6 20. Qa3 Nc3 21. Qxc3 Bxc3 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Bg5 Rdd6 24. Bxf6 Rxf6 25. Rxa7 Bd4 $11) 18. Bb5 (18. Rb5 Rc8) 18... Re6 $11) 14... e6 $1 ({Black would like to snatch the central pawn, but the c4-square is under control, so after} 14... Bxd4 $6 15. Bg5 $1 {will be unpleasant to meet, e. g.} Bxa1 16. Rxd8 Rfxd8 17. Qxe7 Rd7 18. Qa3 $16) 15. Be3 (15. Qb4 {[%cal Ga2a4]} Qh4 16. a4 Rac8 17. a5 (17. Be3 Bh6 $1 {The most consistent continuation, which initiates fight for the complex of dark squares on the kingside and is supporting the activated queen:} 18. Bxh6 (18. a5 Bxe3 19. fxe3 Nd7 20. Qd2 (20. Qxb7 $2 Rc2 $17) (20. Rac1 Rxc1 21. Rxc1 Qg5+ 22. Kf2 Qh4+ $11) 20... Rfd8 $11) 18... Qxh6 19. a5 Qg5+ (19... Nd7 $6 20. Qe7) 20. Kf1 Nd7 21. Qb5 ({a wise decision to trade the queens, the careless} 21. Qxb7 $6 Nf6 22. Qb5 Qh4 $17 {may cost dearly}) 21... Qxb5 (21... Qf4 $5 22. Qxd7 Rc2 23. Ke1 Qxh2 24. Rd2 Qh1+ 25. Bf1 Rxd2 26. Kxd2 Qxf3 $44) 22. Bxb5 Rfd8 {and Black has little to worry about, e. g.} 23. Rac1 Rxc1 24. Rxc1 Nf6 25. Rc4 $11 (25. Rc7 a6)) 17... Rc2 $1 18. Rd2 (18. axb6 Rxe2 19. Rf1 axb6 20. Qc4 Rxe4 21. fxe4 Qg4+ $11) 18... Rxc1+ 19. Rxc1 Bh6 20. axb6 (20. Rcc2 $143 Bf4) 20... Qg5+ 21. Kf1 Qxd2 22. Qxd2 Bxd2 23. Rd1 Ba5 24. bxa7 Bb6 25. d5 (25. Ra1 Ra8 $11) 25... exd5 26. Rxd5 Bxa7 27. Rd7 Rc8 {Restricting ?e2 is much more important than the last queenside pawn, Black has enough compensation after} 28. Rxb7 Bb8 $11) 15... Qh4 16. Qb3 (16. Rab1 {is another way to exert pressure on the b7-pawn -} Rfd8 17. Qc3 Bf8 $11) (16. Rac1 Bh6 (16... Rfd8 $5) 17. Rc7 {is also worth of attention, Black can rely on} Bxe3 18. Qxe3 (18. fxe3 {allows the sharper reply} Rac8 $1 19. Rxc8 Rxc8 20. Rc1 Rxc1+ 21. Qxc1 Qg5+ 22. Kf2 Qh4+ $11) 18... Rab8 19. Kg2 Rfc8 $11) 16... Bh6 {The most active reaction and a reminder to White's monarch that its residence is not entirely safe.} ({Black can postpone this idea for a while in favour of} 16... Rac8 17. a4 Rc7 {, defending the queenside and mobilizing the rooks at first -} 18. a5 (18. Rac1 Rfc8) 18... Nd7 19. Rac1 Rfc8 20. Rxc7 Rxc7 21. Kg2 b6 $11) 17. a4 (17. Bxh6 {might be a bit more precise move order, anyway, Black is in fine shape after} Qxh6 18. Qe3 (18. a4 {will be answered analogously to the leading text -} Qg5+ 19. Kh1 Rac8 20. a5 Nd7 $11 21. Qxb7 $140 $6 Rc2 $36) 18... Qh4 $11) 17... Rac8 18. a5 Bxe3 $146 ({A small refinement of the course} 18... Nd7 19. Rac1 Nf6 20. Bxh6 Qxh6 21. Qe3 Qh4 $11 {in Moiseenko - Lorparizangeneh, Doha, 2015.}) 19. fxe3 ({If} 19. Qxe3 {, then} Nc4 $11 {is the idea.}) 19... Nd7 20. Rac1 ({The greedy} 20. Qxb7 $2 {can bring only trouble for White after the natural} Rc2 {, especially in the view of the exposed penultimate rank.}) 20... Rxc1 21. Rxc1 Qg5+ {with a logical repetition after} 22. Kf2 Qh4+ $11 *

