{[%evp 0,46,13,13,25,4,42,37,50,50,50,49,49,49,51,51,51,24,4,10,95,79,48,63,44,27,27,28,26,48,59,57,56,8,13,-2,39,45,62,7,5,4,73,36,12,-3,31,24,27]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Be3 c5 8. Rc1 {The most straightforward execution of the plan with speedy mobilizing the queenside and "cleaning" the long diagonal by this.} (8. Qd2 {is rarely of independant significance -} Qa5 9. Rb1 $5 (9. Rc1 {just transposes}) ({for} 9. Nf3 {see the next Chapter, here we are going to concentrate on move orders, in which the usual development of Ng1 is delayed or it appears on the e2-square}) 9... b6 $1 10. Bb5+ ({a clever idea to deprive Black of a possibility like} 10. Rb5 Qa4 11. Rb3 Ba6 {with an easy development -} 12. Bxa6 Qxa6 13. Nf3 Nc6 $11) (10. Nf3 O-O) 10... Bd7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Ne2 Nc6 13. h4 h5 $11) 8... Qa5 9. Qd2 cxd4 $5 ({This capture makes sense before} 9... O-O 10. Nf3 {, thus limiting White's options.}) 10. cxd4 Qxd2+ 11. Bxd2 ({More frequent guest in the tournament practice is} 11. Kxd2 O-O {and now:} 12. Nf3 (12. Bb5 Nc6 ({Black may prefer} 12... Rd8 {with X-ray against ?d2, then} 13. Ne2 Nc6 {transposes}) 13. Ne2 (13. Nf3 {- 12.î ..f3}) 13... Rd8 14. Bxc6 ({practically forced, for} 14. Rhd1 {is inviting} Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Ke1 e5 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. Rc7 Be6 19. Rxb7 Bxa2 $11) 14... bxc6 15. f3 (15. Rxc6 $6 Bb7 $15 {[%csl Re4]}) (15. Rhd1 f5 $11) 15... f5 $5 $146 ({Black is rarely paying attention at the hanging c-pawn, it is much more important to open the position for the pair of bishops and the typical break in the text is contributing to that. Besides, there is also} 15... e5 16. Rxc6 exd4 17. Bg5 Re8 $11) 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Rhd1 ({quite characteristic is the exemplary} 17. Rxc6 Rab8 $132 {[%cal Gb8b2]}) 17... Be6 $11) (12. Bd3 Nc6 ({without a pin along the d-file the textmove must be probably preferred to} 12... Rd8) 13. Ne2 (13. d5 $6 Nb4 $1 14. Bb1 Rd8 $15 {[%cal Ge7e6]}) 13... Rd8 {The pressure on the central pawn is increasing, forcing White to the awkward} 14. Rc4 ({once again the advance} 14. d5 $6 {is not well-timed because of} Ne5 {[%cal Ge7e6]} 15. Rhd1 e6 $15) {and now the tricky} 14... Be6 $5 (14... f5 {is fully playable, but Black is trying to reinforce this blow}) 15. Ra4 (15. d5 Ne5 16. Rc7 (16. Rb4 $6 f5 17. f3 Bf7 18. Rxb7 fxe4 19. fxe4 e6 $17 {[%csl Rd2,Rd3][%cal Gd8d2]}) 16... Nxd3 17. Kxd3 f5 $1 18. f3 (18. Nf4 Bd7 19. Rxb7 e5 20. Ne2 fxe4+ 21. Kxe4 Bf5+ 22. Kf3 e4+ 23. Kg3 Rxd5 $11) {and here comes the instructive piece sacrifice} 18... Bxd5 $1 19. exd5 Rxd5+ 20. Kc2 Re5 21. Rc3 {with} Ra5 $1 {as the culmination of Black's operation -} 22. a4 (22. Rd3 $6 Rxa2+ 23. Kd1 a5 $15) 22... Bxc3 (22... Rxa4 $2 23. Kb3 $16) 23. Nxc3 Rd8 24. Rb1 Rd7 $11) 15... Bd7 (15... f5 $11) 16. Rb1 Ne5 17. Bb5 Nc6 {[%cal Ga7a6]} (17... a6 18. Bxd7 Rxd7 $11) 18. Bd3 Ne5 $11 {may result in a repetition.}) (12. Bc4 Rd8 13. Ne2 Nc6 14. Rhd1 (14. d5 $6 Na5 15. Bd3 e6 16. Nf4 exd5 17. Nxd5 Be6 $15) (14. Bd5 $6 Bd7 {[%cal Ge7e6]}) 14... Bxd4 $1 (14... Nxd4 $6 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Kc2 e5 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. Kd3 $14 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gc4d5]}) 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 {transposes to Kramnik - Svidler, in which the knight has been developed on f3, see below}) (12. d5 e6 $132) (12. Rc7 $6 Rd8 $36 {[%csl Rd4]}) 12... Nc6 {is a very important tabiya:} 13. d5 (13. Bb5 Rd8 (13... f5 $5) 14. Bxc6 bxc6 {is very similar to the previously analyzed line with Ng1-e2:} 15. Rc5 (15. Rhd1 f5 16. exf5 Bxf5 ({the slightly unusual} 16... gxf5 $5 {, based on} 17. Rxc6 Bb7 {is a good shot at equality}) 17. Rxc6 Be4 18. Rc7 {So far Shipov - Hasangatin, Podolsk, 1992; now strong enough is} Bd5 19. a3 e5 $11) 15... f5 $1 {is once again the key to counterplay -} 16. Rhc1 (16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Ne5 Be4 18. f3 Bd5 19. Nxc6 Bxc6 20. Rxc6 Bxd4 $14) (16. Ne5 {is revealing a major difference to the set-up with Ne2, so is with} f4 $5 17. Bxf4 Rxd4+ 18. Ke3 Ra4 $11) (16. e5 $6 Be6 17. Ra1 Bd5 $15 {[%csl Gd5]}) 16... fxe4 (16... Be6) 17. Ne5 Bd7 18. R1c2 (18. R1c4 Be6) (18. Rb1 Be8 19. Rb7 a5 $11) 18... Be8 19. Nxc6 Bxc6 20. Rxc6 Bxd4 21. Bxd4 Rxd4+ 22. Ke3 Ra4 $11) (13. Bc4 Rd8 14. Rhd1 Bxd4 $1 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 {transposes to an aforementioned line, Black is fully equalizing, e. g.} 16. Ke1 ({or} 16. Kc3 Nc6) 16... Nc6 17. Rxd8+ Nxd8 18. Bd5 (18. Bg5 Kf8) 18... Nc6 19. Bxc6 bxc6 20. Rxc6 Bb7 21. Rc4 a6 22. f3 Rc8 23. Rb4 Bc6 24. Bd2 Kf8 25. Rb6 Bb5 $11 {Kramnik - Svidler, Nizhnij Novgorod, 2013}) 13... Rd8 14. Ke1 ({here too} 14. Bd3 $2 {is ill-timed because of} Nb4 {[%cal Ge7e6] and White is already in trouble -} 15. Bd4 e6 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 $17 {Werle - Wagner, Muelheim, 2019}) (14. Kc2 Na5 15. Bg5 ({noteworthy, the plan with} 15. Bf4 b6 16. Bc7 Rf8 17. Kb1 {was met by the cool} Nb7 $5 {, improving the knight without any fear of} 18. Ne5 Nc5 19. Nc6 $140 Re8 20. f3 Bb7 21. Bg3 a6 22. Rc2 e6 $132 {Bartsch - Wittal, freechess.de, 2014}) (15. Bd2 $6 b6 $17 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Ge7e6]}) 15... Bd7 $5 ({the practice has shown that Black is not obliged to defend with} 15... Kf8) 16. Bxe7 (16. Kb1 f6 17. Bd2 b6 {proved rock-solid in two email games:} 18. Bb4 (18. Rc7 e6 19. Nd4 (19. dxe6 Bxe6 $11 {Helmer - Payzansky, FICGS email, 2011}) 19... exd5 20. exd5 Bf8 21. Bxa5 bxa5 22. Nc6 Rac8 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. Bb5 Rc7 $11) 18... e6 19. Nd4 exd5 20. exd5 Bh6 21. Re1 Bf8 22. Bxf8 Kxf8 23. Ba6 Re8 $11 {Wojnar - Holroyd, ICCF email, 2014}) 16... Rdc8+ 17. Kb1 Rxc1+ 18. Kxc1 Re8 19. Bb4 (19. d6 a6 {[%cal Ga5c6]} 20. Bd3 Nc6 21. Bg5 h6 22. Be3 Nb4 23. Bb1 Rc8+ 24. Kd1 Ba4+ 25. Ke2 Bb5+ $11) 19... Nc4 $1 {This brilliant tactical resource is justifying Black's idea.} 20. Bxc4 (20. Bd3 $2 Rc8 21. Kb1 Bb5 $17 {can only spell danger for White}) 20... Rxe4 21. Nd2 Bh6 22. Kb2 Bxd2 23. Bxd2 Rxc4 24. Be3 b6 $11 {and soon a draw was signed in Radjabov - Mamedyarov, Zug, 2013.}) 14... Nb4 $1 ({being faced with a choice, Black has no reason to refrain from the more active jump than} 14... Na5) 15. Bd2 (15. a3 $6 {is imprecise in the view of the spectacular} Na2 $1 16. Rc4 (16. Rc7 $2 Nc3 17. Bd3 f5 18. Bc4 Kf8 19. Ng5 Be5 $1 20. Nxh7+ Ke8 $19) (16. Rc2 $2 Nc3 17. Bd3 f5 $17) 16... Nc3 $5 $146 (16... b5 17. Rc7 Rd7 {looks sufficient, but the knight is very alive and kicking}) 17. Bd2 (17. Kd2 Nxe4+ $5 ({Yet another surprise. Black, if he wishes so, can calm down and go for} 17... Nb1+ 18. Kc1 Nc3 19. Kd2 Nb1+ $11) 18. Rxe4 Rxd5+ 19. Ke1 (19. Ke2 Bd7 {[%cal Gd7b5]}) 19... Bc3+ 20. Bd2 Bf5 21. Re3 Bxd2+ 22. Nxd2 Rad8 23. Ne4 Rd1+ 24. Ke2 Be6 25. f4 R8d4 $44) 17... Nb1 $1 18. Bb4 Rd7 $5 ({very complicated is} 18... a5 19. Bxe7 Rd7 20. d6 Nxa3 21. Rc7 a4 {[%csl Ga4]} 22. Bd3 b5 23. Kd2 $13) 19. a4 a5 $5 {Now this is connected with amazing consequent pawn sacrifices for penetrating in White's camp.} 20. Bxa5 b5 $5 (20... f5 $5) 21. axb5 Rda7 22. Bb4 Ra1 23. Ke2 Na3 $1 {The glorious story of this knight is ending with trading for the currently most valuable enemy piece.} 24. Bxa3 R1xa3 25. Nd4 Bd7 $44 26. b6 (26. Nc6 $6 Rb3 27. Rc2 e6 $15 {[%csl Re2]}) 26... Rb8 27. Nc2 Rb3 28. Kd2 Bh6+ 29. Ne3 Rb2+ 30. Rc2 R2xb6 31. Bd3 Ba4 32. Rc4 Rb2+ 33. Bc2 Bxc2 34. Rxc2 R8b4 $11 {[%csl Re4]}) 15... Na6 16. Bg5 {is the most challenging move, if not the only one. Black can once again react in a diametrically opposite manner:} (16. Bxa6 bxa6 17. Ba5 ({the central pawns will be under fire after} 17. Bb4 Rd7 18. Nd2 f5 19. f3 Rb7 $11 {as well}) 17... Rd7 $11 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) (16. Bb5 Bd7 (16... e6 $5) 17. a4 Rac8 18. Rxc8 Bxc8 $11) (16. Bd3 e6 $132) {the restrained} 16... Kf8 {is probably the best -} (16... Nb4 $5 $146 17. Bxe7 ({after} 17. Bc4 b5 $5 18. Bxb5 Nxa2 19. Rc7 Nc3 20. Bxe7 Nxb5 21. Bxd8 Nxc7 22. Bxc7 f5 {seems to offer enough counterchances, for instance} 23. e5 Bb7 24. d6 Bxf3 25. gxf3 Bxe5 26. Ke2 Kf7 $11) (17. Bd2 $11 {is a silent draw offer}) 17... Nxa2 18. Rc2 Rd7 19. Ba3 Nc3 20. Bd3 b5 21. Bb4 Nxe4 22. Bxe4 Bb7 $44) 17. Bxa6 bxa6 18. Ke2 Rb8 {is more or less similar to the aforementioned brief line for 16.?:a6, the verdict seems to be the same after} 19. Rc7 (19. Rc2 Bd7 $11) 19... Rb2+ (19... f6 20. Bd2 Bd7 21. Rhc1 f5 $132) 20. Ke3 Bd7 21. Rd1 (21. Rhc1 f6 22. e5 Ke8 $1 ({avoiding the crafty trap} 22... fxg5 $2 23. Rxd7 $1) 23. exf6 exf6 24. Bf4 Rb5 25. Rd1 Ra5 $11) (21. e5 f6) 21... f6 22. Bf4 Rxa2 23. Nd4 g5 24. Bg3 f5 $1 {The ultimate shot at equality.} 25. exf5 (25. Nxf5 {leads to a very unusual perpetual after} Ra3+ 26. Ke2 Bb5+ 27. Kd2 Ra2+) 25... Bxd4+ 26. Rxd4 Bxf5 27. d6 Ra3+ 28. Ke2 Ra2+ $11) 11... O-O (11... Nc6 $143 $6 12. d5 Nd4 13. Ne2 $14) 12. Nf3 (12. d5 e6 $11) 12... Bg4 $1 {An important nuance in the process of obtaining counterplay.} (12... Nc6 $6 {is once again obviously premature -} 13. d5 $14) (12... e6 {locks the own bishop and allows} 13. Bb5 $1 Nc6 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. O-O $14) 13. Be3 ({In reply to} 13. Ne5 {Black should not hesitate over} Bxe5 14. dxe5 Nc6 15. f4 Rfd8 $132) (13. Rc7 {is demanding, though time-consuming - after} Bxf3 14. gxf3 Bxd4 15. Rxe7 (15. Rxb7 Nc6 $11) 15... Nc6 $1 16. Rxb7 Rab8 {Black has excellent compensation, for instance} 17. Rb3 Bc5 $5 $44 {[%cal Gc6d4]}) ({After} 13. d5 Nd7 {Black is getting all his pieces into play and is therefore absolutely fine -} 14. h3 (14. Be2 Rfc8 $11) (14. Ng5 Nb6 15. h3 Bd7 16. Bd3 h6 17. Nf3 e6 $132 {Maghsoodloo - Grigoryan, Rasht, 2016}) 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 Rfc8 16. Bb5 Rxc1+ 17. Bxc1 Rc8 18. O-O (18. Be3 Ne5) 18... Ne5 19. f4 Nc4 20. e5 Nb6 {[%csl Rd5]} 21. d6 exd6 22. exd6 Rc5 $1 23. a4 a6 24. Be2 (24. Be3 Rd5) 24... Rd5 (24... Nxa4 25. Rd1 $13 {[%csl Gd6]}) 25. Rd1 (25. a5 Nd7) 25... Rxd1+ 26. Bxd1 Kf8 $11) 13... Nc6 (13... Rd8 {is possible, inviting White to transpose to 13.Ne5 from above.}) 14. d5 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nd4 16. Bh3 {An inspired attempt to get full control over the key c-file. Otherwise Black seems in order:} (16. Be2 Rac8 17. Kd2 e6 $11) (16. f4 Rfc8 17. Bd3 (17. Bh3 Rxc1+ 18. Bxc1 Rd8 $11 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) 17... Rxc1+ 18. Bxc1 Rd8 19. Be3 e6 20. dxe6 Nxe6 $11) (16. Bg2 Rac8 17. Kd2 e6 18. f4 exd5 19. exd5 Nf5 $11 {[%cal Gf5d6]}) (16. Rc7 {should be carefully studied in comparison to the textmove - there are tiny, but important differences in the relevant move orders. At this particular moment Black should prefer} e6 $1 (16... Nxf3+ $2 17. Ke2 Nd4+ 18. Kd3 $18) 17. dxe6 (17. Rxb7 exd5 18. exd5 Nxf3+ 19. Ke2 Nd4+ 20. Kd3 Nf5 $11) 17... Nxe6 18. Rxb7 Rfb8 19. Rxb8+ (19. Rb3 Nd4 $11) 19... Rxb8 20. Bd3 Bc3+ 21. Kf1 Bd4 (21... Be5 22. Bc4 Nf4 23. Bb3 a5 $11) 22. Kg2 Rb2 $11) 16... f5 $1 {The standard blow at the central pawns.} ({The offered pawn is poisonous, as witnessed by} 16... Nxf3+ $2 17. Ke2 Nd4+ 18. Kd3 Nb5 19. Bd7 Nd6 20. f4 {[%cal Ge4e5]} Rfd8 21. Rc7 $18) ({White will be enjoying a lasting edge after the less accurate} 16... e6 17. dxe6 Nxe6 18. Bxe6 fxe6 19. Ke2 $14) 17. Kf1 ({In reply to} 17. Rc7 {Black can already continue with} Nxf3+ 18. Ke2 Nd4+ 19. Kd3 (19. Bxd4 Bxd4 20. exf5 {took place in Carlsen - Ding Liren chess24.com INT, 2020, when} Rad8 $11 {could shorten the game}) 19... fxe4+ 20. Kxe4 Nf5 21. Bxf5 Rxf5 22. Rxe7 Bf8 {and the position is roughly equal -} 23. Rd7 (23. Rxb7 Re8+ 24. Kd4 Bg7+ 25. Kc4 Rc8+ 26. Kb3 Rxd5 $11) 23... Rf7 24. Rxf7 Kxf7 25. Rc1 Bd6 $11) 17... Rac8 $5 $146 {A logical idea to fight for the c-file.} ({The more forcing} 17... Nxf3 18. exf5 gxf5 19. Rc7 Rad8 {is the alternative, which must result in a draw as well.}) 18. Kg2 Bf6 19. Rxc8 (19. Rhd1 Nb5 20. exf5 g5 $1 21. f4 gxf4 22. Bxf4 Rfd8 $11) (19. a4 Ne2 20. Rxc8 Rxc8 $11) 19... Rxc8 20. f4 Nc2 $1 {The ultimate equalizer.} 21. Bxa7 (21. e5 $6 Nxe3+ 22. fxe3 Bh4 $15 {[%cal Gc8c2]}) (21. exf5 Nxe3+ 22. fxe3 g5 $11) 21... Ra8 22. Rc1 Rxa7 23. Rxc2 fxe4 $11 *

