 queenside are getting more visible by each move, the crisis of the game is near:} 15. Nf3 (15. Be2 Qa5 $1 16. O-O (16. Qb2 Na6 17. O-O Nc5 18. Rfc1 Na4 $11) (16. Qd5 Bc6 17. Qc5 {does not achieve anything special -} e6 18. O-O Nd7 19. Qe7 a6 $11) 16... Bxd4 $1 17. Bxd4 ({a truly amazing line is starting with} 17. Qd5 {, when after} Bxe3 18. fxe3 e6 19. Qxa8 Bc6 {the blow} 20. Rxb5 $3 Qxd2 {, based on} 21. Qxa7 Nd7 $1 22. Qa6 $1 {is receiving respectable reply in} Qxe3+ 23. Kh1 Qxe2 $3 {with approximate equality after} 24. Qxc8+ Nf8 25. Rbb1 Bxe4 26. Rg1 Bxb1 27. Rxb1 Qxa2 $11) 17... Qxd2 18. Bd3 Nc6 19. Be3 Qa5 20. Qd5 Be6 21. Qxb5 Qxb5 22. Bxb5 Bxa2 23. Rbc1 Nb4 24. Rxc8+ Rxc8 25. Bxa7 $11) 15... Qa5+ $5 (15... Qb7 {looks safe, as confirmed by} 16. Bxb5 Bxb5 17. Qxb5 Qxe4 18. O-O {in Nguyen - Grandelius, Douglas, 2019, for instance} Nc6 19. Rbc1 a5 $11) 16. Bd2 Qb6 17. Bxb5 Bxd4 18. Qd3 $5 ({a stunning attempt to win material; completely different is the course after} 18. Nxd4 Qxd4 19. Qd3 Qxd3 20. Bxd3 Be6 21. a3 Nd7 $11) 18... Bxf2+ 19. Ke2 Be6 $1 20. Rhc1 (20. Be8 Qd6) 20... Bc5 $1 21. Bh6 Nc6 $3 {A magnificient idea, giving a rise of an unbelievable saving operation.} 22. Bxc6 Qxc6 23. Rb5 Qd6 $1 24. Qc3 Bd4 $1 25. Qxd4 Qxd4 26. Nxd4 Rxc1 27. Bxc1 (27. Nxe6 $2 Rc2+) 27... Bc4+ 28. Kd1 Bxb5 29. Nxb5 a6 30. Nc7 Ra7 31. Nd5 f5 $11) (9. Bd2 {is too humble, so Black has a reason to pretend for more with} Bg4 $5 ({avoiding for any case} 9... O-O 10. h3 $5) 10. Be2 (10. Qb3 $6 O-O $1) (10. Rb1 Qxa2 11. Ra1 (11. Rxb7 O-O $132) 11... Qb2 ({Black should reconcile himself with the repetition, since after} 11... Qe6 $2 12. Qa4+ {the check is rather unpleasant to meet}) 12. Rb1 $11) 10... O-O 11. O-O Rd8 {with amounting pressure on the d4-pawn:} 12. Rb1 (12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Qa6 15. d5 Bxa1 16. Qxa1 Nd7 17. e5 e6 18. Bh6 Nf8 19. d6 Nd7 $15 {[%cal Ga8c8]}) (12. Qc2 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Qa6 15. e5 Nc6 16. Bxc6 Qxc6 17. Qxc6 bxc6 18. Be3 c5 19. dxc5 Bxe5 $11) (12. d5 $5 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Qxc3 14. Rc1 Qa3 15. Ng5 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 h6 17. Nf3 Nd7 18. Rfe1 ({Black has just prepared to meet} 18. e5 {with} Nf8 $132) 18... Rac8 19. Qd2 Kg7 20. Rc3 Qb4 21. Qc2 b5 22. Rb3 Qa4 23. Qb2+ Nf6 24. Ra3 {1/2-1/2 P. Rice - B. Benko, ICCF email, 2019.} Qb4 $11) 12... Bxf3 $5 $146 (12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Qxa2 14. Ra1 Qb2 15. Rb1 $11) 13. Bxf3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Qxa2 15. d5 Nd7 16. Rxb7 Rab8 17. Rxb8 Rxb8 $132 {[%csl Ga7][%cal Gg7a1]}) 9... Nc6 10. Rb1 (10. Rc1 cxd4 11. cxd4 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 O-O {transposes to the previous Chapter.}) 10... a6 11. Rc1 (11. Bc4 O-O $11) 11... cxd4 $1 {A necessary intermezzo.} ({Analogously to the immediate 10.Rc1, Black should avoid} 11... O-O $6 12. d5 $16) (11... f5 {is a common counterstrike, but it comes usually at a later stage.}) 12. cxd4 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 e6 $1 (13... f5 14. e5 $14) 14. Bd3 (14. d5 exd5 15. exd5 {is not that dangerous -} Ne5 ({there is also} 15... Ne7 16. Bc4 Bf5 $1 17. Nd4 O-O $11) 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. g3 Bf5 18. Bd3 Bxd3 19. Kxd3 Kd7 $11 {Sarana - Sjugirov, Khanty-Mansiysk, 2018}) (14. h4 O-O 15. h5 {can hardly be approved, Black is at least equal after} Rd8) (14. Bc4 O-O 15. Rhd1 Bd7 {and White is at important crossroads:} 16. Ke2 (16. d5 exd5 17. Bxd5 {is more pretending after the opponent's castling, but Black has the incredible strike} Nb4 $1 18. Bc5 ({or} 18. Bxb7 Rad8 19. Ke1 Bb5 $132 20. Rxd8 $140 Rxd8 21. Rc8 Rxc8 22. Bxc8 a5 $11 {[%cal Gb4a2]}) 18... Nxd5 19. Bxf8 Bxf8 20. exd5 Ba4 $1 21. Rg1 Rd8 $1 {, winning the d-pawn with huge compensation for the exchange -} 22. Ke3 Rxd5 23. Rc8 Kg7 {[%csl Ga4,Gf8]} 24. Rgc1 Bd6 $44) 16... Na5 17. Bd3 {and the logical sequence} Ba4 (17... Nc6 $11) (17... Rfc8 $11) 18. Re1 (18. Bc2 Bb5+ $11) 18... Rfc8 {seems to equalize without efforts, for instance} 19. Rxc8+ Rxc8 20. Rb1 b5 $11) 14... O-O 15. h4 (15. Rc5 Bd7 $5 ({The textmove is preparing the c8-square for the rook instead of} 15... Rd8 {Also, Black has a concrete idea of how to make use of the extra a7-a6 move.}) 16. Rb1 b5 {Here it is! Now the vulnerable b6-square is covered.} 17. Ne5 (17. Rbc1 Rfc8 18. Ke2 Bf8 19. R5c3 Nb4 $11) 17... Nxe5 18. dxe5 Rfc8 19. f4 Bf8 20. Rxc8 Rxc8 21. g4 {White has seized space on the kingside and may consider the march of the f4-pawn, but the queenside majority is also a factor -} Be7 $11) (15. e5 Rd8 16. h4 h6 {tranposes to the main line.}) (15. Rc4 {can be answered with the same} Bd7 16. Rhc1 (16. Rb1 b5 $11) (16. h4 h6) 16... Rfd8 ({or} 16... Rfc8 {, even though ?g7-f8 is not going to attack a piece at once}) 17. Ke2 (17. Bg5 $6 f6 18. Be3 Bf8 $15 {[%cal Gc6b4]}) 17... h6 $11) 15... h6 {After both h-pawns have moved, the same White's options must be examined.} 16. e5 (16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 {is more critical here. Black can probably agree to trade pawns, but to eliminate the central one, while searching counterplay with} Bd7 $1 18. f4 $140 Bb5 {looks even more convincing -} 19. Bb6 Rfc8 $11) (16. Rc5 Bd7 17. Rb1 b5 18. e5 (18. h5 g5) 18... Rac8 $146 ({the familiar} 18... Rfc8 19. Be4 $140 Ra7 {is the alternative}) 19. Be4 (19. Nh2 Ne7 20. Rbc1 Rxc5 21. Rxc5 Bc6 22. f3 Bd5 23. Ng4 (23. a3 h5) 23... Bxa2 24. Nxh6+ Bxh6 25. Bxh6 Rc8 $11) 19... Na5 20. Rbc1 Nc4+ 21. Ke2 Rxc5 22. dxc5 Rc8 23. Bb7 Rc7 24. Bxa6 Nxe3 25. fxe3 (25. Kxe3 Bf8) 25... Bf8 26. Nd4 Rxc5 27. Rxc5 Bxc5 28. Nxb5 ({better than} 28. Bxb5 Bxd4 29. Bxd7 Bxe5 $11 {, though Black must easily hold even without a pawn due to the opposite-coloured bishops}) 28... Bc6 29. Kf2 Be7 30. g3 Bxb5 31. Bxb5 Bb4 32. a4 Bc3 $11) ({more about} 16. Rc4 Bd7 {can be seen in the next note.}) 16... Rd8 17. h5 (17. Rc4 Bd7 18. Be4 (18. Rb1 b5) 18... Na5 $5 (18... Rac8 19. Rhc1 Bf8 $11 {[%cal Gc6b4] Le - Ding Liren, Chess.com INT, 2019}) 19. Rc7 Rac8 20. Rhc1 Bc6 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 $11) 17... g5 18. Nxg5 Nxd4 $1 ({But not} 18... hxg5 $2 19. h6 $18) 19. Ne4 {The tournament practice has also seen:} (19. Nf3 Nxf3+ 20. gxf3 Bxe5 21. Rhg1+ (21. Bxh6 Bd7) 21... Kh8 22. Bxh6 Bd7 23. f4 Bb2 (23... Bb5 $5) 24. Rc7 Rac8 25. Bg5 Rxc7 26. Bxd8 Rc5 27. Be7 Rd5 28. Ke2 Bd4 $11 {with a draw in Grigoryev - Gonzalez Rabago, ICCF email, 2017}) ({The attractive idea for} 19. Bh7+ Kf8 20. Nxf7 Kxf7 21. Rc7+ Kf8 22. Rd1 $1 {received an adequate reaction -} Nf5+ $1 23. Ke2 Rxd1 24. Bc5+ Ke8 25. Kxd1 Bd7 26. Bg6+ Kd8 27. Bb6 Rc8 {with a very entertaining perpetual after} 28. Rc6+ Ke7 29. Bc5+ Kd8 30. Bb6+ Ke7 {in Andreikin - Grischuk, Belgrade, 2022.}) 19... Bxe5 20. Bxh6 f5 $1 21. Nc5 (21. Nc3 $6 Bd7 $15) 21... b6 $5 ({A logical idea to chase Nc5 and mobilize the queenside rather than} 21... Nc6) 22. Bg5 $146 ({Black has successfully passed the practical test -} 22. Na4 Bb7 23. Nxb6 (23. Bg5 $143 Bxg2 $1 {and Black is at least equal}) 23... Kh7 24. Be3 Rab8 25. Nc4 Bf6 26. f3 Rd7 $44 27. Bxd4 Rxd4 28. Rb1 e5 29. Rb6 Bd5 30. Rxb8 Bxc4 31. Rb7+ Kh8 32. Rb8+ {1/2-1/2 Granz - Walton, ICCF email, 2019} Kh7 $11) (22. Nb3 Bb7 23. f4 Nxb3+ 24. axb3 Be4 25. Rh3 Bg7 26. Bxg7 Kxg7 $11) (22. f4 Bf6 $11) 22... Rd6 23. f4 (23. Na4 Bd7 {may transpose to 24.Na4, see below.}) 23... Bh8 $1 24. Nb3 (24. Be7 Rc6 25. Nb3 Bb7 $11) (24. Na4 Bd7 25. Be7 Rc6 26. Rxc6 Bxc6 27. Nxb6 Ra7 28. Bg5 Bxg2 $11) 24... Nxb3+ (24... Nc6 $5 {[%cal Gc6b4] is a plausible alternative and possibly a more ambitious one.}) 25. axb3 Bb7 $11 *

