{[%evp 0,52,15,16,20,-4,37,37,51,51,51,51,43,51,51,51,51,25,21,17,36,37,2,11,30,8,30,34,21,-23,40,19,59,39,49,44,25,3,68,21,-7,-28,-3,-26,-83,-82,-116,-5,-10,-34,-20,5,1,1,19]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8. h3 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gc8g4]} ({After} 8. Be2 Nc6 {Black has maximum pressure on the central pawns:} 9. d5 $5 {is inviting} (9. Be3 Bg4 {[%csl Rd4]} 10. e5 cxd4 11. cxd4 Qa5+ {with excellent play -} 12. Bd2 ({if} 12. Qd2 {, then Black can exchange the queens and transfer the bishop to a dominating position on the d5-square}) 12... Qc7 $5 ({Black, if he wishes so, can just repeat -} 12... Qd8 13. Be3 Qa5+ $11) ({or} 12... Qa3 13. Bc1 $11 {, but he has every reason to rely on the queenside majority in the long run}) 13. Be3 (13. O-O Rd8) 13... Rd8 14. Qa4 O-O 15. O-O Qd7 $11) (9. Rb1 {Had Black castled on the last move, then the textmove would have been an invitation to the well-trodden numerous branches of the Gambit variation. Here it contains another type of pawn sacrifice -} cxd4 10. cxd4 Nxd4 {(the most consistent move, going for the a2-pawn does not make sense here, as Nc6 is exposed to d4-d5)} 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Bb5+ Kf8 (12... Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7 15. Rxb7+ Ke6 $11 {looks pretty safe either}) 13. O-O Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Be6 15. Bd7 b6 16. Bc6 Rc8 17. Bb7 Re8 18. Bc6 Rc8 $11) 9... Bxc3+ 10. Bd2 Bxa1 11. Qxa1 {This exchange sacrifice is quite common in the Gruefeld, in many of them Black has concerns about the king and a knight on the edge (the a5-square) of the board, while here this problem can be solved at once -} Nd4 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Qxd4 O-O (13... f6 $5 14. O-O Qb6) 14. O-O ({it is important that} 14. Bh6 $6 {is effectively met by} Qa5+ 15. Kf1 f6 16. Bxf8 Kxf8 $15) 14... Qb6 (14... Re8 $13 {[%cal Ge7e5]}) 15. Qc3 (15. Qa1 f6 16. Rb1 Qc7 17. Rc1 Qd6 $132 18. Qd4 Bd7 19. Bb4 Qf4 {took place in Paessler - Kappes, ICCF email, 2008. Objectively speaking, White has no reason to refrain from the repetition} 20. Bd2 Qd6 $11) (15. Qe5 $5 Qf6 (15... Qd6 {may just transpose, though, apart from exchanging the queens, White has a retreat to the b2-square with an idea for ?d2-b4}) (15... Re8 16. Bc3 f6 17. Qf4 Bd7 18. e5 Rac8 19. Ba1 $44) 16. Qc7 Qd6 {leaves White in search of compensation.} 17. Qxd6 (17. Rc1 Bd7 18. Bf4 Qf6 $132) 17... exd6 18. Bf4 Bd7 $5 {[%cal Gf8c8]} ({as usual, it is highly recommended to activate the pieces rather than} 18... Rd8 19. f3 $44 {[%csl Rd6]}) 19. Rb1 $1 (19. Bxd6 Rfc8 $15 {[%cal Gc8c2]}) 19... b6 (19... b5 $5) 20. Bxd6 Rfc8 21. a3 $44 g5 $5 22. f3 f6 $11) 15... Bd7 (15... Qf6 16. e5 Qh4 17. f4 $44 {[%csl Rh4]}) 16. Bh6 (16. Be3 Qd6) 16... f6 17. Bxf8 Rc8 18. Qf3 (18. Qd2 Kxf8 $11) 18... Kxf8 19. e5 Kg7 20. exf6+ exf6 (20... Qxf6 $11) 21. h3 Qd6 $11 {Grischuk - Nepomniachtchi, Moscow, 2019, Black has nothing to worry about.}) 8... Nc6 9. Be3 ({Here} 9. d5 Bxc3+ 10. Bd2 Bxa1 11. Qxa1 Nd4 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Qxd4 O-O {favours Black, because of the idle h2-h3 he is practically a tempo up and has every reason to play for the full point -} 14. Bd3 Qb6 15. Qa1 f6 16. O-O Bd7 $132) 9... Qa5 $5 ({It would be interesting to see practical examples with} 9... O-O 10. Be2 cxd4 11. cxd4 f5 $5 (11... Qa5+ {transposes})) 10. Bd2 (10. Qd2 cxd4 11. cxd4 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 {may also transpose to various lines, there is also the original} f5 $5 $146 (12... O-O {[%cal Gf8d8]}) 13. Bd3 (13. e5 Be6 $15 {[%cal Ge6d5,Ga8d8]}) (13. Bb5 O-O) 13... Rf8 {[%cal Gf5f4]} 14. exf5 (14. d5 Ne5) 14... Bxf5 15. Ke2 Rd8 $11) 10... O-O 11. Be2 (11. d5 Ne5 12. Nxe5 (12. c4 $6 Qc7 13. Rb1 f5 $1 $15) 12... Bxe5 {is double-edged -} 13. Qb3 (13. c4 Qa3) (13. Qc2 b5 $5 14. Be2 e6 15. c4 b4 $132) 13... Rb8 $5 (13... Bd7 14. c4 Qc7 15. Rb1 e6 16. Bd3 exd5 17. exd5 Rfe8 18. O-O b6 $11) 14. c4 Qc7 15. Rb1 e6 16. Bd3 exd5 17. exd5 Bd4 18. O-O Bxh3 19. Bxg6 {So far T. Williams - M. Horvat, ICCF email, 2012, when} hxg6 20. Qxh3 b5 $1 21. Rxb5 (21. cxb5 Rbd8) 21... Rxb5 22. cxb5 Qe5 23. Qf3 Rd8 $11 {is fine for Black.}) 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Qa3 $1 ({Instead,} 12... Qd8 $6 {allows White to reinforce the center with} 13. Bc3 e6 14. Qd2 $16) 13. d5 (13. Bc1 $6 Qd6) (13. Be3 Qc3+ $11) 13... Ne5 $1 (13... Nd4 $143 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. O-O $14 {, the bishop will feel safer on the e5-square.}) 14. O-O (14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. O-O Bd7 $1 ({The best, Black should better hold his temper and reject} 15... Bxh3 16. Rb1 Bd7 17. Rxb7 Rfd8 18. Qc2 $14) ({or} 15... Bxa1 $6 16. Qxa1 f6 17. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gd2b4]}) 16. Rb1 (16. Bh6 Rfc8) 16... Qxa2 17. Rxb7 Ba4 18. Qe1 Rfb8 $132 {A. Onischuk - L. Ftacnik, Germany, 2000}) (14. Rb1 Nxf3+ (14... Qxa2 15. O-O {may transpose to the featured move order, as well as to the leading line}) 15. Bxf3 Qxa2 16. O-O {is very similar to the Gambit variation, Black can once again put his hopes on the passed pawns, namely} a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5a4]} (16... Re8 {is defending the e7-pawn in advance}) (16... Be5 {is likely to transpose already on the next move}) 17. Qc1 (17. Bf4 {from Carlsen - Nepomniachtchi, chess24.com INT, 2020, with the intention for e4-e5, is best answered by} Qc4 $1 18. Qd2 a4 $132) ({Black has combined the ideas} 17. Re1 a4 18. Bb4 Re8 {in Wojtaszek - Giri, chess24.com INT, 2022, his chances are not worse even after the strongest} 19. Qc1 $1 {due to the tactical operation} a3 20. Be2 Qxb1 21. Qxb1 a2 22. Qb3 a1=Q 23. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 24. Kh2 Be5+ 25. g3 Bd7 $11) 17... Be5 18. Bd1 ({essential is} 18. Bc3 Qxb1 $1 19. Qxb1 Bxc3 20. Be2 a4 $44) 18... a4 19. Be2 b5 $1 20. Bxb5 Ba6 21. Bxa6 Rxa6 22. Bc3 Bd6 $11 {Acevedo Villalba - Petrolo, email, 2017.}) 14... Bd7 $1 {The familiar instructive reply.} ({In fact, here Black can accept the challenge -} 14... Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Bxa1 16. Qxa1 f6 17. Rb1 $44 {[%cal Gd2b4]} Rf7 $1 {[%csl Re7]} 18. Bb4 (18. Rb3 Qd6) 18... Qd3 19. Rb3 Qc4 $13) 15. Rb1 (15. Nxe5 Bxe5 {- 14. N:e5}) (15. Nd4 Rfc8 {deprives White of any ambitious plans with f2-f4 -} 16. Qb3 Qxb3 17. axb3 Nd3 18. Bxd3 Bxd4 $11 {A. Hoffman - P. Ricardi, Pinamar, 2001.}) 15... Ba4 $5 (15... Qxa2 {is a sound alternative -} 16. Rxb7 Rfb8 (16... Ba4 $143 $6 17. Qe1 Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 {and} Rfb8 {is a signal for} 19. Rxb8+ Rxb8 20. Bf4 Rb5 21. e5 $36) 17. Qb1 ({here} 17. Rxb8+ Rxb8 18. Bf4 {is answered with} Qb2 $1 {, insisting on the control over the e5-square by delaying the exchange of the knights till a proper moment}) 17... Qxb1 18. Rfxb1 Nxf3+ 19. gxf3 (19. Bxf3 Be5 $11) 19... Be5 20. f4 Bd6 21. e5 (21. Kg2 f6 $11) 21... Bf5 $1 {The key to sufficient counterplay!} 22. exd6 {offers an attractive exchange sacrifice, but Black is able to hold after} (22. R1b3 Rxb7 23. Rxb7 Rb8 24. Rxa7 Bc5 25. Rc7 Rb1+ 26. Kg2 Bb6 27. Rb7 (27. Rxe7 $2 Rb2 $19) (27. Rc6 Rb3 $11 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gf5h3]}) 27... Rb2 {A pair of bishops will be exchanged, Black has enough compensation in either cases:} 28. Be3 (28. Bf3 Rxd2 29. Rxb6 Rd3 $1 30. Rb8+ Kg7 31. Rb7 Kf8 32. h4 Bh3+ $1 {The ultimate equalizer.} 33. Kxh3 (33. Kg3 h5) 33... Rxf3+ 34. Kg4 Rxf2 $11) 28... Rxe2 29. Rxb6 Be4+ 30. Kf1 Bd3 31. Kg1 Re1+ 32. Kh2 Rb1 $11) 22... Bxb1 23. Rxb8+ (23. Rxe7 Rb6 24. Bc4 Bf5 25. d7 Rf8 26. Ba5 Rd6 27. d8=Q Rfxd8 28. Bxd8 Rxd8 29. Rxa7 Bxh3 $11) 23... Rxb8 24. dxe7 f5 (24... f6 $5 {is an equivalent alternative}) 25. d6 Kf7 {Grischuk - Preotu, Chess.com INT, 2022, a sample line is} 26. Be3 Be4 27. Bxa7 Rb2 28. Bc4+ Ke8 29. Bd4 Rb4 30. Be2 Bc6 31. Be5 Rb1+ 32. Kh2 Rh1+ 33. Kg3 Rg1+ 34. Kh4 h6 $11) 16. Qe1 (16. Qc1 Qxa2 17. Nxe5 (17. Rxb7 {is premature, when} Rac8 {reveals a drawback of 16.?c1 -} 18. Qe1 Rc2 $132) 17... Bxe5 18. Bc4 Qc2 19. Qxc2 Bxc2 20. Rxb7 Bd6 $11) 16... Nd3 17. Bxd3 ({Very interesting is} 17. Bb4 Nxb4 18. Qxb4 Qxb4 19. Rxb4 Bc2 $1 {The only, but sufficient response - Black's counterplay against the central pawns is coming just in time.} 20. e5 (20. Rc1 Rac8) 20... Rfc8 21. Rxb7 Be4 $11) 17... Qxd3 18. Bg5 (18. Rxb7 Bb5 {is definitely not encouraging for White, a sample line goes on with} 19. Nh2 Ba6 20. Rxe7 Rfe8 21. Rxe8+ Rxe8 $132) (18. Bf4 a5 $5 {takes the b4-square off the queen, Black seems to be in order -} 19. Be5 (19. Rxb7 $6 {fails to the resumed threat} Bb5) 19... f6 $132) 18... Rfe8 $1 19. Qb4 (19. Rxb7 Bb5 20. Bxe7 {is a more critical try, Black should hold after} Qxf1+ 21. Qxf1 Bxf1 22. Kxf1 Bf8 23. Bxf8 Kxf8 24. Ng5 (24. e5 Reb8 $11) 24... h6 25. Nxf7 Rab8 26. Rxa7 Rxe4 27. g3 Re7 28. Rxe7 Kxe7 29. Nxh6 Kd6 $11 {with a relatively easy draw after the elimination of the last queenside pawns.}) (19. Qa5 $143 b5) 19... b5 20. Rbc1 (20. Bxe7 a5 21. Qd6 b4 $132) 20... a5 21. Qc5 Qxe4 22. Rfe1 Qf5 23. g4 Qc8 24. Rxe7 Qxc5 25. Rxe8+ Rxe8 26. Rxc5 Bf8 $11 *

