ur than a weakness in his camp:} 12. Nxe5 (12. O-O $143 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Bxc3 (13... b5 $5) 14. Be3 c4 $5 $146 (14... Qa5) 15. Rc1 Be5 16. Rxc4 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7b5,Ga8c8,Gd8a5]}) 12... Bxe5 {follows the main line and now:} 13. O-O (13. c4 Qa5+ 14. Bd2 Qxa2 15. O-O b5 (15... Bd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7a4]}) 16. cxb5 axb5 17. Bxb5 Ba6 18. Bxa6 Rxa6 $11) (13. Qd2 Qa5 $5 (13... b5 14. f4 Bc7) (13... e6 14. f4 Bg7 15. d6 e5 $132) 14. Rb3 b5 {Taking advantage of the additional tempo - the threat of c5-c4 forces White to} 15. f4 Bg7 16. c4 Qxd2+ 17. Bxd2 e6 {Black is ready to destroy the center -} 18. Kf2 (18. d6 e5) 18... Re8 19. e5 f6 $11) 13... e6 $5 ({at first glance, there is nothing wrong with} 13... Bxc3 14. Be3 Qa5 15. h4 $5 Rb8 16. h5 Bd7 $13 {Yu Yangyi - Nepomniachtchi, Khanty-Mansiysk, 2019, but undermining the center is a part of Black's plan anyway}) 14. c4 (14. Be3 exd5 15. Qxd5 (15. exd5 $6 Qd6) (15. Bxc5 Bxh2+) 15... Qxd5 16. exd5 b5 $1 17. Bxc5 (17. c4 Bf5 {- 14.c4}) 17... Bf5 $1 {An effective counterstrike with mass exchanges to follow.} 18. Bxf8 (18. Rbc1 Rfc8) (18. Rb3 Rfc8 19. Bb4 Be4 $11) 18... Bxb1 19. Rxb1 (19. Bb4 Bxa2 20. d6 a5 21. Bc5 (21. f4 axb4 22. fxe5 bxc3 23. Bxb5 c2 $11) 21... Be6 22. Bxb5 Rc8 $11) 19... Kxf8 20. c4 bxc4 21. Bxc4 a5 $44 {/=}) 14... b5 $1 15. Be3 (15. cxb5 {should objectively lead to simplifications and equality -} axb5 16. Bxb5 exd5 17. Bc6 Qh4 18. g3 Qxe4 19. Bxa8 Qxb1 20. Bxd5 $11) (15. a4 b4 (15... bxa4 $5 16. Qxa4 Qc7 $13) 16. Be3 Qa5 {with decent chances to take over the initiative, for example} 17. f4 Bc3 18. Bd3 Bd7 19. f5 exf5 20. exf5 Rfe8 $132) 15... exd5 {the same belongs to the queenless endgame after} 16. Qxd5 (16. Bxc5 dxc4 $1 17. Bxf8 Qxd1 18. Rfxd1 Kxf8 $44 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4,Ge5] and it is White, who needs precise moves for keeping the balance -} 19. a4 $1 c3 20. Rd5 Bf4 21. Rc5 $1 b4 $140 22. Rxb4 Bd6 23. Rbc4 Bxc5 24. Rxc5 Bd7 25. Rxc3 Bxa4 26. Ra3 Bc6 27. Rxa6 Rxa6 28. Bxa6 Bxe4 $11) (16. cxd5 Bd6 {is double-edged, the queenside majority should not be underestimated -} 17. f4 (17. a4 Re8) 17... f6 18. Bf3 Re8 19. Rc1 (19. Re1 Bd7 $132) 19... Bf5 $5 (19... Qe7 $13) 20. Bxc5 (20. Qc2 Qe7) 20... Bxe4 21. Bxe4 Rxe4 22. Bxd6 Qxd6 23. Rc6 Qa3 $11) 16... Qxd5 17. cxd5 (17. exd5 Bf5 18. Rbc1 Bd6 19. cxb5 axb5 20. Bxc5 Bxc5 21. Rxc5 Rxa2 22. Bxb5 Ra5 23. Rfc1 Rb8 24. Bf1 Rxc5 25. Rxc5 Rb1 26. Rc3 Rd1 $11 {The forced play has come to an end, Black is regaining the pawn with an absolute draw, Nyback - Cheparinov, Batumi, 2019}) 17... c4 (17... Bd6 $5 18. a4 (18. f4 f6) 18... Re8 19. axb5 Rxe4 $11) 18. f4 (18. a4 Bd7 19. f4 Bd6 20. e5 Ba3 $132) 18... Bd6 19. e5 Ba3 $132) 9... Qa5 10. Rb1 Bxc3+ (10... a6 $143 $6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O $14) 11. Bd2 a6 12. Bxc6+ ({A tricky sequence is} 12. Ba4 Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 b5 14. dxc6 bxa4 15. O-O ({or} 15. Qc1 Be6 {with a probable transposition}) {and Black has to be careful and continue with} 15... Be6 $1 (15... O-O $2 16. Nc4 Qc7 17. Qxa4 $18) 16. Nf3 (16. Qc1 O-O) 16... O-O 17. Qc1 Rfc8 (17... Rac8 18. Rb7 Rc7) 18. h4 (18. Qh6 f6 19. h4 Qd8 {[%cal Gd8f8]} 20. Rfd1 Qf8 21. Qc1 Rxc6 22. Nd4 Rd6 23. Nxe6 Rxe6 $11) 18... Rxc6 19. Qh6 f6 ({safer than} 19... Qd8 20. Ng5 Qd4 21. Qxh7+ Kf8 22. Nxe6+ Rxe6 23. Rbc1 $11) 20. h5 g5 (20... gxh5 21. Rb7 Qd8 22. Ng5 fxg5 23. Qxg5+ Kf7 24. Qxh5+ $11) 21. Nxg5 fxg5 22. Qxg5+ Kf7 23. Qf4+ Ke8 24. Qe5 Kf7 $11) 12... bxc6 13. dxc6 (13. O-O $6 Bxd2 14. Nxd2 O-O 15. Nc4 Qc7 $15) 13... Be6 $1 14. Rc1 (14. Bxc3 Qxc3+ 15. Qd2 {is demanding - Black has to find} Qc4 $1 ({of course not} 15... Qxd2+ $2 16. Kxd2 $16) 16. Ng5 (16. Qe2 Qa4 $17) (16. Qe3 O-O-O $1 $17) 16... Qxa2 ({Black has the luxury to eliminate one more pawn on the queenside rather than going for the advanced one with} 16... Rc8) 17. Rc1 h6 18. Nxe6 Qxe6 19. Qd5 Qxd5 20. exd5 Kd8 21. Rb1 Kc8 22. Kd2 Ra7 23. Rhc1 Kc7 24. Rxc5 e6 $11) (14. Qc2 Bxd2+ 15. Qxd2 Qxa2 (15... Qa4 $11) 16. Rc1 Qxd2+ 17. Kxd2 O-O-O+ 18. Ke3 Kc7 19. Rxc5 Rb8 20. Nd4 Bc8 $11 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gh8