$11) 21. Bxf3 Rd4 22. Qb3+ Kxh7 23. Qf7+ Kh8 24. Qf6+ Kh7 $11) (13. Bc4 Bf6 $132 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gd8c8]}) 13... Bxf3 (13... Bg7) (13... Qc8) 14. gxf3 ({Black is fine after} 14. Bxf3 Bd4 15. a3 Qc8 16. Rb5 Na6 $132 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ga6c7]}) 14... Qc8 15. Qxc3 (15. Rb5 a6 16. Ra5 Qh3+ 17. Kg1 Bd4 $132) 15... Nxa2 $1 16. Qa3 ({slightly better than} 16. Qb2 Nxc1 17. Ba6 Qh3+ 18. Kg1 Qxf3 19. Qxc1 Qg4+ 20. Kf1 Qxe4 21. Rg1 Rab8 $44 {Black has many pawns and rich play for the bishop, so is in the leading text.}) 16... Nxc1 17. Ba6 Rb8 18. Rxb8 Qh3+ 19. Kg1 Rxb8 20. Qxc1 Qxf3 $11) (10. Be3 $6 Nc6 $132 {[%csl Rc3,Rd4]}) 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 (12. gxf3 $6 Bxd4 13. Rxb7 Nc6 $11) 12... Bxd4 (12... Qxd4 $6 13. Be3 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Nc6 15. Rxb7 $16) 13. Rxb7 ({The idea to free the light-squares bishop and open the position by means of} 13. e5 Nc6 14. Bh6 Re8 15. e6 {is logical and deserves to be thoroughly studied. After} fxe6 16. Qb3 (16. Rxb7 Ne5 $11) (16. Qa4 Qd6 17. Rxb7 Ne5 18. Be2 Red8 19. Bg5 Rd7 20. Rxd7 Nxd7 $11 {1/2 Salem - Dubov, Abu Dhabi, 2018}) 16... Qd6 17. Rbd1 (17. Qxb7 $6 Ne5 $15) (17. Bg4 Kh8 18. Bxe6 Be5 $11) (17. Rfe1 Ne5 18. Bxb7 Rab8 19. Be3 Bxe3 20. Qxe3 Red8 21. h3 Nf7 $11) 17... Kh8 18. Be3 (18. Qxb7 Ne5) 18... e5 {the extra pawn is cementing the position of ?d4, thus actively taking part in the fight for the central squares.} 19. Qxb7 Nb4 $1 20. Rd2 (20. Qe4 Rad8 21. Rd2 Nd5 22. Bxd4 Nf6 23. Bxe5 Qxd2 $11) (20. a3 Na6 $11) 20... Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5]} 21. Bxd4 (21. Rc1 Rab8) (21. Rfd1 Rab8 22. Qe4 Nc5 23. Qh4 Rb4 24. Bxd4 exd4 25. Rxd4 Rxd4 26. Rxd4 Qf6 27. Qxf6+ exf6 $11) 21... exd4 22. Rc2 Nb4 23. Rc4 a5 24. a3 Nd3 25. Rd1 Rab8 26. Qe4 Nc5 27. Qxd4+ Qxd4 28. Rcxd4 Rb3 29. Rc4 Nd3 $11) ({From the other side,} 13. Bh6 Bg7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Rxb7 Nc6 {is too dry, including after the most ambitious continuation} 16. Qd5 Qxd5 17. exd5 Nd4 18. Rxe7 Rfe8 19. Rxe8 Rxe8 {and the extra pawn is of little use -} 20. Rd1 Nxf3+ 21. gxf3 Kf6 $11) 13... Nc6 14. Qa4 ({In reply to} 14. Bh6 {Black has also} Qc8 15. Rb5 Rd8 $11 {as an alternative.}) 14... Ne5 $5 {Black has almost equalized after the elimination of the d4-pawn, but, as soon as the opponent has some playing initiative, a precision is required.} (14... Qc8 {is another sensible continuation.}) 15. Be2 (15. Bh6 Re8 {will most probably transpose}) ({Perhaps the most critical line goes on with} 15. Ba3 Qc8 $1 16. Rxe7 Rd8 {and now:} 17. Be2 (17. Rd1 Qc3 $1 18. Be2 Nc6 19. Rb7 Bb6 $132) (17. Rc1 Nxf3+ 18. gxf3 Qh3 19. Qb3 Bxf2+ 20. Kxf2 Qxh2+ 21. Kf1 (21. Ke3 $2 Qd2#) 21... Qh1+ $11) 17... Qc3 $1 {a different try is} 18. Qb3 ({the bishop transfer} 18. Bd1 {[%cal Gd1b3]} Rab8 19. Bb3 {looks tempting, but after the cool} a5 $1 20. h3 (20. Rc1 Qd2) 20... g5 $44 {[%cal Gg5g4] all White's long-distance pieces are suddenly finding themselves isolated at the edge of the board in a total contrast with their excellently centralized counterparts}) 18... Qd2 $1 19. Bc4 Rab8 20. Bxf7+ Kh8 21. Qg3 (21. Rb7 Rxb7 22. Qxb7 Nf3+ $1 23. gxf3 Qg5+ 24. Kh1 Qf4 25. Kg2 (25. Qb3 $2 Be5 $19) 25... Qg5+ $11) 21... Nd3 {Another picturesque situation, the whole Black's army is concentrated on the f2-pawn!} 22. Bb3 (22. h3 Rb1 $1 23. Rxb1 Bxf2+ 24. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 25. Kh1 Qg3 {with a draw at least, for instance} 26. Kg1 Qf2+ $11) ({in case of} 22. Qf3 {the pressure is increased in an instructive manner -} Rb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6f6]} 23. Re6 Qxf2+ 24. Qxf2 Nxf2 25. Rxb6 Nxe4+ 26. Kh1 Bxb6 $11) 22... Rxb3 23. axb3 Nxf2 24. Qf3 Nxe4+ 25. Kh1 Nf2+ $11) 15... Bb6 16. Bh6 (16. Bf4 $6 {does not disturb the opponent in the view of} Qd6 $1 17. g3 (17. Bg3 $6 {Haba - Ranft, Chemnitz, 1997} Rac8 $15) 17... Rab8 18. Rxb8 Rxb8 $11) (16. Ba3 {is vigorously met by} Qd2 $1 17. Qb5 Nc6 $1 18. Bc4 ({quite risky is} 18. Qxc6 Qxe2 19. Bxe7 {because of} Rfc8 {, when White is saving himself by the skin of his teeth, namely} 20. Qf6 Qxe4 21. Bd6 $1 Qxb7 $140 22. Be5 Kf8 23. Bd6+ Kg8 $11) 18... Nd4 (18... Qa5 $5) 19. Qa6 Rfe8 20. Bxe7 $140 Rxe7 21. Rxe7 Nf3+ 22. Kh1 (22. gxf3 Qg5+) 22... Qd6 $1 23. Bxf7+ Kh8 24. gxf3 Qxe7 25. Bd5 Rf8 26. Qe2 Bc7 $44 {[%csl Re5,Rf4,Rh1,Rh2]}) (16. Qb5 Qd6 $1 17. Bb2 (17. Bg5 f6 18. Rd1 Qe6 $11) 17... Nc6 $1 18. Rd1 (18. e5 Qe6) 18... Qe6 19. Qb3 Rad8 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Qxe6 fxe6 $11) (16. Bg5 $5 {provokes} f6 {Nevertheless, Black seems in full order:} 17. Qb3+ (17. Bh6 Re8 18. Bb5 {looks frightening, but Black is able to hold due to several exquisite intricacies -} Qc8 $1 {[%csl Rb7]} 19. Qa6 (19. Qb3+ Kh8) 19... Qe6 $1 {[%cal Gb6f2,Ge6a6]} 20. Kh1 (20. Bxe8 $2 Bxf2+ $1) 20... Reb8 21. Ba4 Qd6 22. Rd1 Qb4 23. Bb3+ Kh8 24. Rxb8+ Rxb8 25. Qe2 Qc3 $11) (17. Be3 Rb8 $1) 17... Kh8 18. Qe6 (18. Be3 Rb8 $1 19. Bxb6 Rxb7 20. Bxd8 Rxb3 21. Bxe7 Rb2 $1 22. Bxf8 Rxe2 23. f3 Kg8 24. Bc5 Rxa2 25. Rb1 g5 26. Rb8+ Kg7 27. Rb7+ Kg6 28. Rxa7 Rc2 $11 {[%csl Gc2,Ge5,Rg1]}) 18... Qd6 $1 19. Qxd6 ({indeed,} 19. Qxe7 Qxe7 20. Rxe7 fxg5 21. Rxe5 Rac8 $11 {[%csl Gb6,Rf2][%cal Gc8c2] should not worry Black at all due to his mighty bishop. His minor pieces are perfectly placed in the text as well}) 19... exd6 20. Bd2 Rab8 21. Rxb8 Rxb8 22. Rd1 Bc5 23. Bc3 Kg7 24. Kf1 g5 25. g3 g4 $11 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5]}) 16... Re8 17. Qa3 (17. Rd1 $6 Qc8 {[%csl Rb7]}) 17... Qd4 $5 ({Black, if he prefers so, can get rid of the annoying rook -} 17... Rb8 18. Rxb8 Qxb8 19. Kh1 f6 20. Qb3+ e6 21. f3 Bc5 22. Qc3 Qb6 23. Rd1 Nf7 24. Bf4 Rd8 $11) 18. Rxe7 Rec8 {Still speculating on trapping the rook.} (18... Qxe4 {is fully possible, after} 19. Qd6 Qf5 {[%csl Rf6]} 20. h3 Rxe7 21. Qxe7 Rd8 22. g4 Qe6 23. Qxe6 fxe6 24. Rb1 {White has only a symbolic edge, for example} Nf7 25. Bc1 Ne5 26. Kg2 Nd3 27. Bg5 Rd4 $11) 19. Be3 (19. Qg3 Nc6 {leads to spectacular perpetual after} 20. Rxf7 Kxf7 21. Qb3+ Ke7 22. Bg5+ Kf8 23. Bh6+ Ke7 $11) 19... Qxe4 20. Ba6 Rc7 21. Rxc7 Bxc7 22. Qc3 Bb6 {The trade of these bishops will further enable Black.} 23. Re1 Bxe3 24. Rxe3 (24. Qxe3 Qxe3 25. Rxe3 Nc6 26. g3 Rd8 $11) 24... Qa4 25. Bf1 Ng4 26. Re2 h5 27. h3 Nh6 $11 *

