{[%evp 0,58,12,12,20,6,33,46,51,41,41,41,41,41,38,51,51,43,29,43,40,10,0,-6,48,70,29,64,33,73,43,51,38,35,31,31,31,33,38,42,42,56,41,42,42,41,52,1,40,-6,25,47,49,44,60,59,80,78,58,74,65]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. Be3 {This set-up has been the most popular one for decades.} (9. d5 $5 Ne5 $5 ({The textmove is connected with an original plan,} 9... Na5 {is the typical route for the knight, aimed at challenging the d5-pawn after} 10. Bd3 O-O {[%cal Ge7e6]}) 10. Bb3 Qa5 $5 {The hidden point - Black will advance to the c4-square and penetrate on the d3-square even at the cost of the same pawn} 11. O-O (11. f4 c4 12. Bc2 Nd3+ 13. Bxd3 cxd3 14. Qxd3 b6 15. O-O Ba6 16. Qf3 Rc8 $11) 11... O-O 12. f4 (12. a4 e6 13. c4 Bd7 $132 {White's b3-bishop leaves a sad impression, the opponents in T. Lins - D. Morozov, ICCF email, 2019, came soon to a peaceful agreement}) 12... c4 13. Bc2 Nd3 14. Bxd3 cxd3 15. Qxd3 b6 {The second bishop is also getting to a nice working diagonal, then the rooks can utilize the c-file for a combined pressure.} 16. Qf3 (16. Rd1 Ba6 17. Qc2 Rac8 $11) 16... f5 $5 ({There is nothing wrong with} 16... Ba6 {, Black has to watch for the opponent's pawn center and the unexpected textmove has to do with it}) 17. e5 Bb7 {[%csl Rd5]} 18. Rd1 Rac8 (18... Rfd8 19. c4 Rac8 20. Qb3 Ba6 21. Bd2 Qc5+ 22. Be3 Qxc4 23. Rd2 $11) 19. a4 Rfd8 20. Ba3 e6 {The central clash has reached its climax. As it often happens in very sharp situations, the game is quickly petering out to a draw -} 21. c4 (21. Bb4 Qa6) 21... Rxc4 22. dxe6 Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Bxf3 24. Rd8+ Bf8 25. Rxf8+ Kg7 26. Rf7+ Kg8 $11) 9... O-O 10. h4 {Such impudent advances are quite trendy nowadays.} ({With this idea in mind, White can also use the common} 10. Rc1 {in advance. As soon as his king is still in the center, it makes sense to go for} cxd4 11. cxd4 Qa5+ 12. Kf1 (12. Bd2 Qh5 $5 ({A curious provocative idea instead of} 12... Qb6 13. Be3 $11 {with probable repetition}) 13. d5 (13. O-O Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Bxd4 16. Bb4 Bf6 $11) ({in reply to} 13. Be3 {Black can give yet another check or play} Qg4 $5 14. O-O $140 Qxe4 15. Qd2 {[%csl Re4]} Qf5 16. d5 Ne5 17. Bb5 Rd8 18. Ng3 Qf6 19. Ne4 Qf5 $11) 13... Ne5 14. O-O Nxc4 15. Rxc4 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd7b5]}) 12... Qa3 $5 ({An unusual idea, but Black is anticipating exactly the intended march of the h-pawn. The possible alternatives are the developing moves} 12... Bd7) ({and} 12... Rd8) 13. Rc3 ({we are still going to see a lot of} 13. h4 Bg4 $132 {[%csl Rd4,Re2,Re3]}) ({another point behind the last Black's move is to disable} 13. Qb3 Qxb3 14. Bxb3 Rd8 15. d5 $140 Na5 16. Ba4 b6 17. f3 Ba6 18. Kf2 Nc4 $132) 13... Qd6 (13... Qb2 $5) 14. h4 Rd8 {[%csl Rd4]} (14... Be6 $5 {is worth considering right now}) 15. h5 (15. Qb3 Ne5 $1 {[%cal Gd6d1]} 16. Bd5 e6 $1 {is suddenly forcing simplifications to equality after} 17. Bg5 $1 (17. dxe5 Bxe5 {[%csl Rc3,Rd5]}) 17... exd5 18. dxe5 Bxe5 19. Bxd8 Bxc3 20. Nxc3 Qxd8 21. Nxd5 Be6 $11) 15... Be6 $1 16. hxg6 (16. d5 {contains a certain risk, as Black can accept the challenge with} Bxc3 17. Nxc3 Rac8 {with every chance to play for the full point after} 18. hxg6 fxg6 $1 $132) 16... hxg6 17. d5 (17. Bf4 $2 Qb4 18. Bxe6 Nxd4 $1 $17) 17... Rac8 $1 ({the h-file is open, so parting with the mighty bishop} 17... Bxc3 $2 {may be fatal for Black -} 18. Nxc3 Rac8 19. Bb3 $16 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gh1h8]}) 18. Bb3 Bg4 19. Rc2 Na5 20. f3 Bd7 21. Bd4 Nxb3 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. axb3 Bb5 24. Qc1 Rxc2 25. Qh6+ Kf6 {1/2-1/2 J. Weber - A. Kristjansson, ICCF email, 2016.} 26. Qh4+ $11) (10. Qd2 Qa5 $11 {[%cal Ga5d2,Gc5d4]}) 10... cxd4 {This is the right move order, as can be seen from} (10... Qa5 11. O-O $5 cxd4 12. cxd4 Qh5 13. f3 Qxh4 14. Qd2 $44 {[%csl Rh4]}) 11. cxd4 Qa5+ ({Curiously, Black has} 11... Na5 $5 12. Bd3 Nc6 {, inviting the opponent to repeat.}) 12. Kf1 (12. Bd2 $6 {has a tactical drawback -} Qh5 {with double attack after} 13. Be3 Qg4 $15 {[%csl Re4,Rg2]}) 12... Qa3 $5 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gc8g4,Ga3e3]} (12... h5) 13. h5 ({White is going to have problems with the central pawns after} 13. Rc1 Bg4 $132 {[%csl Rd4,Re2]}) (13. Qc1 {does not entirely correspond to the aggressive march of the h-pawn -} Qxc1+ 14. Rxc1 Rd8 $1 $146 ({an essential improvement upon} 14... Bd7 15. f3 Rfc8 16. Kf2 $14 {Ovetchkin - Paravyan, Chess.com INT, 2022}) 15. h5 $5 ({an interesting pawn sacrifice, but Black is able to initiate serious counterplay on the queenside after the natural} 15. d5 Ne5 16. Bb3 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ga7a5]}) 15... Nxd4 16. h6 Bf6 17. Nxd4 Bxd4 18. Ke2 Bxe3 19. Kxe3 Kf8 20. Bb3 ({the textmove allows the king to march on to the center and cover all the vulnerable squares, the direct shot at a penetration} 20. Rhd1 {is parried by} Bd7 {, leaving White with compensation, but nothing more -} 21. Bd5 Rab8 $11) 20... Rb8 21. Rc7 Rd7 22. Rhc1 Rxc7 23. Rxc7 Ke8 24. f4 Kd8 $11) ({Here too, the trade of the queens by} 13. Qb3 {should not seriously disturb Black -} Qxb3 14. axb3 (14. Bxb3 Rd8 $132) 14... h5 $5 (14... Rd8) 15. f3 Rd8 $11) ({The prophylactic retreat} 13. Bb3 {is providing Black with large choice -} Rd8 $5 ({worth considering are} 13... h5) (13... Na5) ({or} 13... a5 {at once}) 14. h5 a5 $1 15. hxg6 ({The hunt for the light-squared bishop continues after} 15. Qd2 a4 16. Bc4 (16. Bd5 e6 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. hxg6 fxg6 $132 {[%cal Gc8a6]}) 16... Na5 17. Rc1 Nxc4 18. Rxc4 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6] Analogously to the note for 16.?d5, Black is getting access for his ?c8 to the a6-f1 diagonal with fantastic play -} 19. hxg6 (19. Rc3 Qd6 {will probably transpose}) 19... fxg6 20. Rc3 ({White should feel lucky for any available escape to a draw, such as} 20. Bh6 Ba6 21. Rh3 Bxh6 22. Qxh6 Qxh3 23. Qxh3 Bxc4 24. d5 $1 Bxa2 $140 25. Qe6+ Kf8 26. Qe5 $11) 20... Qd6 21. f3 Ba6 22. Kf2 Bxe2 23. Qxe2 Bxd4 {and White can rely on the drawish tendencies of the ensuing rook ending after} 24. Qc4+ Kg7 25. Qxd4+ Qxd4 26. Bxd4+ Rxd4 27. Rc7 Re8 $11) 15... hxg6 {and White has yet to decide about ?b3:} 16. Nf4 {is attacking the g6-pawn, thus adding fuel into the fire:} (16. Rb1 Bg4 17. f3 a4 18. Bc1 Qd6 19. Bd5 Be6 20. Bf4 Qa3 (20... Qd7 $11) 21. Bc1 Qd6 $11) (16. Qd3 $6 {took place in Livaic - Tabatabaei, Chess.com INT, 2020, when} Be6 $1 $15 {gains in power due to the shaky position of ?d3}) 16... a4 (16... Rxd4 $5 17. Bxd4 Nxd4 18. e5 Qc5 19. Nxg6 Bd7 $11 {Most probably, the readers will not be surprised to learn that Stockfish is assessing this highly unbalanced position as completely equal. Here are several sample lines:} 20. Kg1 (20. Rh4 Nxb3 21. Qxd7 Nxa1 22. Nxe7+ Kf8 23. Ng6+ Kg8 $11) (20. Qh5 Bb5+ 21. Kg1 Ne2+ 22. Kh2 Qxf2 23. Rhf1 Qg3+ 24. Kh1 Qxb3 25. Nxe7+ Kf8 26. Ng6+ Kg8 $11) 20... Bb5 21. Rh4 Ne2+ 22. Kh1 a4 23. Qd5 Qxd5 24. Bxd5 e6 25. Bxb7 Rb8 26. Bc6 fxg6 27. Rb1 Nc3 28. Rxb5 Nxb5 29. Rb4 Bxe5 30. Rxb5 Rxb5 31. Bxb5 a3 $11) 17. Bd5 e6 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Nxg6 (19. e5 c5 $132) 19... fxg6 20. Qg4 Kf7 21. Qf4+ Kg8 22. Qg4 $11) 13... Bg4 {Here is once again the idea behind Black's last move.} 14. hxg6 ({In the era of Alpha Zero its trademark} 14. h6 {should always be considered. The pawn is like a thorn, but Black has a forced simplifying operation -} Bxe2+ 15. Bxe2 Bxd4 $1 16. Bxd4 Rfd8 17. Rh3 Qb4 18. Rb3 Rxd4 19. Rxb4 Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Nxb4 21. Rd7 Kf8 22. a3 Nc2 {(pretty safe is to return the knight in order to exchange the rooks)} 23. Rxb7 Nxa3 $11 {After} 24. Bd3 a6 {is the only, but sufficient move.}) 14... hxg6 15. Rh4 (15. e5 $6 Rfd8 $15 {[%csl Rd4]}) 15... Bxe2+ 16. Bxe2 Rad8 17. d5 (17. Rh3 {does not succeed in defending indirectly the central pawn, for instance, Black has} Qd6 18. d5 $140 Qe5 $1 19. Rb1 Qxe4 20. Bf3 Qc4+ 21. Qe2 Ne5 22. Rxb7 Bf6 $11) 17... e6 18. Rc1 (18. Rb1 Qxa2 $1 19. Rxb7 exd5 20. exd5 Rxd5 21. Qc1 {looks precarious for Black, but here comes} Rfd8 $1 $11 {for preventing 23.Bc4, while the attacked Nc6 is untouchable.}) (18. Bg5 {is a bit annoying, but Black has his arguments:} Rd7 (18... exd5 $5 19. Bxd8 (19. exd5 Ne7 20. Ra4 Qd6 $11) 19... Rxd8 20. Rb1 dxe4 (20... Qe7 {would have been the reply to both 20.e:d5 and 20.Rh3, here it is quite reasonable as well}) 21. Qb3 Qe7 22. Rg4 Re8 $44) 19. Bc4 exd5 ({indeed,} 19... Na5 20. Bb5 Nc6 {is likely to transpose, but Black should better insert the textmove for practical reasons}) 20. exd5 (20. Bxd5 $6 Nb4) 20... Na5 21. Bb5 Nc6 22. Bc4 (22. Rc1 Qd6 $11) 22... Na5 $11) 18... exd5 19. exd5 Qxa2 20. Bc4 (20. Rhc4 Rfe8 $13) 20... Qb2 $1 {The queen is best belonging to the big diagonal.} ({Still, the a3-square is a sort of an alternative one, while} 20... Qa5 $2 {in Triapishko - Darini, Chess.com INT, 2021, could have been punished by} 21. Bd2 $1 $18) 21. Re4 (21. Rb1 Qf6) 21... Na5 22. Be2 Qf6 23. Qd3 b6 24. g3 Nb7 {[%cal Gb7c5,Gb7d6]} 25. Ra4 ({Black is holding after} 25. Rc6 Qf5 $132 {as well.}) 25... Nc5 {The simplest - Black has to blockade the potentially very dangerous d5-pawn and the opposite-coloured bishops will contribute to this.} 26. Bxc5 bxc5 27. Rxc5 Rc8 28. Rxc8 Rxc8 29. Rxa7 Bf8 $11 {[%cal Gf8c5]} *

