{[%evp 0,64,12,20,17,6,46,46,51,41,41,41,49,51,51,51,51,40,40,51,41,53,79,26,50,5,30,17,12,37,46,29,60,59,36,-28,36,34,35,35,36,0,19,17,14,-19,53,31,19,24,54,-28,169,43,10,11,-12,40,2,0,0,0,0,0,0,7,47]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O {The initial position for one of the main White's systems against the Gruenfeld. I would like to focus on the trendy} b6 ({There are tons of theory about the sound alternatives} 10... Na5) (10... Bg4) ({and} 10... Qc7) 11. Rc1 {White has many opportunities to choose from:} ({The materialistic approach} 11. dxc5 {is an acid test for Black's set-up, after} Qc7 {we are at important crossroads:} 12. Nd4 (12. cxb6 axb6 {with ample compensation for the pawn:} 13. Rb1 (13. Bb5 Ne5 14. Bf4 (14. a4 Rd8 $44) 14... Ra3 ({or trading the defender of the light squares with} 14... Ba6 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 16. Qc2 Rfa8 $11) (14... Rd8 $44) 15. Qc1 Qc5 $44 {Timofeev - Nepomniachtchi, Moscow, 2015}) 13... Ne5 14. Bd5 Rb8 15. f4 (15. Bf4 Ba6 $44) {White's burst of initiative on the last moves is of temporary character, time has come to point at his unstable bishops with} 15... Ng4 $5 ({more principled than} 15... Nc4 16. Bd4 Bxd4+ 17. Qxd4 Ba6 18. f5 Ne5 $11 {, even though Black can rely on sufficient counterplay here as well}) 16. Bd4 Bxd4+ 17. cxd4 (17. Qxd4 $6 e6 $15 {[%cal Gc8a6]}) 17... Ne3 18. Qc1 Nxd5 19. exd5 Qd6 $11) (12. Nf4 {is naturally met by} e6 13. Nd3 (13. Qd6 $6 {looks very attractive, but in fact White's difficulties in defending his pawns are just emerging -} Qxd6 14. cxd6 Rd8 15. Rfd1 Na5 16. Bb5 Bd7 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rd6]}) 13... Bb7 14. f3 (14. Bb5 Ne5 $11) (14. Bf4 Qc8 15. Qe2 Ba6 $11) 14... Bxc3 (14... Rfd8 15. Qc2 Na5 $11) 15. Rb1 (15. Rc1 Bd4 $44) (15. cxb6 axb6 16. Rc1 Bg7 $11) 15... Bd4 16. Qe2 Rfd8 17. Rfc1 Qe7 $11) (12. f4 bxc5 13. Rb1 Na5 $5 ({the knight goes to its common location after it has been deprived of the e5-square. The known practical example featured