{the harsh} 13. h4 $6 {will be seriously tested by} e5 $1 14. Bd5 (14. Bg5 Qd7) (14. d5 $6 Na5 15. Bd3 f5 $1 16. Bg5 Qd6 17. c4 $2 f4 $1 $17 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gh7h6]}) 14... Na5 $132) (13. f3 e6 14. Rfd1 {- 13.îRfd1.}) 13... e6 14. Bg5 {should be answered with} ({White has made all the necessary developing moves and} 14. Bh6 {is logical. Black is able to force exchanges with the help of} Bxh6 (14... Qe7 $5) 15. Qxh6 cxd4 16. cxd4 Na5 $1 17. Bd3 Rxc1 18. Rxc1 {and now} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] forces} 19. Qe3 Qd6 20. e5 (20. Bb5 Rc8 21. f3 Ne7 22. Rxc8+ Bxc8 $11) 20... Qe7 21. Be4 ({Black is armoured to meet any attempt to exploit the complex of vulnerable dark squares near the king, as shown by} 21. Ng3 Nb4) ({or} 21. Nf4 Rd8) 21... Nb4 22. a3 Bxe4 23. axb4 Bb7 $11 {Ivanchuk - Grischuk, Beijing, 2014}) (14. f3 {does not look quite useful, Black has the usual play on the queenside -} Na5 15. Bd3 cxd4 16. cxd4 Qd7 17. h4 (17. Qb4 Rxc1 18. Rxc1 Rc8 19. Rxc8+ Qxc8 20. Qc3 Qd7 21. Kf2 Nc6 $11 {1/2-1/2 Forsloef - Gburek, ICCF email, 2012}) (17. Bh6 Bxh6 18. Qxh6 Rxc1 19. Rxc1 Rc8 $11) 17... Rxc1 18. Rxc1 Rc8 19. h5 Rxc1+ 20. Qxc1 Nc6 $11) (14. Bb5 {transposes to the leading line}) 14... Qd7 ({less logical are both} 14... Bf6 15. h4) ({and} 14... Qd6 15. e5) 15. h4 {is another plan against the king's residence, but the main events are currently on the opposite flank -} (15. Bb5 {is harmless in the view of} a6 16. Bxc6 (16. Ba4 b5 17. Bc2 Na5 $132) 16... Bxc6 17. d5 Ba4 18. Re1 Rfe8 19. c4 exd5 20. exd5 b5 $132) (15. e5 {is a common strategy in this type of position, ?g7 is restricted, but Black is ready to initiate the queenside counterplay -} cxd4 16. cxd4 Na5 17. Bd3 Rxc1 18. Rxc1 Rc8 19. Rxc8+ Qxc8 $11) 15... cxd4 16. cxd4 Na5 17. Bd3 Rxc1 18. Rxc1 Nc6 $1 19. Bb5 (19. h5 Nxd4 20. h6 Be5 $132) (19. Be3 Rd8 20. Bb5 a6 21. Bxc6 Bxc6 $11) 19... a6 20. Bxc6 Bxc6 {The next critical position has arisen, White has just saved the d-pawn at the cost of the light-squared bishop.} 21. e5 (21. Ng3 Rc8 22. d5 exd5 23. exd5 Bb7 24. Rxc8+ Qxc8 25. d6 Bc6 26. Bh6 Bxh6 27. Qxh6 Qe6 28. Qd2 b5 $11) (21. h5 $5 {is a very entertaining pawn sacrifice.} Bxe4 22. Qf4 ({or the immediate} 22. h6 Bh8) 22... Bf5 23. h6 Bh8 24. Qh4 ({Black seems to hold after} 24. Rc7 Qd5 {either}) 24... f6 25. Be3 Bd3 26. Nf4 Be4 27. f3 Bb7 28. d5 e5 29. Ne6 Rc8 30. Rxc8+ Qxc8 31. Qa4 Bxd5 32. Nc7 Bf7 $11) 21... Rc8 22. h5 ({All the resources on the kingside are in use, now the push h5-h6 is an option as well. Instead, preceding the textmove with} 22. Bf6 Bf8 23. h5 Bb7 $132 {led to a quick draw in Melkumyan - Ragger, Zagreb, 2019}) 22... Bd5 23. Rxc8+ Qxc8 24. Be7 Qd7 25. Bd6 gxh5 $1 26. Nf4 (26. Ng3 h4 27. Nh5 Qd8 $13) 26... Qb5 27. Qc3 h6 28. Qc8+ Kh7 $11) 12... Rc8 13. Qd2 ({Here White has the possibility for} 13. d5 Ne5 14. c4 {, but the b5-bishop will be a target, e. g.} a6 15. Ba4 e6 16. Nf4 exd5 17. exd5 (17. cxd5 $6 b5 $15) 17... Qd6 $132 {N:c4}) ({Parting with it} 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 {has drawbacks as well, White's center is under fire after the natural} 14. d5 Bd7 15. Qd2 (15. c4 e6 16. Nc3 f5 $1 17. Qd2 Qf6 $132) 15... e6 16. Bg5 (16. c4 exd5 17. cxd5 Qe7 $132) 16... f6 17. Bh6 Bxh6 18. Qxh6 Re8 19. Rfe1 exd5 20. exd5 c4 $132) 13... e6 14. Rfd1 (14. Bg5 {is clever in the present situation, for, compared to aforementioned line, here the queen must avoid the d7-square, after} Qd6 15. e5 {is coming with tempo.} Qd7 {Black, in his turn, will use the location of the b5-bishop for expanding on the queenside:} 16. Rfd1 (16. h4 a6 17. Bxc6 (17. Ba4 b5 18. Bb3 b4 $132) 17... Rxc6 18. h5 cxd4 19. cxd4 Rfc8 20. h6 Bf8 $132) 16... a6 17. Ba4 (17. Bxc6 Qxc6 18. f3 cxd4 19. cxd4 Qd7 $11) 17... b5 18. Bc2 Na5 {with mutual chances:} 19. Ng3 (19. Bf6 cxd4 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. Qg5 (21. cxd4 Qd8) 21... Qd8 22. Qg3 Bd5 $132) 19... Nc4 20. Qf4 Nb2 $1 $132 21. Rd2 ({White's straightforward assault} 21. Re1 cxd4 22. Bf6 {is perfectly countered by} d3 $1 {, when the perpetual after} 23. Bxg7 Kxg7 24. Qf6+ Kg8 25. Nh5 gxh5 26. Qg5+ $11 {is the logical outcome}) 21... Nc4 22. Rdd1 Nb2 $11) 14... cxd4 15. cxd4 Na5 $1 {A typical shot at counterplay in the spirit of the relevant middlegame fight in the Semi-Tarrasch.} 16. Rxc8 (16. Bg5 Qd6 17. f3 Rxc1 18. Rxc1 a6 (18... Rc8) 19. Bd3 Nc6 (19... Qd7) 20. e5 Qd7 21. Be4 Rc8 $11) (16. f3 Rxc1 17. Rxc1 a6 18. Bd3 Nc6 19. Bb1 Qd7 20. h4 Rd8 21. Rd1 {Nepomniachtchi - Vachier Lagrave, Saint Louis, 2022.} Qc7 $5 22. Qc1 Rd7 $11) 16... Qxc8 17. Bg5 (17. Rc1 Qa8 18. f3 Rc8 $11) 17... Ba6 $5 18. Rc1 (18. a4 Bxb5 19. axb5 Qd7 20. Qd3 Rc8 $11) 18... Qb7 19. Bxa6 Qxa6 20. d5 Nc4 $1 21. Qd3 b5 22. Be7 (22. d6 {is neutralized by} f6 $1 23. Bf4 Rd8 {[%csl Rd6]} 24. Qb3 $140 e5 25. Nc3 Qa3 26. Nxb5 Qxb3 27. axb3 Nxd6 28. Nxd6 Rxd6 29. Be3 Rd3 30. Rb1 a6 $11) 22... Ne5 ({Preserving the knight on the nice c4-square does also deserves attention, for example} 22... Rb8 $5 23. d6 Bf8 {, when it is difficult for the pawn to make a new step.}) 23. Qc2 Re8 24. d6 Bf8 25. Qc7 Bxe7 ({The more concrete} 25... Qxa2 26. Nc3 $140 Qa3 27. Nxb5 Qb2 {might be even easier to handle - White won a pawn after} 28. Bxf8 Rxf8 29. Nxa7 {, but} Ra8 30. Rf1 Qd4 {in Tomilin - Palladino, ICCF email, 2021, impressed White so much, that a draw was agreed on the next move. White's knight is restricted to utmost after} 31. Nb5 Qd3 32. Nc3 Ra3 33. Rc1 Rb3 {, so he cannot make any progress.}) 26. dxe7 (26. Qxe7 $5 {is probably more demanding, though, after the precise} Rf8 $1 27. d7 Qa5 28. Ng3 $140 Qd2 {the advanced d-pawn cannot make the last step to glory and needs to be defended -} 29. Rc7 h5 30. Nf1 Qd4 $11) 26... f6 27. Nd4 Kf7 28. h3 (28. Qd8 Nc4) 28... Qb6 {A straightforward decision, albeit far from an obligatory one.} ({Indeed, Black should be patient, as seen in} 28... Rxe7 $2 29. Qd8 $18 {with a rook penetration on the 8th rank to follow}) ({, but} 28... g5 $5 {is fully playable - Black is establishing the excellent location of the knight and will be waiting for the most appropriate moment for getting rid of the stranded e7-pawn.}) 29. Qxb6 axb6 30. Nxb5 Kxe7 ({Black should hold without much trouble after} 30... Rxe7 31. Nd6+ Kg7 32. Rb1 Ra7 33. Rxb6 Rxa2 34. Rb7+ Kf8 35. Rxh7 g5 $11) 31. Rc7+ Nd7 32. Rc6 Rd8 $11 *

