{[%evp 0,11,21,13,27,4,39,31,31,26,26,10,-1,-8]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3 O-O 6. Bg5 {The second most popular move. Nowadays this move is losing its popularity. The idea of the move is to prevent e7-e5 and also provoke h7-h6.} a6 $5 {A bit rare, but a very flexible move. The idea is to prepare c7-c5 and then to be ready after d4-d5 to push b7-b5 immediately.} ({More popular are the moves:} 6... c5) (6... Nc6) (6... Nbd7) 7. Qd2 {The main move. All other options are harmless for Black.} (7. Nge2 {This move is quite typical in Saemish, but in this case, Black is ready for c7-c5 and then the b7-b5 break.} c5 8. d5 ({The endgame does not look very promising for White.} 8. dxc5 dxc5 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. Na4 {[%csl Rb6,Rc5] Trying to use the weak b6 square.} ({In case of} 10. e5 Nfd7 11. Bxe7 ({Or} 11. Nd5 Nc6) 11... Re8 12. Nd5 Nc6 {The position becomes very concrete, but somehow it feels like White is playing with the fire. Next couple of moves are very forced.} 13. Bf6 Ndxe5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Nc7 Nd3+ 16. Kd2 Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d2]} 17. Nxa8 Nf2+ 18. Ke3 {The only way to continue the game.} ({A draw is:} 18. Ke1 Nd3+ $11) 18... Nxh1 19. Nc3 Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2] The position is very sharp, definitely Black has his chances.} 20. Rc1 Bf5 21. Nc7 Nc2+ 22. Rxc2 Bxc2 23. g3 h5 $132 {The position is sharp, but I like Black's chances.}) 10... Nc6 $1 {Black should play very energetically.} 11. Nec3 ({Or} 11. Nb6 Rb8) (11. Nxc5 Nb4 $1) 11... Nd7 12. Nd5 ({In case of} 12. O-O-O {strong is} Bd4 $1 13. Nd5 f6 14. Bf4 Nde5 $132 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5]}) 12... Kf8 {A simple move.} 13. Rd1 Rb8 14. Bf4 Be5 15. Bxe5 Ncxe5 16. Ndb6 Ke8 17. Nxd7 Nxd7 $11 {Black is out of danger.}) 8... b5 9. cxb5 h6 $1 $146 {An important improvement.} 10. Be3 (10. Bd2 {Looks a bit passive.} axb5 11. Nxb5 e6 12. dxe6 Bxe6 $132 {[%cal Gd6d5] Black has an excellent position. d6-d5 is coming next.}) 10... Qa5 11. Qd2 ({Or} 11. Ng3 h5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} 12. h4 e6 $132) 11... axb5 12. Bxh6 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 13. Ng3 c4 $132 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gb5b4] Black has an excellent counterplay.}) (7. a4 {Without c5/ d5 included this move feels strange.} Nc6 $1 8. Nge2 ({If} 8. d5 $6 {then} Nb4 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc7c6] The knight on b4 is untouchable.}) 8... Na5 $1 {[%csl Rc4]} 9. b3 c6 $132 {[%cal Gd8b6,Ge7e5] Black has excellent prospects.}) (7. Bd3 {It is a strange move, connected with Bg5.} Nfd7 $5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg7d4] A nice move in this case.} 8. Nge2 c5 9. d5 Ne5 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black has an excellent play.} 10. a4 {White must prevent b5.} Nbd7 11. b3 ({Worse is:} 11. f4 $6 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 f6 $1 {A very nice and unusual idea. Black already takes the advantage.} 13. Bh4 g5 $1 14. Bg3 ({If} 14. fxg5 $6 {then strong is} Ne5 15. Qg3 f5 $1 $17) 14... gxf4 15. Bxf4 ({Worse is:} 15. Nxf4 $6 Ne5) 15... Ne5 16. Bxe5 fxe5 $132 {The game is still double-edged, but I prefer Black here.}) 11... Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 f5 $132 {[%cal Gd7e5] Black is doing great in the game: Aymard,M (2041)-Alonso Gonzalez,C (2414) ICCF email 2018.}) 7... c5 $1 8. d5 ({After:} 8. Nge2 {good is:} Nc6 9. d5 Ne5 10. Ng3 b5 11. cxb5 c4 $132 {With an excellent play for Black.}) 8... b5 ({Similar is:} 8... Qa5) 9. cxb5 Qa5 10. a4 ({After:} 10. bxa6 {the right move is:} Nxa6 $1 {The point to take with the knight on a6 is that now for White is very difficult to develop his pieces.} ({Worse is:} 10... Bxa6 $6 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. Nge2 Rfb8 13. O-O $14) 11. Bc4 ({Or} 11. Nge2 Nc7 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gc8a6]} 12. Ng3 $6 e6 13. dxe6 Bxe6 $15 {[%cal Gd6d5] Black is better.}) 11... h6 $1 {Not the only, but in my opinion the best move.} 12. Be3 (12. Bxf6 {It is possible but is clear that Black already has a fantastic compensation for the pawn.} Bxf6 13. Nge2 Nc7 ({Also good is:} 13... Nb4 14. O-O Ba6 15. Bxa6 Qxa6 16. Qxh6 Nd3 $44) 14. O-O Ba6 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 16. Qxh6 Rb8 17. Rab1 Nb5 $44 {Black is two pawns down, but the initiative on the queen's side completely compensates that.}) ({White is worse after:} 12. Bxh6 $6 Bxh6 13. Qxh6 Qb4 $15 {[%csl Rb2,Rc4]}) 12... Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7e5] White has no time to take a breath.} 13. Bxh6 {Now there is nothing better.} Bxh6 14. Qxh6 Qb4 15. Nh3 {[%cal Gh3g5] The point. White still can fight.} Qxc4 {Leads to a forced draw.} ({Worse is:} 15... Qxb2 $6 16. Rc1) ({A possible way to continue the game is:} 15... Rd8 $5 {[%cal Gd7f8]} 16. Bxa6 (16. Ng5 $6 Nf8) 16... Bxa6 17. Qd2 Ne5 18. Kf2 Nc4 $132 {with a nice counterplay.}) 16. Ng5 Nf6 17. e5 dxe5 18. Nce4 Qb4+ 19. Kf1 ({Similar is:} 19. Kf2 Nxe4+ 20. fxe4 Qd4+ 21. Kf3 Qd3+ $11) 19... Qc4+ 20. Kg1 Qd4+ $11 {With a perpetual check.}) 10... Nbd7 (10... axb5 $6 {Only helps White to develop.} 11. Bxb5 Ba6 12. Nge2 $16) 11. Nge2 ({The alternatives are:} 11. bxa6 Bxa6 12. Bxa6 Qxa6 13. Nge2 Rfb8 14. O-O Rb4 $44 {[%cal Gd7e5,Ga8b8] Black has an excellent play.}) (11. Ra3 Ne5 12. f4 {White has to play this move, otherwise is not possible to develop his pieces.} Ned7 $132 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ga5b4]}) (11. Nh3 {Another serious option.} Nb6 ({Probably also fine is:} 11... axb5 12. Bxb5 Ba6 $44 {1/2-1/2 (23) Kortig, S-Wynkele,H IECC email 2012}) 12. Nf2 axb5 13. Bxb5 Ba6 14. O-O ({Or} 14. Bxa6 Qxa6 $44 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gf8b8,Gb6c4]}) 14... Bxb5 15. axb5 Qxa1 16. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 17. Nfd1 Rfa8 18. Kf2 {This position occurred in the game: Hoffman, A (2506) -Socko,B (2577) Linares 2003. Now Black had to play} Nh5 $132 {[%cal Gg7d4]}) (11. Nd1 $5 $146 {A new move.} Qxd2+ {I believe the endgame is good enough for Black.} ({Also possible is:} 11... Qc7 $5 {[%cal Ge7e6]}) 12. Kxd2 ({Or} 12. Bxd2 axb5 13. Bxb5 Ba6 14. Bxa6 Rxa6 15. a5 e6 16. dxe6 fxe6 $44 {[%cal Gd6d5] Black has good compensation for the pawn.}) 12... e6 13. Nc3 exd5 14. exd5 Bb7 $132 {[%csl Rd5] Black is doing great.}) 11... Nb6 $1 12. Nc1 ({An awkward move.} 12. Ra2 Bd7 (12... Nc4 13. Qc2) 13. Nc1 e6 {It is important to open the centre.} 14. b3 ({Or} 14. bxa6 c4 $44) 14... axb5 15. dxe6 ({The alternatives are:} 15. axb5 Qb4 $132) (15. Nxb5 exd5 16. Qxa5 Rxa5 17. Bd2 ({The other option is:} 17. Nxd6 c4 18. bxc4 dxe4 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Nxe4 Bd8 $44 {Black is at least not worse.}) 17... Raa8 18. a5 Bxb5 19. Bxb5 Nc8 20. exd5 Ne7 21. Kf2 Nfxd5 $11 {Black is fine.}) 15... b4 $1 {An important intermediate move.} 16. exd7 ({Or} 16. exf7+ Rxf7 17. Nb5 d5 $132) 16... bxc3 17. Qxd6 Nfxd7 18. Bb5 Be5 19. Qd3 Bd4 $44 {[%cal Gd7e5] Black has an excellent game in the game: Granados Ramirez,C-Vertiz Gutierrez,P (2318) ICCF email 2018.}) 12... axb5 ({Another interesting option is:} 12... e6 $5) 13. Bxb5 Bd7 14. Ra3 {Getting ready for Bxb5.} ({Worse is:} 14. Bxd7 $6 Nfxd7 {[%cal Gb6c4,Gd7e5]}) 14... Bxb5 15. axb5 Qb4 {The game is still very sharp, but I believe Black is doing very well. For example:} 16. N1a2 Qd4 17. Qxd4 cxd4 18. Nb1 Nc4 19. Rxa8 ({Or} 19. Ra6 Rab8) 19... Rxa8 20. Nb4 Nxb2 21. O-O h6 $11 {The endgame looks approximately equal.} *

