{[%evp 0,11,21,22,27,4,39,31,26,26,26,-1,18,-9]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3 O-O 6. Nge2 {Very popular move lately, also one of the most interesting to fight for the advantage with White.} c5 {In Saemish, in all lines I prefer the Benoni setup. I believe is better compared to the e5 plans.} 7. d5 e6 8. Ng3 {The main move. This is the point behind 6.Nge2. The idea is to postpone Be3 or Bg5.} (8. Bg5 {This move here, is not very accurate.} h6 9. Be3 exd5 10. cxd5 Nbd7 $1 {The best move order. I believe Black is doing very well here.} 11. Ng3 ({In case of} 11. Qd2 {strong is} Ne5 {[%cal Ge5c4]} 12. Ng3 ({Or} 12. Nc1 $6 Nh5 $15 {[%cal Gd8h4]}) 12... h5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} 13. h4 a6 14. a4 Bd7 15. Be2 b5 $15 {Black is already at least slightly better.}) 11... h5 {[%cal Gh5h4] The typical move after White plays Ng3.} 12. Be2 ({If} 12. Bg5 $6 {then} Qb6 13. Qd2 Nh7 $15 {[%cal Gh5h4]}) 12... h4 13. Nf1 Rb8 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5] Already is a good idea to prepare b7-b5.} ({Also good is the typical move in this situations} 13... Nh7 $132 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) 14. Bg5 {[%csl Rh4]} (14. a4 a6) 14... b5 $1 {Black does not care about the pawn on h4.} 15. Bxh4 b4 16. Nb1 ({Risky is:} 16. Nb5 Qb6 {[%csl Rb5] White must be careful with his knight.} 17. a4 bxa3 18. Nxa3 Qxb2 {Next couple of moves are forced.} 19. Nc4 Qc3+ 20. Nfd2 Nxd5 $1 21. Rc1 Ne3 $1 {A small tactic.} 22. Rxc3 Nxd1 23. Ra3 Nc3 24. Nxd6 Rb2 $132 {Only White can be worse in this endgame.}) 16... Qc7 {[%cal Gf6h5] Prepares Nh5.} 17. Ne3 Nh5 18. Qc2 Nf4 $44 {Black has an excellent play.}) 8... exd5 9. cxd5 {The main position. Here Black has many different plans.} a6 {I prefer to include a6-a4.} ({Other possible moves are:} 9... Nbd7) (9... Na6) (9... h5) 10. a4 {The logical response.} (10. Be2 {Possible, but it looks like Black is doing great.} b5 11. O-O b4 $5 $146 {A nice improvement.} ({Also very possible is:} 11... Nbd7 12. Bg5 h6 13. Be3 h5 14. Qd2 {Topalov,V (2739)-Krysa,L (2491) Caleta 2017. Here Black could continue} Re8 $13 {With a very double-edged position.}) 12. Na4 ({A little worse is:} 12. Nb1 Nbd7 13. Nd2 a5 14. Nc4 Nb6 $15) 12... Re8 {Waiting for White to develop his bishop from c1 and just then to push h7-h5.} 13. Bf4 h5 14. Bg5 Qc7 15. Re1 Nbd7 $132 {[%cal Gf6h7,Gd7e5] Black has a nice play.}) 10... h5 {The most typical move in this pawn structure especially when White's knight is on g3. Here White has two main options. 11.Bg5 and 11. Be2.} 11. Be2 (11. Bg5 $5 Nbd7 (11... Qb6) (11... Qe8) (11... Qc7 {Similar to our main move, but permits 12.Qd2.}) 12. Be2 (12. Qd2 h4 $1 13. Bxh4 (13. Nge2 $6 Ne5 $17 {[%cal Ge5c4,Gh4h3]}) 13... Nxe4 14. Bxd8 Nxd2 15. Bc7 Nxf1 16. Kxf1 Ne5 17. Bxd6 Re8 18. Bxe5 (18. Bxc5 $6 Nd3 19. Ba3 $2 b5 $1 $19) 18... Bxe5 19. Nge4 Bf5 20. a5 Bxe4 (20... Rad8 $11) 21. fxe4 (21. Nxe4 $6 Bxb2 22. Rb1 Bd4 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) 21... Bxc3 22. bxc3 Rxe4 $11) 12... Qc7 13. Qd2 (13. Nf1 $5 Ne5 (13... Nh7 14. Bh4) 14. Qd2 (14. Ne3 Bd7 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (14... Nh7 15. Bh4 Bh6 16. Bf2 h4 17. O-O Qe7 18. Kh1 $14) 15. O-O (15. f4 $6 Neg4 $15) (15. a5 b5 (15... Nh7 $5 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) 16. axb6 Qxb6 17. Qd2 Bb5 18. O-O Rfb8 19. Ra2 Bxe2 20. Qxe2 c4 21. Kh1 Qb3 22. Nc2 Nfd7 23. Nd4 Qb7 $11) 15... b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8 Rxa8 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. f4 Ng4 (19... b4 $5 20. fxe5 Bxe5 21. Nb1 Bxb2 22. Nc4 Bd4+ 23. Kh1 Bb5 $44 {[%csl Gb4,Gd4][%cal Ga8a1]}) 20. Bxg4 hxg4 (20... Bd4 21. Bxd7 Bxe3+ 22. Kh1 Qxd7 23. Qe2 Bd4 24. Nxb5 Bg7 25. Nc3 Qg4 $11 {[%csl Rb2,Re4][%cal Gg7b2]}) 21. e5 dxe5 (21... Bg7 $5) 22. d6 Qd8 23. f5 Bg5 $132) 14... c4 $1 15. Bh6 (15. Ne3 Nfd7 {[%cal Gd7c5]} (15... Rb8 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) 16. f4 (16. O-O Nc5 17. Ra3 Bd7 $132) 16... Nd3+ 17. Bxd3 cxd3 18. O-O (18. Qxd3 $6 Nc5 19. Qc2 Bd4 $1 20. f5 Re8 $15) (18. f5 Bxc3 $5 19. bxc3 Nc5 {[%csl Re4]} 20. Bh6 Re8 21. O-O Nxe4 22. Qxd3 Qxc3 $11) 18... Nc5 19. f5 Re8 $132) 15... Bxh6 16. Qxh6 Bd7 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 17. Ne3 b5 18. O-O (18. f4 Nd3+ 19. Bxd3 Qc5 20. f5 cxd3 21. fxg6 fxg6 22. O-O (22. Qxg6+ $2 Kh8 23. Qh6+ Nh7 $19 {[%csl Re1]}) 22... Rf7 (22... b4 $5 23. Qxg6+ Kh8 24. Ncd1 Nh7 $44) 23. Qxg6+ Rg7 24. Qxf6 Qxe3+ 25. Qf2 (25. Kh1 $6 b4) 25... Qxf2+ 26. Rxf2 Re8 27. axb5 axb5 28. Re1 Rge7 $11 {[%cal Gb5b4]}) 18... Qc5 19. Kh1 Nh7 $132) (13. O-O c4 $1 14. Be3 (14. Qd2 {Transpose to 13.Qd2.}) (14. Kh1 $146 Nh7 15. Bh4 Rb8 $1 (15... g5 16. Bxg5 Nxg5 17. Nxh5 Nh7 18. Nxg7 Kxg7 19. f4 $44) 16. f4 (16. a5 b5 17. axb6 Rxb6 $132) 16... Bf6 $1 (16... b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. e5 $1 dxe5 19. Nge4 $36) 17. Bxf6 Ndxf6 18. e5 (18. Bf3 b5 19. Rc1 Re8 $132 {[%cal Gh5h4]}) 18... dxe5 19. d6 Qc5 20. f5 Kg7 21. Bxh5 (21. Nge4 Qd4) 21... Bd7 22. fxg6 fxg6 23. Bf3 Ng5 $11) 14... Rb8 15. Bd4 (15. a5 b5 16. axb6 Rxb6 $1 17. Qc2 h4 18. Nh1 h3 $132) 15... Ne8 $5 (15... b5 16. axb5 h4 17. Nh1 axb5 18. b4 $1 cxb3 19. Nxb5 Qc2 20. Nxd6 Nxe4 $1 21. Bxg7 Qxd1 22. Rfxd1 Nxd6 23. Bxf8 Kxf8 $44 {[%csl Gb3]}) 16. a5 (16. Bxg7 Nxg7 $132 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gh5h4]}) 16... b5 17. axb6 Rxb6 18. Na4 (18. Bxg7 Nxg7 19. Qc1 Ne5 $11) 18... Rb4 19. Bc3 a5 $1 20. Qd2 Qa7+ 21. Rf2 Nc7 $132) 13... c4 14. O-O (14. Bh6 Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) 14... Rb8 15. Be3 (15. a5 b5 16. axb6 Qxb6+ 17. Be3 Qxb2 18. Bxc4 Qxd2 19. Bxd2 Nc5 $11) (15. Rab1 b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. b4 cxb3 18. Rxb3 b4 (18... Nc5 $5 19. Rxb5 Bd7) 19. Na2 {1-0 (34) Grover,S (2532)-Ootes,L (2326) Wijk aan Zee 2012} Nc5 $1 20. Rxb4 Nb3 $1 21. Qd3 (21. Qe1 Rxb4 22. Nxb4 Qc5+ 23. Kh1 Nh7 24. Bf4 h4 25. Nd3 Qb6 {[%csl Rg3]} 26. Qb4 Qxb4 27. Nxb4 hxg3 28. Bxd6 Rd8 29. Bc7 Rf8 $11) 21... Nc5 22. Qe3 Nh7 23. Bf4 Rxb4 24. Nxb4 h4 25. Nc6 g5 $1 (25... hxg3 $2 26. Qxc5) 26. Bxg5 Nxg5 27. Qxg5 hxg3 28. Ne7+ Kh7 29. Kh1 Qd8 30. Rb1 Bh6 31. Qf6 Bg7 $11) (15. Rac1 b5 16. b4 bxa4 17. Nxa4 Ne5 18. Kh1 (18. f4 Nd3 19. Bxd3 Qa7+ 20. Kh1 cxd3 21. f5 Qd4 $132) 18... Nh7 19. Bh4 Qb7 20. f4 Qxb4 21. Nc3 Nd3 22. Bxd3 cxd3 23. Qxd3 a5 24. Rb1 Ba6 25. Qxa6 Qxc3 $11) 15... h4 16. Nh1 Nc5 17. Bxc4 (17. e5 $5 Nb3 (17... dxe5 18. Bxc4 $14) 18. exf6 Nxd2 19. fxg7 Nxf1 20. gxf8=Q+ Kxf8 21. Bxf1 Qa5 22. Nf2 Bf5 23. Re1 b5 $132) 17... Ncxe4 18. Nxe4 Qxc4 19. Nhf2 Nxd5 (19... Bf5 $5) 20. Bh6 Qb4 21. Qg5 Bf5 22. Qxh4 f6 23. Bc1 Rbe8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (29) Gupta,A (2198)-Opperman,R (2359) ICCF email 2020}) (11. Bd3 {This is a very rare move. Normally in this line, the bishop is better on e2. Now very easily can be attacked after Nbd7-e5.} h4 12. Nge2 Nbd7 13. O-O Rb8 {Prepares b5.} ({Another option is:} 13... Ne5 14. Bc2 Bd7 15. f4 Nc4 $132) 14. Bg5 h3 {The game is now very complicated, but it seems that Black has a good game.} 15. gxh3 Qe8 {[%cal Gf6h7] Prepares Nh7.} ({Black still should be careful. Worse is:} 15... Ne5 $6 16. f4 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Qe8 18. f5 b5 19. axb5 axb5 20. Ng3 $14 {White's position is more pleasant.}) 16. f4 Nh7 17. Bh4 Ndf6 18. f5 b5 $132 {Black has a very serious counterplay.}) 11... Nh7 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gf7f5] Another typical move. Prepares f5 at the right moment.} 12. Be3 ({Of course not} 12. O-O $2 {because of} Bd4+ {with the idea after} 13. Kh1 $140 $2 h4 $19 {[%csl Rg3] Black wins a piece.}) 12... h4 {The most accurate move order.} ({Big theory is:} 12... Nd7 13. O-O h4 14. Nh1 f5) 13. Nf1 Nd7 $1 {Black should be very accurate. I believe this is the best move order.} ({Worse is:} 13... f5 14. exf5 gxf5 (14... Bxf5 $6 15. g4 $1 hxg3 16. hxg3 $16) 15. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Rf5,Rh4] Black's pawn structure can be a problem in a long term.}) 14. Nd2 h3 $1 {A very rare, but in my opinion the best move.} ({Worse is:} 14... Bd4 $6 {in view of} 15. Nc4 Qf6 16. a5 $16 {White has the advantage.}) ({In most of the games in this position Black played:} 14... f5 15. exf5 gxf5 16. O-O Re8 17. Bf2 $14 {I think,this position is very dangerous for Black.}) 15. g3 {The most logical move.} ({A bit strange is:} 15. O-O Bd4 $1 {A nice intermediate move.} 16. Bf2 ({Clearly worse is:} 16. Bxd4 $6 cxd4 17. Ncb1 f5 $17 {Black takes the advantage.}) 16... hxg2 17. Kxg2 Re8 $132 {The game is very sharp, but Black has a good chance here.}) 15... Re8 16. O-O Rb8 $146 {A good improvement. For now, I prefer to prepare b5 and postpone f5.} ({Also an option is:} 16... f5 {Herzog,K (2022)-Belanoff,S (2339) LSS email 2009.} 17. Qc2 $13 {The game is still very sharp and unclear.}) 17. Kh1 {White has plenty of other moves here. For example:} (17. Qc2 {Another logical move.} Ne5 18. Kh1 f5 {Already is time for this typical push.} 19. a5 b5 20. axb6 Rxb6 $132 {The game is very double-edged.}) (17. a5 b5 18. axb6 Nxb6 {This is a rare case where taking with the knight is better than with the rook.} 19. Nb3 ({To an equal game leads.} 19. Bxa6 Bxa6 20. Rxa6 Bxc3 21. bxc3 Nxd5 22. Nc4 Nxe3 23. Nxe3 Qf6 {[%csl Rc3]} 24. Nd5 Qe5 $11 {Black has no problems.}) 19... Nd7 $5 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gb8b2] Keeps the tension.} ({Also an option is:} 19... Bxc3 20. bxc3 Nxd5 21. Qxd5 Be6 22. Qd2 Rxb3 23. Rxa6 Qb8 $13 {[%cal Gb3b2] With an unclear game.}) 20. Ra2 Qc7 $132 {Black has enough counterplay.}) (17. Nc4 $6 {This is not very accurate in view of} Ne5 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. Qd2 Bd7 $15 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black is taking the advantage.}) 17... Ne5 {Provoking f4.} 18. f4 ({The alternatives are:} 18. Qc2 f5 $132) (18. Ra3 f5 $132) 18... Nd7 {[%csl Re4] The game now is very double-edged. The game can continue:} 19. g4 b5 $1 20. axb5 axb5 21. Nxb5 Ndf6 22. Nc3 Rxb2 23. Ra3 Qc7 ({The other options are:} 23... Qe7 $5) (23... Bd7 $5) 24. g5 Rxd2 $1 {Black still must play very dynamic.} 25. Bxd2 Nxe4 26. Nxe4 Rxe4 27. Bf3 Rd4 28. Qe2 Nf8 $44 {Black has more than enough compensation for the exchange down.} *

