{[%evp 0,11,22,24,25,4,39,26,26,26,34,17,9,24]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3 O-O 6. Be3 {The most popular move.} c5 {Once again I prefer the Benoni setup.} 7. d5 {A rare move compare to 7.Nge2 and 7.dxc5. Nowadays the theory proved that Black is doing great here.} e6 8. Qd2 ({After:} 8. Nge2 exd5 9. cxd5 Nbd7 10. Ng3 h5 {Transpose to the previous chapter with 6. Nge2.}) 8... exd5 9. cxd5 a6 {Almost always is good to include this move.} 10. a4 Re8 {The critical position. White has two main options here.} 11. Nge2 {The main move, although I believe Black has zero problems here.} (11. Bd3 $6 {Once again, this is not the optimal square for the bishop.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 12. Nge2 Ne5 13. O-O Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 15. f4 Nf6 $1 $15 {[%csl Re4] I believe Black is already better.}) (11. Be2 $5 {A very awkward, but interesting move. Recently was played by very strong players, including Jan Duda. The idea is to wait for 11...Nbd7 and then to play 12.Nh3 followed by Nf2.} h5 {A good waiting move.} ({Another interesting waiting move is:} 11... Qe7) 12. h4 {[%cal Gg1h3] The most logical response to h5.} ({The alternatives are:} 12. Bd1 $6 {This looks a bit too slow for White.} Nbd7 13. Nge2 Ne5 {[%cal Ge5c4]} 14. b3 {White must prevent Nc4.} b6 $1 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb6b5] Black has time for this slow,but very strong plan.} 15. O-O Rb8 16. Bc2 b5 $15 {Black was better in the game: Yevseev, D (2503)-Sakaev, K (2649) St Petersburg 1999.}) (12. Bh6 {This is another logical move.} Bh8 {Of course the bishop is important.} 13. Bf4 ({Another option is:} 13. Nh3 Bxh3 14. gxh3 {Looks strange for White, but in fact, the game is still very double-edged.} Nbd7 15. O-O Rc8 16. Kh1 c4 $132 {With a very sharp game in the game: Schlenther, M (2517) -Nichols, S (2372) LSS email 2020.}) 13... Nh7 {The solution of the engines.} ({Also possible is:} 13... Qc7 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc5c4]}) 14. h4 Bd4 $1 {[%csl Gd4]} 15. Bd3 Qe7 16. Nge2 Bf6 17. g3 Nd7 $13 {Black was doing fine in the game: Figlio,G (2484)-Sasikiran,K (2553) ICCF email 2020.}) (12. a5 {Here Black is completely fine after:} b5 13. axb6 Qxb6 $132) 12... Qc7 $5 {Another waiting move.} ({The other options are also playable:} 12... Nh7 13. g3 f5 14. Nh3 ({May be interesting is:} 14. Bd3 $5) 14... fxe4 $6 ({Here better was:} 14... Bxc3 $1 15. bxc3 fxe4 16. Nf4 Qe7 $13 {with a very complicated game.}) 15. Nxe4 Bf5 {This position occurred in the game Duda, J (2738)-Naroditsky, D (2623) chess24.com INT 2021. Here White could take advantage after:} 16. Nhf2 $14) (12... Nbd7 {Is also an option.} 13. Nh3 Ne5 14. Nf2 Bd7 15. O-O Rb8 16. a5 b5 17. axb6 Rxb6 $11 {Looks like a very playable position.}) 13. Kf2 {Still waiting for Nbd7.} ({If} 13. Bh6 {then} Bh8) ({Clearly worse is:} 13. Nh3 $6 Bxh3 14. Rxh3 Nbd7 $15 {[%csl Re1] Black is better.}) (13. a5 b5 14. axb6 Qxb6 $132 {Black lost a tempo, but this does not make a big difference.}) (13. g4 {A very direct approach. I believe Black has enough defensive resources.} hxg4 14. Bh6 Qe7 ({Also interesting is:} 14... Re5 $5) 15. h5 Nbd7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. hxg6 fxg6 18. Qh6+ Kg8 $1 {[%cal Ge7g7] The best defense.} 19. Qxg6+ Qg7 20. Qxg7+ Kxg7 21. Kd2 Ne5 $11 {Only White can be worse in this endgame.}) 13... Nbd7 {Black's waiting move are over.} ({A bit worse is:} 13... c4 14. Ra3 Nbd7 15. Nh3 Nc5 16. Ng5 Nb3 17. Qc2 Nd7 18. Rd1 $14) 14. Nh3 Ne5 15. Ng5 Bd7 {[%csl Ge5] With h5-h4 included, the knight on e5 is untouchable, because the plan h3-f4 is no longer available.} 16. Rhc1 {[%cal Gc1c7] The best position of White's rook. Other options are:} (16. a5 b5 17. axb6 Qxb6 18. b4 $5 {A very typical idea. Here the game is very complex and sharp.  The next couple of moves is very forced:} Qxb4 19. Rhb1 Nc4 $1 20. Qc1 Nxe3 21. Rxb4 cxb4 22. Qxe3 bxc3 $44 {[%csl Gc3] Black has a very serious counterplay, but the game is still very concrete.} 23. Qf4 ({The same is:} 23. Qb6 Rab8) 23... Rab8 $1 24. Qxd6 c2 {[%csl Gc2]} 25. Rc1 ({Also a draw is:} 25. e5 Rb1 26. exf6 c1=Q 27. Rxb1 Qxb1 28. Qxd7 Rxe2+ 29. Kxe2 Qc2+ 30. Ke3 Qc3+ $11 {With a perpetual check.}) 25... Ng4+ $1 {Clearly the best move.} 26. fxg4 Bd4+ 27. Ke1 {The rest of the moves are worse for White:} (27. Kg3 $2 {Here Black wins after:} Rb3+ 28. Nf3 Be5+ 29. Qxe5 Rxe5 30. Kf4 Re8 31. Rxc2 Bxg4 $19 {White's position is hopeless.}) (27. Kf1 $6 {Maybe still holds, but very risky for White after:} Rb1 28. Qf4 f6 29. Ne6 Bb2 30. Qc7 $1 {The only way to keep the balance.} Rxc1+ 31. Kf2 Rf1+ 32. Bxf1 c1=Q 33. Qxd7 Bd4+ $1 {The best chance.} 34. Kg3 ({Black wins after:} 34. Nxd4 $2 Rxe4 35. Qd8+ Kf7 $19) 34... Qe3+ 35. Kh2 Qg1+ 36. Kh3 Qh1+ 37. Kg3 Be5+ 38. Kf2 Qxh4+ 39. Ke2 Qxg4+ 40. Kd2 Rxe6 {The only way to continue fighting for a win.} 41. dxe6 Qf4+ 42. Ke2 Qxe4+ 43. Kd1 $15 {[%csl Gd7,Ge6] It is not obvious how Black can win here.}) 27... Bc3+ 28. Kf1 {The only way to play for a win.} (28. Kf2 Bd4+ $11) 28... Rb1 29. Qf4 f6 30. Bd3 $1 fxg5 {Black has also some alternatives.} 31. Qxg5 Rf8+ 32. Kg1 Bd4+ 33. Kh1 Rf6 $1 {The best move. Now a draw is:} 34. Bxc2 Rf1+ 35. Rxf1 Rxf1+ 36. Kh2 Bg1+ 37. Kg3 Bf2+ $11 {With a draw.}) (16. Rhb1 {[%cal Gb2b4] A very logical move. Prepares b4.} Nh7 $1 {[%cal Gg7c3] I think this is the best move, stopping b4 for now.} ({A bit worse for Black is:} 16... b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. Nxb5 Bxb5 19. Bxb5 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 Rb8 21. Be2 $14) 17. a5 Nxg5 18. hxg5 Rab8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 19. Kg1 b5 20. axb6 Rxb6 21. Rxa6 Rxa6 22. Bxa6 c4 $44 {[%csl Ra6] Black has an excellent game for the pawn.}) 16... Qa5 ({Also an option is:} 16... Qd8 $5) 17. Kg1 Nh7 $11 {Looks fine for Black. The game is approximately equal.}) 11... Nbd7 12. Nc1 {A typical way to develop the pieces.} ({A strange, but possible move is.} 12. Nd1 {[%cal Ge2c3]} Nh5 $5 $146 {A good improvement.} ({Also good is:} 12... Ne5 13. Nec3 Bd7 $132 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) 13. Nec3 f5 14. Be2 Qh4+ 15. Bf2 Qf6 $132 {Black has an excellent game.}) ({Another option is:} 12. Ng3 h5 13. Be2 ({Or} 13. h4 Ne5 14. Be2 Nh7 $132 {[%csl Rh4] For White will be very difficult to make a castle.}) 13... h4 14. Nf1 Nh7 {[%cal Gf7f5] Black is doing great here. For example:} 15. Bf2 h3 16. Rg1 ({Worse is:} 16. g4 $6 Ne5 $17) 16... hxg2 17. Rxg2 Ndf6 $132 {According to engines the game is about equal, but in a practical game, definitely will be easier for Black.}) 12... Ne5 13. Be2 Nh5 {[%cal Gf7f5] The plan in this position.} 14. O-O f5 15. f4 {The only way for White to not be worse.} ({In case of:} 15. exf5 $6 Bxf5 16. Re1 ({Or} 16. g4 $2 Nxg4 $1 {A nice tactic. Black is crushing here.} 17. fxg4 Rxe3 $1 18. gxf5 Qg5+ 19. Kh1 Ng3+ $1 20. hxg3 Qxg3 21. Rf3 Rxf3 22. Bxf3 Re8 $1 $19 {[%cal Ge8e1] Black wins.}) 16... b6 $15 {[%cal Ga8a7,Ga7e7] Black is already at least slightly better.}) 15... Ng4 16. Bxg4 fxg4 17. N1e2 b6 {[%cal Ga8a7,Ga7e7] This position occurred in the game: Agafii,V (2259)-Macovei,A (2454) Kishinev 2022. The game here is still balanced but looks very easy game for Black. For example:} 18. Rae1 Ra7 19. Ng3 Nxg3 20. hxg3 Rf7 {I like this move. Black wants to keep the game going. Prevents f5 for now.} ({Equal is:} 20... Bxc3 21. Qxc3 Rxe4 22. f5 $1 {[%cal Ge3h6] White must create problems for Black's king.} Bxf5 23. Bh6 Rxe1 24. Rxe1 a5 25. b3 Rf7 26. Qe3 $11 {For Black is very difficult to make any progress.}) ({Also an option is:} 20... Rae7 21. f5 Rf7 22. Bg5 Bd4+ 23. Kh2 Qd7 24. Ne2 Be5 $13 {With a very sharp game.}) 21. Bf2 h5 $132 {The game is approximately equal, but I like Black's chances.} *

