{[%evp 0,11,22,24,25,4,39,26,26,26,34,17,9,24]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3 O-O 6. Be3 c5 7. Nge2 {The most critical line nowadays. Here usually the game is very sharp and double-edged.} Nc6 {Black must keep the pressure in the centre.} 8. d5 {The other options are:} ({In case of} 8. dxc5 dxc5 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. Bxc5 {Transposes to the next chapter.}) (8. Qd2 {It is a logical move, but not very dangerous for Black.} Qa5 $1 {The best move, Black is getting ready for the actions in the centre.} 9. d5 {It is difficult to keep the centre untouched.} (9. O-O-O {Looks a bit risky for White.} Rb8 $5 {A bit unusual move, but a very decent one.} ({Also good is:} 9... b6 $5) 10. Kb1 b6 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6] Prepares Ba6.} 11. d5 (11. h4 {White's attack is too slow.} Ba6 $132) 11... Ne5 12. Nc1 Bd7 $132 {[%cal Gb6b5,Ga7a6] Black has an excellent play on the queen's side.}) (9. Rd1 {Another waiting move.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] The most logical way to continue. Prepares b5.} ({Also good are:} 9... b6 $5) (9... Rb8 $5) 10. dxc5 {With a6 played, already d5 looks not logical because after Ne5 Black is ready to play b5 immediately.} dxc5 11. Nc1 {[%cal Gc1b3]} ({Or} 11. Nd5 Qxd2+ 12. Rxd2 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Ge7e6] Black has a good game.}) 11... Rd8 12. Nd5 Qxd2+ 13. Rxd2 Nd7 14. Nb3 ({Or} 14. Bg5 Kf8 $11) 14... b6 $11 {[%cal Ge7e6] Black is doing very well. e7-e6 is coming next.}) (9. Rc1 {Looks worse than the rook on d1.} a6 $132 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) 9... Ne5 10. Ng3 {The most normal move.} ({The alternative is:} 10. Nc1 Nfd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6] The best plan here. For White is very difficult to protect the c pawn.} 11. Nb3 Qb4 12. Nb5 Qxd2+ 13. Nxd2 a6 14. Nc3 f5 $132 {Black is at least not worse in the game: Amico, R (2378)-Doric, N (2376) ICCF email 2016.}) 10... Nfd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6] Clearly the best plan. Provokes f4, otherwise is very difficult to protect the c pawn.} 11. f4 ({If} 11. Be2 $2 {White is already lost after:} Nb6 $1 $19 {[%csl Rc4]}) 11... Ng4 12. Bg1 {The is still sharp, but Black is doing well. I White should be more careful.} Ngf6 13. Be2 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 14. Be3 b5 15. O-O Nb6 {[%cal Gb6c4]} 16. f5 $1 {The only way to create counterchances. To more or less a forced draw leads:} Nxc4 17. Bxc4 bxc4 18. fxg6 hxg6 19. Bh6 Bxh6 20. Qxh6 Ng4 $1 21. Qh3 ({Also a draw is:} 21. Qh4 f6 22. Nf5 $1 gxf5 23. Rf3 {[%cal Gf3h3]} Rf7 {Black has enough defensive resources.} 24. Qh5 $1 Bb7 25. Rh3 Rg7 26. exf5 Ne5 27. Re1 Qb6 28. Rxe5 dxe5 29. Qh8+ Kf7 30. Qh5+ Kf8 31. Qh6 $1 $11 {with this move White keeps the balance.}) 21... Ne3 22. Nf5 ({Or} 22. Qh6 Ng4 $11) 22... Nxf1 {Here a draw was agreed in the game: Kibalnichenko, S (2181)-Popov, E (2365) ICCF email 2017.} 23. Qh6 Bxf5 24. exf5 Qb4 25. Rxf1 Qxb2 26. fxg6 fxg6 27. Qxg6+ Kh8 28. Qh6+ $11 {With a perpetual check.}) 8... Ne5 9. Ng3 ({Much worse is:} 9. Nc1 $6 e6 10. Be2 exd5 11. cxd5 Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gd8h4,Gf7f5] White is already in a serious danger.} 12. g4 $1 {The only chance for White.} ({Worse is:} 12. O-O f5 $17) 12... f5 $1 {There is no way back.} 13. gxh5 fxe4 14. f4 Qh4+ 15. Kd2 Rxf4 $1 {Black's attack is quite serious.} 16. Bxf4 ({Probably better is:} 16. Qe1 $5 Qf6 17. Bxf4 Qxf4+ 18. Kd1 Ng4 {[%cal Gg4e3,Gg4f2]} 19. Bxg4 Bxg4+ 20. N1e2 Qe3 21. Qd2 Qh3 $40 {[%cal Ge4e3] White is still under serious attack.}) 16... Qxf4+ 17. Kc2 b5 $1 {Black is attacking with all forces.} 18. Rf1 Qxh2 19. hxg6 hxg6 20. a4 ({Or} 20. Rh1 Qf4 21. Rf1 Qg5 $40) 20... b4 21. Nxe4 Ng4 $1 {[%cal Gg4e3]} 22. Kb1 Ne3 23. Qd2 Nxf1 24. Bxf1 Qe5 $17 {Black was better in the game: Husemann, A (2285)-Anderskewitz, R (2325) LSS email 2019.}) 9... e6 ({Another big line is:} 9... h5 $5 10. Be2 h4 11. Nf1 e6 12. Bg5 $13 {With a very big complications.}) 10. Be2 exd5 11. cxd5 {This is the critical position. Black has different plans.} b5 $5 {A rare move, compared to the main lines. Black sacrifices a pawn but immediately gets the initiative. The game here is very concrete and requires a lot of knowledge from both sides.} ({More popular are:} 11... h5) (11... a6) 12. Nxb5 {I believe the best and the most challenging move for Black.} ({The other possible capture is:} 12. Bxb5 Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b2]} ({The alternative is:} 12... h5 $5) 13. Rb1 {A bit passive, but protects the b pawn for now.} ({After:} 13. O-O {interesting is:} Nfg4 $5 14. fxg4 Nxg4 {[%csl Rb5,Rc3,Re3][%cal Gg7c3,Gb8b5,Gg4e3] All White's pieces are under attack.} 15. Rf3 Bxc3 ({Also fine is:} 15... Nxe3 16. Rxe3 Bd4 17. Nf1 f5 18. exf5 gxf5 19. Kh1 f4 20. Re4 Bxc3 21. bxc3 Rxb5 22. Qd2 Qf6 $11 {With approximately an equal game.}) 16. bxc3 Rxb5 ({Also good is:} 16... Nxe3 17. Rxe3 Rxb5 $11) 17. Bf4 Qe7 $11 {Black has equal chances. Galopoulos, N (2430) -Gaehwiler,G (2260) Plovdiv 2012.}) 13... h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4] Already is time for this typical idea.} 14. O-O h4 15. Nh1 ({Worse is:} 15. Nge2 $6 Nh5 16. Qc1 Qa5 $15 {[%csl Rb5] The problem for White now is that the bishop does not have the e2 square.}) 15... h3 {The easiest way to gain a lot of play.} ({Interesting, but not enough is:} 15... Nxe4 $6 16. fxe4 Ng4 17. Bd2 Be5 18. Nf2 Nxh2 19. Qc1 $14 {White keeps a small advantage.}) ({Unclear is:} 15... Nh5 $5 16. Nf2 g5 17. Qd2 Nf4 18. Bxf4 gxf4 19. Qxf4 f5 $44 {Black definitely has a nice compensation for the pawns.}) 16. g3 ({In case of:} 16. Bg5 hxg2 17. Kxg2 {Black has the nice trick..} Nxd5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gd5e3]}) 16... Qa5 $1 {[%csl Rb5]} 17. Be2 ({Worse is:} 17. a4 $6 c4 {[%csl Rb5]}) 17... Ba6 $1 {[%cal Ge5c4] The threat now is Nc4.} 18. Bxa6 ({Or} 18. Nf2 Nc4 $132 {[%csl Rb2,Re3][%cal Gc4b2,Gc4e3]}) 18... Qxa6 19. Nf2 Nfd7 ({Also possible is:} 19... Nc4 20. Qd3 Rb6 $44) 20. Nxh3 Nc4 $132 {[%csl Rb2,Re3][%cal Gc4b2,Gc4e3] Black has an excellent counterplay on the queenside.}) ({To not take the pawn, looks very strange for White:} 12. O-O $6 b4 13. Nb1 a5 $15 {Black is better.}) ({Or} 12. Qd2 b4 13. Nd1 Re8 14. O-O Qb6 15. Bh6 Bh8 16. Ne3 c4 17. Kh1 Ba6 18. Rac1 Rac8 $132 {Black has an excellent game.}) 12... Rb8 {A very critical moment. White has two serious moves here.} 13. Qd2 {The most played move. White wants to keep the pawn up for now.} ({Another option is to give the pawn back by} 13. O-O $5 a6 14. Nc3 {The most serious try. The rest of the moves are harmless:} (14. Na7 {Looks a bit strange.} Rxb2 ({A bit worse is:} 14... Bd7 15. b3) 15. Nxc8 Qxc8 16. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2c3] White transfers the bishop to c3. The game is still very dynamic, but probably approximately equal.} Re8 17. Bc3 Rb8 18. Nh1 {[%cal Gh1f2] A nice and typical idea.} Bh6 $5 {[%cal Gh6e3] Also a typical plan. Black wants to activate his bishop.} 19. Nf2 Be3 20. Kh1 c4 21. Bd4 {There is nothing better.} Bxd4 22. Qxd4 Rb5 $11 {I believe the game is equal. For example:} 23. f4 Ned7 24. Bxc4 Rb4 25. Rac1 Qc5 26. Qxc5 Nxc5 {[%csl Re4] White cannot keep the pawn up.}) (14. Na3 Rxb2 15. Qc1 ({Or} 15. Rb1 Rxb1 16. Qxb1 {Goryachkina,A (2518)-Lagno,K (2560) St Petersburg 2018.} h5 $132 {Black has a very nice game.}) 15... Rb4 {The rook is very nicely placed here.} 16. Bg5 ({If} 16. h3 {[%cal Gf3f4] then} h5 $1) 16... Re8 17. Kh1 Bd7 18. f4 {White already must do something.} Neg4 19. Bxg4 Bxg4 20. Nc4 Qd7 {Black is completely fine. For example:} 21. a3 Rbb8 22. Qc2 Nh5 $1 23. Nxh5 Bxh5 24. Rae1 f5 $11 {With a good game for Black.}) 14... Rxb2 15. Qc1 (15. h3 {[%cal Gf3f4] A possible move. Prepares f4.} Nfd7 $1 {[%cal Gd8h4]} 16. Qc1 ({Or} 16. f4 Qh4 17. Nh1 Nc4 18. Bxc4 Bxc3 $132 {Black has good counterplay.}) 16... Rb4 {[%cal Ge5c4]} 17. f4 Nc4 18. Bf2 Re8 $132 {Black has a very nice game. After 19.a3 Black is planning to play Rb3.}) 15... Rb4 16. Bh6 c4 {[%cal Gd8b6,Ge5d3] The game is very sharp here. Definitely Black should be a bit careful, but with a few accurate moves, Black can get equal chances.} 17. h3 {[%cal Gf3f4]} ({The alternative is:} 17. Bxg7 Qb6+ 18. Kh1 Kxg7 19. Qd2 h5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} 20. f4 {White has nothing better.} Nd3 21. Bxd3 cxd3 22. h3 ({White is worse after:} 22. Qxd3 $6 h4 23. Nge2