Bd3 Nxf2 21. Bxf5 Rxb5 22. Bxg6 fxg6 23. Qxg6 Re7 {Black must stop Rf7.} 24. Bxf2 Qe8 {Black has full compensation, but the game remains level. For example:} 25. Qxd6 Rxb2 26. Rf1 c4 {[%csl Gc4]} 27. Qc5 c3 {The draw is near.} 28. d6 Ree2 29. Qd5+ Qe6 30. Qxe6+ Rxe6 31. Rd3 Rd2 32. Rxd2 cxd2 33. Rd1 Rxd6 34. Be3 Bc3 $11) 19... a6 $5 {Probably the most concrete continuation.} ({The possible alternatives are:} 19... Bf5) (19... Qa5) 20. Nc3 Bf5 $1 21. Rxf5 Rxb2 $1 {An important intermediate move.} 22. Qxb2 gxf5 23. Rxf5 Nxc3 24. Bh5 Re7 $1 {It is important to start with this move. Now White has many ways to make a draw. One of them is:} 25. Qc2 ({Or} 25. Qf2 Qe8 26. Qf1 Rb7 $1 {[%cal Gb7b1]} 27. Nf2 Qxe3 28. Qxh3 Ne2+ 29. Kg2 Nd4 30. Rf4 f5 31. Bg6 Be5 32. Rxf5 Nxf5 33. Qxf5 Re7 $11 {White has enough compensation to make a draw here.}) 25... Rxe3 26. Bxf7+ Kf8 $1 27. Bh5+ Kg8 28. Bf7+ $11 {With a perpetual check.}) 16... Bd7 $1 {I prefer this move.} ({A bit worse is:} 16... hxg2 {Sasikiran,K (2640)-Ding,L (2749) Danzhou 2015. Now after the unusual move:} 17. Rf2 $1 Bh3 18. Bh6 $14 {White has slightly preferable chances.}) 17. Na3 ({White has some alternatives. For example:} 17. Nc3 {Sethuraman,S (2632)-Triapishko,A (2508) St Petersburg 2017. Here the best move is:} Nh7 $1 {[%cal Gd8h4]} 18. gxh3 ({Or} 18. f4 Ng4 $132) 18... Bxh3 19. f4 Ng4 20. Bxg4 Bxg4 21. e5 f5 $5 {An interesting idea.} 22. Rae1 Re8 23. e6 Qh4 $132 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gb8b2] White's position is not safe.}) (17. Nxa7 {Black gets a serious counterplay after:} Qc7 18. Nc6 Bxc6 19. dxc6 d5 $1 20. gxh3 Rfd8 $132) (17. a4 {This inclusion, does not change much.} a6 18. Nc3 (18. Nxd6 Ne8 $1 {Still the best} 19. Nxe8 Rxb2 $1 20. Qc1 Rxe8 $132 {Black has an excellent play.}) 18... hxg2 19. Kxg2 Nh7 $132 {[%cal Gd8h4] Black is doing great.}) (17. Nxd6 Ne8 $1 {This is the point.} 18. Nxe8 Rxb2 $1 19. Qd1 Rxe8 $132 {Black has the initiative.}) 17... Nxe4 $1 {A very nice tactical shot. Now the game is very messy.} ({Probably also interesting is:} 17... Nfg4 $5) 18. Nxe4 ({Worse is:} 18. fxe4 $6 Rxb2 $1 19. Nc2 Ba4 20. Rac1 Rxa2 21. gxh3 Qh4 $15 {[%cal Ga2c2] Black's pieces are very well placed. White should be very careful here.}) 18... Rxb2 $1 {The point of Black's previous move.} 19. Nc2 {The best defense.} ({The alternatives are worse:} 19. Qe1 $6 Re8 $15 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Ge8e1] White's pieces are completely lacking coordination.}) (19. Qxb2 $2 {This leads to a clear advantage for Black after:} Nxf3+ 20. Rxf3 Bxb2 21. Rb1 Re8 $1 {[%cal Ge8e4]} 22. Rxb2 Rxe4 23. Bd3 Rg4 24. g3 ({Or} 24. Nc4 Bf5 $17) 24... Qa8 $1 25. Bc4 Rxc4 $1 26. Nxc4 Qxd5 27. Nd2 Kg7 $17 {[%csl Gd5,Gd7,Rg1] Black's domination is obvious.}) 19... f5 $1 {Black continues to play very direct.} 20. Bg5 Qb6 21. Nf2 c4 $1 {[%cal Gb6g1] Black definitely got a lot of initiative.} 22. Rac1 c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3] very critical position for the whole combination. White has many options here, but Black is fine everywhere.} 23. Qf4 ({The alternatives are:} 23. Qd1 Ba4 $1 {[%cal Ga4d1] the pins is very unpleasant.} 24. f4 Ng4 25. Bxg4 fxg4 26. gxh3 gxh3 27. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e7] The game is still very balanced.} Rxa2 28. Re7 Rxc2 {This forces the draw.} 29. Rxc2 Bxc2 30. Qxc2 Qb2 31. Qxg6 Qa1+ 32. Nd1 Qxd1+ 33. Kf2 Qd2+ $11 {With a draw.}) (23. Qxc3 Rc8 24. Qd2 Ba4 25. Bd1 Bb5 26. Re1 ({A draw is:} 26. Be2 Ba4 $11) 26... Nd3 $1 27. Be3 Bc3 $1 {The position is absolute mess.} 28. Qxd3 ({Also equal is:} 28. Qxc3 Rxc3 29. Bxb6 Nxc1 30. Bxa7 Rxa2 $11) 28... Qb7 {[%csl Rd3] White's queen is trapped.} 29. Qxc3 Rxc3 30. Bd4 Qc7 31. Nxh3 Rbxc2 32. Bxc2 Rxc2 33. Rb1 Qa5 $11 {White has compensation,but nothing more. The game is about level.}) (23. Qe3 Qxe3 24. Bxe3 Ba4 {[%csl Rc2]} 25. f4 Bxc2 26. fxe5 hxg2 27. Rfe1 Bxe5 $44 {[%csl Gc3] Black still keep fighting for the advantage.}) 23... Nf7 $1 {[%csl Rg5] The best move. White's pieces are paralyzed for the moment.} 24. Qh4 ({The alternatives are:} 24. Bd3 Re8 {This will transpose to some of the other lines.}) (24. Qg3 Re8 25. Bd3 ({Or} 25. Bc4 Ba4 $1) ({This looses to} 25. Rfe1 $2 Ba4 $1 $19) 25... Ne5 26. Kh1 ({Of course, White can repeat the moves with} 26. Be2 Nf7 $11) 26... Nxd3 27. Nxd3 Re2 28. Rf2 Rxf2 29. Nxf2 Ba4 {[%csl Rc2,Rf2]} 30. Nxh3 Rxc2 31. Re1 Rd2 $1 {The best move.} 32. Bf6 ({Or} 32. Bh6 Qd4) 32... Qc7 $1 33. Bxg7 ({Of course not} 33. Qxg6 $2 Qf7 $19 {[%csl Gc3]}) 33... Qxg7 34. Qh4 {[%cal Gh4d8,Gh4a4]} c2 $1 {Leads to a forced draw.} 35. Qxa4 Qe5 $1 36. Rxe5 ({Or} 36. Rg1 Qe2 37. Qc6 Rd1 $11) 36... c1=Q+ 37. Ng1 dxe5 38. Qe8+ $11 {With a perpetual check.}) 24... Re8 $1 25. Rfe1 {Here this move is possible because now the queen controls the a4 square.} ({The other reasonable move is:} 25. Bd3 Ne5 26. Kh1 ({The alternatives are:} 26. Be3 Nxd3 $5 {Looks very tempting.} 27. Bxb6 Nxc1 28. Nxh3 $1 {[%cal Gh3g5] White starts to counter-attack. Now is a forced draw after:} Ne2+ 29. Kh1 axb6 30. Ng5 Kf8 $1 31. Nh7+ Kf7 32. Ng5+ $11 {With a perpetual check.}) ({Or} 26. Be2 Nf7 $11) 26... Nxd3 27. Nxd3 Qb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5d3] The most accurate move here.} 28. Nxb2 cxb2 29. Rb1 Re2 30. Ne3 ({Or} 30. Rf2 Qd3 31. Rxe2 Qxe2 32. Ne3 hxg2+ 33. Kg1 Bb5 34. Bf4 Qxf3 35. Qd8+ Kh7 36. Qh4+ $11 {With a draw.}) 30... f4 $1 {[%cal Gd7f5] The only way for Black to keep the balance.} 31. Bxf4 Bf5 $1 32. Qd8+ ({Or} 32. gxh3 Bxb1 33. Qd8+ $11) 32... Kh7 33. Qh4+ $11 {White must give a perpetual check.}) 25... Nxg5 26. Qxg5 Kf7 $1 {Black needs to protect the g6 pawn.} 27. Qh4 ({A bit more logical is:} 27. Bd3 Bf6 $1 28. Qh6 ({The alternative is:} 28. Qg3 Rxe1+ 29. Rxe1 Ba4 {[%csl Rc2]} 30. Qxh3 Kg7 $1 {[%csl Rc2] A very nice and calm move.} 31. Ne3 c2 32. Bxc2 Bxc2 33. g4 $1 {With this move White manages to keep the balance.} Qb4 34. Rc1 Rxa2 35. gxf5 Qd2 36. Rxc2 Rxc2 37. Nxc2 Qxc2 $11 {With an equal endgame.}) 28... Rh8 29. Qe3 Qxe3 30. Rxe3 ({After:} 30. Nxe3 {strong is:} Rd2 $1 {[%cal Gf6d4]} 31. Nc4 Bd4 $1 32. Be2 Rxa2 33. Nxd6+ Kg7 $132 {[%cal Gd4f2] With a very nice compensation for the piece.}) 30... Bg5 31. Nxh3 Rxh3 $1 {Leads to a drawish endgame after:} 32. gxh3 Rxc2 33. Rxc2 Bxe3+ 34. Kf1 Bd2 {[%csl Gc3]} 35. Ke2 Ba4 36. Rxd2 cxd2 37. Kxd2 f4 38. h4 Kf6 $11 {The draw is near.}) 27... Rh8 28. Qg3 Bf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6h4] An important move.} 29. f4 Rxa2 30. Bd3 Ba4 31. Qf3 hxg2 32. Kxg2 Qc5 $44 {[%csl Gc3] Black has very nice domination. Now White must play for a draw with} 33. Rb1 Bxc2 (33... Rb2 $5 {Also leads to a draw after:} 34. Ne4 $1 fxe4 35. Qxe4 Rh6 36. Rxb2 cxb2 37. Qxa4 Rxh2+ 38. Kxh2 Qf2+ 39. Kh3 Qf3+ $11) 34. Rb7+ Kf8 35. Rb8+ $11 {With a perpetual check.} *

