{[%evp 0,11,22,24,25,4,39,26,26,26,34,17,9,24]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3 O-O 6. Be3 c5 7. dxc5 {One of the most popular moves in this position. White takes a pawn and enters an endgame. The practice has shown that Black has enough compensation for the pawn.} dxc5 8. Qxd8 ({The other moves are not so popular here.} 8. Bxc5 {In this move order Black has a couple of interesting ideas.} Qa5 $5 $146 {An interesting improvement. Black is definitely fighting for the advantage here.} ({The alternatives are:} 8... Nc6 {Will transpose to the main line.}) (8... Nfd7 $5) (8... Qc7 $5 9. Be3 Rd8 10. Qc1 Bd7 $44) 9. b4 (9. Bxe7 {Looks risky.} Nxe4 $1 {The point. White is probably still fine, but already he should be very careful.} 10. fxe4 ({A mistake is:} 10. Bxf8 $2 {because of} Bxc3+ $1 11. bxc3 Qxc3+ 12. Ke2 Bg4 $3 {The winning move.White's king is too weak.} 13. fxg4 ({Or} 13. Qc1 Qd4 $1 $19 {[%cal Gd4f2]}) 13... Nc6 $19 {[%cal Ga8e8] Re8 is coming next. Black wins.}) 10... Re8 11. Bd6 Rxe4+ 12. Nge2 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qxc3+ 14. Kf2 Qf6+ 15. Kg1 {The only move is to keep the balance.} (15. Ke1 $2 Nc6 $19) 15... Bg4 16. c5 {Unfortunately, Black has nothing more than a draw here.} Bxe2 17. Bxe2 Rxe2 18. Qxe2 Qxa1+ 19. Kf2 Qf6+ ({Similar is} 19... Qd4+ 20. Qe3) 20. Qf3 Qd4+ $11 {With a draw. The endgame is also equal.}) (9. Bf2 Nxe4 {Leads to a forced draw.} ({Another option is:} 9... Be6 $5 10. Qa4 Qxa4 11. Nxa4 Nfd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6] A nice manouvre.} 12. O-O-O Nb6 13. Nxb6 axb6 14. Kb1 b5 $11 {The endgame is approximately equal.}) 10. fxe4 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qxc3+ 12. Ke2 Bg4+ 13. Nf3 Qb2+ 14. Ke3 ({Also a draw is:} 14. Ke1 Qc3+ $11) 14... f5 $1 {[%cal Gf5f4] Now White must give a perpetual check by} 15. Qd5+ e6 16. Qxe6+ Rf7 17. Qe8+ Rf8 $11) (9. Be3 Nfd7 $1 {Here this is the best move.} 10. Bd2 (10. Bd4 {Black has many interesting ideas here. One of them is:} Ne5 $5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf8d8]} 11. f4 Rd8 12. b4 $1 {The only way to more or less keep the balance.} Qxb4 13. Rb1 Qa5 14. Rb5 Rxd4 $1 {A very nice exchange sacrifice. Black has a full compensation. For example:} 15. Rxa5 ({Worse is:} 15. Qxd4 $2 Nf3+ 16. Kd1 Bxd4 17. Rxa5 Nxg1 18. Rd5 Bb6 19. Rxg1 Be6 $17 {Black is better.}) 15... Rxd1+ 16. Nxd1 Nec6 17. Rb5 e5 $1 18. f5 Na6 19. Ne3 b6 $44 {[%cal Ga6c5,Gc6d4] Black has an excellent compensation.}) (10. Nge2 {Looks scary for White after:} Nc5 11. Kf2 Nc6 $44 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gf8d8,Gc5d3]}) 10... Nc6 11. Nd5 Qd8 12. Bc3 {This was the idea of White's previous move.} Bxc3+ 13. Nxc3 Nc5 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 {[%cal Gc5d3,Gc6d4,Gc6b4] White still did not develop his pieces.} 15. Rd1 ({Or} 15. Nd5 e6 16. Ne3 Nb4 $11 {[%cal Gb4d3]}) 15... Rxd1+ 16. Kxd1 Be6 17. Kd2 {[%cal Gd2e3]} ({Also equal is:} 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. cxd5 Nb4 19. a3 Nbd3 {[%cal Gd3b2,Gd3f2]} 20. Nh3 Nxb2+ 21. Kc2 Nba4 $11 {The endgame is equal.}) 17... Rd8+ 18. Ke3 Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2]} 19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. cxd5 Nxa2 21. Bc4 Nb4 22. Ne2 e6 23. Rc1 b6 $11 {[%csl Gb4,Gc5] Black has no problems at all.}) 9... Qc7 10. Be3 ({Worse is:} 10. Nb5 $6 Qe5 11. Bd4 Qh5 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 12. Ne2 Nc6 13. Nf4 Qg5 14. Be3 {Now Black is better after the small combination..} Nxe4 $1 15. fxe4 Rd8 16. Qc1 Qe5 $1 {[%csl Ra1,Re4][%cal Ge5a1,Ge5e4]} 17. Rb1 a6 {[%csl Rb5]} 18. Nd3 {The best defence.} Qxe4 19. Nf2 Qe5 20. Nd3 Rxd3 $1 {Playing for a win.} 21. Bxd3 Bh6 22. Kf2 Bxe3+ 23. Qxe3 axb5 24. Qxe5 Nxe5 25. Be2 bxc4 $15 {Black has two pawns for the exchange down and definitely only White can be worse here.}) (10. Rc1 Na6 {Black is doing great here.} 11. Nb5 Qc6 {[%csl Rb4,Rc5]} 12. Bf2 Nxb4 13. Qb3 Na6 $132 {[%cal Ga6c5]}) 10... Nc6 11. Qb3 Be6 12. Rc1 ({Worse is:} 12. Rd1 $6 Rfc8 {[%csl Rc4]}) 12... Rfc8 13. Nd5 Qd6 $44 {White is still lacking development. Black has excellent compensation for the pawn.}) (8. e5 {Only Black can be better here.} Nfd7 9. f4 f6 $1 {This move is always good in this situation.} 10. exf6 Nxf6 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bxc5 Nc6 13. Nf3 Bf5 {[%cal Gf6e4] The activity of Black's pieces compensates the pawn completely.} 14. Be2 Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Kf2 {White has nothing better.} Bxb2 17. Rad1 Bf6 $11 {The endgame is equal.}) 8... Rxd8 9. Bxc5 (9. e5 $6 {White is fighting for the equality after:} Ne8 $1 ({Only equal is:} 9... Nfd7 10. f4 b6 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7]}) 10. Bxc5 ({Or} 10. f4 b6 11. Be2 Bb7 12. Bf3 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 Nc6 14. O-O f6 $15 {I believe Black is slightly better.}) 10... Nc6 11. f4 b6 12. Be3 g5 $1 13. g3 (13. fxg5 {Also looks better for Black after:} Nxe5 $15) 13... Nxe5 $1 {The point.} 14. fxe5 Bb7 15. Nd5 Rxd5 16. cxd5 Bxd5 17. Nf3 Bxf3 18. Rg1 Bxe5 {[%cal Ge5b2]} 19. Bg2 Bxg2 20. Rxg2 f6 21. Rc2 Kf7 $15 {Black is definitely out of danger and still fighting for the advantage.}) 9... Nc6 {The critical position. White has many different moves:} 10. Nge2 {Together with 10.Rd1, this is the most critical line.} (10. Nd5 {The old main move. Already the theory proved that Black is completely fine and out of danger.} Nd7 11. Nxe7+ ({The other options are:} 11. Ba3 e6 12. Nc7 Rb8 13. O-O-O (13. Nb5 $6 {Looks too slow, and White loses a lot of important time.} a6 14. Nd6 b5 $1 {Black is already much better.} 15. cxb5 axb5 16. Bxb5 ({Or} 16. Nxb5 Ba6 17. Nc3 Nd4 $19 {[%cal Gd4c2] Black wins.}) 16... Nd4 17. Ba4 ({Or} 17. Bd3 Ne5 $19) 17... Ra8 ({Also good is:} 17... Ba6 $17) 18. Nxc8 Rxa4 19. Ne7+ Kh8 20. Rd1 Rc4 $1 {[%csl Re7] Black has full domination.} 21. Nh3 Bf6 22. O-O Nc5 $19 {[%csl Re7] Black wins material.}) 13... a6 $1 {[%csl Rc7] White's knight on c7 is in big trouble. For example:} 14. f4 Bf8 $1 15. Bxf8 Kxf8 16. Nf3 Nc5 17. Rxd8+ Nxd8 18. Nd2 Ke7 $17) (11. Bxe7 {Leads to equality after:} Nxe7 12. Nxe7+ Kf8 13. Nd5 Bxb2 14. Rb1 Bg7 {It is clear that Black has more than enough compensation for the pawn. The game can continue:} 15. Nh3 Nc5 16. Nf2 Be6 17. Be2 Rac8 $44 {[%csl Gc5,Gg7]}) 11... Nxe7 12. Bxe7 Bxb2 13. Rb1 ({Another option is:} 13. Bxd8 Bxa1 14. Ne2 Be5 {This is just one of the good moves here.} 15. Be7 b6 $44 {[%cal Gc8a6]}) 13... Bc3+ 14. Kf2 ({Or} 14. Kd1 Re8 15. Ne2 Bg7 16. Bh4 Nc5 $44 {[%cal Gc8e6] Black is doing great.}) 14... Bd4+ 15. Kg3 Re8 16. Bg5 Nf6 $44 {[%cal Gf6h5] Black has a strong initiative.}) (10. Rd1 {Played by some strong players lately. Definitely this move is a serious one, and Black should know exactly what to do.} Rxd1+ 11. Kxd1 ({A bit worse is:} 11. Nxd1 b6 ({Also good is:} 11... Nd7 12. Bf2 Nde5 $44) 12. Ba3 ({Worse is:} 12. Be3 $6 Nb4 $15 {[%cal Gb4a2,Gb4c2]}) ({Or} 12. Bf2 $6 Be6 $15) 12... a5 {[%cal Gc6b4] The typical move with the bishop on a3.} 13. Ne2 Nb4 14. Nec3 Nc2+ 15. Kd2 Nxa3 16. bxa3 Nd7 $44 {[%cal Gd7c5] Black has an excellent game.}) 11... Nd7 $1 12. Bf2 ({Worse is:} 12. Ba3 $6 {because of} Bxc3 $1 13. bxc3 Nde5 $15 {[%csl Rc4]}) 12... Bxc3 {Looks nice here.} ({The alternative is:} 12... b6 $5 13. Nge2 Ba6 14. Nb5 Nc5 $44) 13. bxc3 Nde5 ({Probably also fine is:} 13... b6 $5 14. Ne2 Ba6 15. Nf4 Kf8 $44) 14. Ne2 Be6 $1 {the best move. I believe now Black equalizes.} ({A bit worse is:} 14... Nxc4 15. Nf4 $14) 15. Nd4 Bxc4 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Bg3 Rd8+ 18. Kc2 {This position occurred in the game L'Ami, E  (2621)-Efimenko,Z (2597) Germany 2022. Now Black could equalize easily after:} Nd3 19. Be2 Nb4+ 20. cxb4 Bxe2 $11 {The draw is near.}) (10. Ba3 {This move was popular some years ago. Nowadays looks like Black has zero problems.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gc6b4] I believe the best move.} ({The alternatives are:} 10... Be6) (10... b6) 11. Rd1 ({Much worse is:} 11. Nd5 $6 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Nb4 $15) 11... Be6 12. Nd5 ({Or} 12. Bd3 Nb4 13. Nd5 {Transpose to 12.Nd5.}) ({Similar to the main line is:} 12. Rxd8+ Rxd8 13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. cxd5 Nb4 $132) 12... Nb4 $1 {The key move.} 13. Nxe7+ (13. Bd3 {Looks harmless after:} Nfxd5 $1 14. cxd5 ({Or} 14. exd5 Nxd3+ 15. Rxd3 Bf5 16. Rd1 Rac8 17. b3 a4 $132 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gf5c2,Gb7b5] Only Black can be better here.}) 14... Bd7 15. Ne2 e6 {Black must open the centre. Now White more or less keeps the balance with} 16. Bxb4 axb4 17. Bc4 Bxb2 $11 {The endgame is approximately equal, but still a bit more pleasant for Black.}) 13... Kh8 ({Of course not} 13... Kf8 $2 14. Nd5 $16 {[%cal Ga3f8]}) 14. Rxd8+ ({Similar, but a bit worse version for White is:} 14. Nd5 Nc2+ 15. Kf2 Nxa3 16. bxa3 b5 $132) 14... Rxd8 15. Nd5 Nc2+ 16. Kf2 Nxa3 17. bxa3 b5 $1 {It seems that now the game is absolutely level. For example:} 18. Nh3 bxc4 19. Bxc4 Rc8 20. Bb3 ({Or} 20. Nxf6 Rxc4) 20... Nxd5 $146 {A novelty.} ({Also completely equal is the theoretical move} 20... a4 21. Bxa4 Nxd5 22. exd5 Bxd5 $11) 21. exd5 ({Or} 21. Bxd5 Rc2+) 21... Bxh3 22. gxh3 Bf8 $11 {The endgame is just a draw.}) (10. Be3 {Another not very popular move here.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2] The most direct approach.} ({Also possible is:} 10... Be6) 11. Rc1 Be6 12. Kf2 ({The alternative is:} 12. e5 Nd7 13. f4 f6 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. a3 Nc6 16. Nf3 Nb6 $44 {[%csl Rc4] Black is at least not worse.}) 12... Ne8 $5 {[%cal Ge8d6] One of the good moves.} ({The alternatives are:} 12... Rac8 13. a3 Nd3+ 14. Bxd3 Rxd3 15. Nge2 Bxc4 16. Rhd1 Rxd1 17. Rxd1 a6 $11 {The endgame looks very equal.}) (12... Nd7 13. a3 Nc6 14. Nh3 Bxh3 15. gxh3 Nd4 $44 {Black has enough compensation.}) 13. a3 ({After:} 13. Nh3 Nd6 {[%csl Rc4]} 14. b3 Bxc3 15. Rxc3 Nxa2 16. Rc2 Nb4 17. Rd2 Bxh3 18. gxh3 b6 $11 {Black is just fine.}) 13... Nc6 14. b4 ({Or} 14. c5 Nd4 15. Nge2 {Now Black can force a draw by} Nb3 16. Rc2 Na1 17. Rc1 Nb3 $11) 14... Nd6 15. Nd5 a5 $1 {An important move.} 16. b5 Bxd5 17. exd5 ({Worse is:} 17. cxd5 $6 Ne5 $15 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd8c8] Only Black can use the c file.}) 17... Ne5 {[%cal Gd6f5]} 18. g4 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gd6f5] An interesting positional move. Prevents Nf5.} ({In case of:} 18. Nh3 Nf5 $1 19. Bd2 Rac8 20. Be2 b6 $44 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf5d4,Gf5d6] Black is doing great.}) 18... b6 $1 {The only move to keep the balance.} 19. Bxb6 Rdc8 20. Be3 ({Of course not} 20. c5 $2 {because of} Nd7 $1 $17) 20... Nexc4 21. Bxc4 Nxc4 22. Ne2 {The endgame is about equal. For example:} Bb2 23. Rc2 Bxa3 24. Ra1 Nxe3 25. Rxc8+ Rxc8 26. Kxe3 Bb4 $11) (10. Rc1 {A very rare move. Does not bring anything for White.} Nd7 11. Ba3 ({Or} 11. Be3 Nde5 {[%cal Ge5d3]}) 11... b6 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gd7c5]} 12. Nh3 a5 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gd7c5]} 13. Be2 Nc5 $44 {[%csl Rb4,Rd4][%cal Gc5d3] Black has a full control of the game.}) 10... b6 $1 {I believe is the best move.} ({The other possible continuation is:} 10... Nd7) 11. Ba3 ({Of course not} 11. Be3 $2 {because of} Nb4 $19 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gb4d3]}) 11... Ba6 {One of the good moves. I prefer this move, but the alternatives are also possible:} (11... Bb7) (11... a5 {[%cal Gc6b4]}) (11... e6) 12. Nb5 {The main move. Blocking the bishop on a6.} (12. b3 {A possible and logical move.} Rd7 $1 {[%cal Ga8d8] I think objectively this is the best move. Prepares Rad8.} 13. Rd1 Rad8 14. Rxd7 Nxd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c5] Transfers the knight into a more active position.} 15. Na4 b5 {Black has some alternatives, but this move equalizes very easy after:} 16. cxb5 Bxb5 $44 17. Nec3 Bxa4 18. Nxa4 Nb6 $1 19. Be2 ({Or} 19. Nxb6 Bc3+) 19... Nxa4 20. bxa4 Bc3+ 21. Kf2 Rd2 22. Rc1 Bd4+ 23. Ke1 Rxa2 24. Rxc6 Rxa3 $11 {White must be a bit more careful.}) (12. Nd5 {Leads to full equality after:} Bxc4 13. Nxe7+ Nxe7 14. Bxe7 Re8 15. Bxf6 ({Of course not} 15. Ba3 $2 {because of the very strong tactical shot} Nxe4 $1 16. fxe4 Rxe4 17. Kf2 Rd8 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gd8d2] Black is better. The threat is Rd2.} 18. Kf3 f5 19. Rc1 Rd3+ 20. Kf2 Rd2 21. Ke1 Bh6 $17) 15... Bxf6 16. Nc3 Rac8 17. Bxc4 Rxc4 18. Rc1 Rec8 $11 {Black has zero problems.}) (12. Nf4 $6 {This is not very accurate, because of} e6 {[%csl Rf4] Now White has some problems. For example:} 13. Rd1 g5 $1 14. Nh3 g4 15. Rxd8+ Rxd8 16. Nf4 Nd4 17. Kf2 Nc2 $15 {I prefer Black here.}) 12... Rd7 {[%cal Ga8d8] Doubles the rooks and prevents Nc7.} 13. Rd1 ({Similar is:} 13. Nec3 Rad8 14. Rd1 {Transpose to 13.Rd1.}) 13... Rad8 14. Nec3 ({The alternative is:} 14. Rxd7 Nxd7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gd7e5] Looks more logical} ({In this situation also possible is} 14... Rxd7) 15. Nec3 Nc5 16. Be2 Bc8 {[%cal Ga7a6] Black definitely has the initiative.} 17. Nd5 e6 18. Ne3 Na4 $5 {[%csl Rb2] The most direct approach.} ({Also possible is} 18... f5 19. exf5 gxf5 $44) 19. Nd1 Bb7 20. Ndc3 Nxc3 21. Nxc3 ({Or} 21. bxc3 a6 22. Nd4 Nxd4 23. cxd4 Bxd4 24. Bd3 $11) 21... f5 $1 22. exf5 gxf5 23. Rf1 {White cannot castle, because Black rook is ready to enter the d2-square.} Nd4 24. Bd1 Ba6 $132 {Black is at least not worse.}) 14... Bxb5 $5 {I like to force the game. I believe Black equalizes by force here.} 15. Rxd7 ({Or} 15. cxb5 Nd4 16. Bd3 Nxf3+ 17. gxf3 Rxd3 18. Rxd3 Rxd3 {Transposes to the main line.}) 15... Rxd7 16. cxb5 ({Or} 16. Nxb5 Bh6 $1 17. Be2 Be3 18. Nc3 Rd2 19. e5 $1 {The only move to not be worse.} Nxe5 20. Nd1 Bh6 21. Bxe7 Nfd7 22. Bb4 Rc2 $11 {[%csl Gc2] The endgame is approximately equal. Black's rook is very active.}) 16... Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2]} 17. Bd3 {White must return the pawn up.} ({Clearly worse is:} 17. Kf2 $6 Nc2 $15) 17... Nxf3+ 18. gxf3 Rxd3 19. Ke2 Rd7 {The endgame should be equal. For example:} 20. Rd1 {There is nothing better.} Rxd1 21. Nxd1 Kf8 22. Ne3 Ke8 $11 {[%cal Ge8d7,Ge7e6,Gf6h5] The endgame is complex,but approximately equal.} *

