1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 (2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. e3 {A possible and very solid plan. The idea is to develop slowly by Nge2,0-0 and the b3-Bb2.} (6. e4 {This is very dubious here. White is just not ready for this move.} c5 $1 {Definitely the best reaction. Black breaks immediately the centre.} 7. Nge2 (7. dxc5 {The endgame looks absolutely harmless for Black.} dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. e5 Nfd7 10. f4 Nc6 11. Nge2 Nb6 12. b3 f6 {The typical plan in this kind of situation.} 13. exf6 Bxf6 $11 {The endgame is about equal, but only White should be careful.}) (7. d5 $6 {It is a bad idea here,because of} e6 8. Nge2 exd5 9. cxd5 a6 10. a4 Nbd7 {Black has an excellent Benoni. The knight on e2 is too passive.} 11. O-O Re8 12. h3 Rb8 $15 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gb7b5] Black's game is very easy.}) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {White's problem is that now Nxe4 is a serious threat.} 9. Nde2 ({Worse is} 9. O-O $6 {because of} Nxe4 $1 10. Nxc6 Nxc3 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. bxc3 Be6 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4] With a slightly better position for Black.}) 9... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Preparing the typical b5 push.} 10. O-O ({In case of} 10. a4 {strong is} Bg4 $1 11. h3 Bxe2 12. Nxe2 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 13. Rb1 Nde5 14. b3 b5 $15 {Black is better.}) 10... Be6 11. b3 ({Or} 11. Nd5 b5) 11... b5 12. cxb5 axb5 13. Bb2 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gd7c5] Black has an excellent position.}) 6... e5 7. Nge2 Re8 8. O-O (8. h3 {Does not change much} c6) 8... e4 $5 {A bit rare, but a very ambitious plan. Black wants to block the bishop on g2.} ({More natural is:} 8... c6) 9. h3 ({Worse is:} 9. Qc2 $6 Bf5 {Now for White will be more difficult to open the position by f2-f3.}) 9... c6 ({If} 9... h5 $6 {then} 10. Nf4 {[%csl Rh5]}) 10. g4 {[%cal Ge2g3] A very logical move. White's plan is to play Ng3 next and put more pressure on the e4 pawn.} ({Also possible is:} 10. Nf4 Nbd7 11. g4 h6 {To prevent g4-g5 is important.} 12. f3 g5 $1 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8g6] Looks risky, but actually is the best move. In some lines, Black knight can come to g6 via f8.} 13. Nfe2 ({Tempting, but not enough for advantage is:} 13. fxe4 $5 gxf4 14. exf4 c5 $1 {Black must break the centre.} 15. e5 {There is nothing better.} cxd4 $1 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. Nb5 a6 18. Nxd4 Qb6 {[%cal Gb6g1] Black definitely has good counterplay. For example:} 19. Kh2 Nxg4+ 20. hxg4 Bxd4 21. f5 Bd7 $132 {The game is very sharp.}) 13... exf3 14. Bxf3 Nf8 $1 {[%cal Gf8g6] The knight will be perfectly placed on g6.} 15. e4 Ng6 16. Ng3 Be6 $132 {The game is quite complicated, but Black has an excellent chance to fight for the advantage.}) 10... h6 {Stopping g4-g5 is crucial.} 11. Ng3 ({Or} 11. Qc2 d5 12. Bd2 Na6 $132) 11... d5 12. f3 {The most natural plan for White.} ({The alternative is:} 12. Bd2 Be6 13. Rc1 a5 $11 {[%cal Gb8a6]}) 12... exf3 13. Qxf3 Be6 14. cxd5 cxd5 ({Also good is:} 14... Nxd5 15. Nce4 Na6 $11) 15. Nge2 {[%cal Ge2f4]} g5 $5 {The most ambitious continuation. The game is very sharp now.} 16. Ng3 Nc6 17. Nf5 ({Or} 17. Bd2 Ne7 $11) 17... Bxf5 18. Qxf5 Ne7 19. Qd3 Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c6,Gc6e6]} 20. Bd2 Rc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6e6]} 21. Rae1 Re6 $11 {The game is approximately equal. Both sides have their chances.}) 2... g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d6 {In this chapter we will see all the options for White except 6.c4.} 6. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] A popular move. White wants to play in the style of Pirc-Ufimcev.} (6. Re1 $5 {An interesting move order. White prepares e4, but also keeps the option to play Nc3 later.} c5 $5 {A bit strange move. I prefer to play this way because I think this leads to a more complicated game.} ({The other moves are:} 6... Nbd7 7. e4 e5 8. Nc3 $14) ({Or} 6... d5 7. c4) 7. dxc5 {This is probably the best way for White to fight for the advantage.} ({Harmless is:} 7. d5 b5 8. e4 Nbd7 $132 {Looks good for Black.}) (7. e4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 $11 {This is a nice Dragon for Black.}) (7. Nc3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] Black has no problems. For example, :} 9. a4 Nc6 10. Nb3 Be6 11. a5 Qc7 12. e4 Qd7 13. Nd5 Bh3 $11 {The game is about equal.}) (7. c3 $5 {The best alternative to 7.dxc5. Black still should play a bit more accurate here.} cxd4 8. cxd4 Bf5 9. Nc3 ({The alternatives are harmless:} 9. Nh4 Be4 $11) ({Or} 9. Qb3 Nc6 $1 {of course Black does not care about the b7 pawn.} 10. Qxb7 Qe8 {[%cal Ga8b8]} 11. Qb3 ({To a draw leads:} 11. Nc3 Rb8 12. Qc7 Rc8 $11) 11... Rb8 12. Qd1 Nb4 13. Na3 {Black has excellent compensation for the pawn. For example:} Qc6 $5 ({Also possible is} 13... a5 $44) 14. Bd2 Qa6 15. Bf1 Ne4 $44 {Black has a very nice piece play.}) 9... Ne4 10. Nh4 {A logical move.} (10. Nd2 {Another possible move.} Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qd7 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e4 Bg4 14. Nc4 Rac8 15. Ne3 Bh3 $11 {Black is doing very well. Now to take the pawn by} 16. Bxh3 Qxh3 17. Qxb7 $2 {It is a bad idea in view of} Bxd4 $1 18. cxd4 Nxd4 {[%cal Gd4f3]} 19. e5 Rc6 $1 $19 {[%cal Gd4f3] Black wins.}) ({Looks harmless after:} 10. Qb3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Be4 $11) 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bc8 {There is nothing better now.} 12. Nf3 Qc7 13. Qd3 Nc6 $11 {The game is still very complex, but I believe Black has his chances.}) 7... dxc5 8. c3 {In my opinion this is a bit better move order for White.} ({The most common move is:} 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. c3 ({After:} 9. Ne5 {good is:} Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5b4]}) 9... Be6 $1 {The point is that now Black can play without Nc6.} 10. Ng5 ({Black is completely fine after:} 10. a4 Nc6 11. Ng5 Bd7 12. a5 h6 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Rab8 {[%cal Gb7b6]} 15. Nd2 b6 16. axb6 axb6 17. Nc4 Be6 18. Bxc6 Bxc4 $11 {With a completely level game.}) 10... Bd5 11. e4 Bc6 12. Nd2 h6 13. Ngf3 Nbd7 14. e5 {The only way for White to fight for something more.} ({Or} 14. h3 e6 $11) 14... Ng4 15. e6 fxe6 16. Rxe6 Kf7 17. Re2 Nde5 18. Nxe5+ Nxe5 $11 {he controls of the d file should be enough for equality.}) ({Another possible move is:} 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Bf4 Be6 10. Qc1 Qc8 11. e4 Rd8 12. Bh6 Bh3 $11 {Should be very equal.}) 8... Qc7 $5 {A very rare move, there is only one game. The point is already to keep the queens.} ({A bit unpleasant is:} 8... Nc6 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. Be3 $14) 9. Bf4 ({Another option is:} 9. Na3 Nc6 10. Nc4 Be6 11. Bf4 Qc8 $11) 9... Qb6 10. Qc1 Nc6 11. Nbd2 {Of course the game is still complex, but Black also has chances to fight for more than just equality.} Nd5 12. Bg5 Be6 ({Interesting is:} 12... f6 $5) 13. e4 Nf6 14. e5 Nd5 15. Nc4 Qa6 16. Bf1 b5 17. Na3 ({Or} 17. Ne3 Qb7 $11) 17... Qb7 18. Bxb5 Rab8 {Black is a pawn down, but it is clear that the counterplay is strong enough.} 19. b3 Qc7 {[%csl Re5]} 20. Bh6 Nxe5 $1 {Black should fight for the initiative at all costs.} 21. Nxe5 Bxe5 22. Bxf8 Rxf8 23. Bc4 ({After:} 23. Nb1 Rd8 $44 {Black has an excellent compensation.}) 23... Nxc3 24. Bxe6 fxe6 25. Qe3 Bd4 26. Qxe6+ Kh8 {[%csl Rf2]} 27. Re3 $5 {An interesting move, but not enough for an advantage.} ({After} 27. Rf1 {Black has to play} Rf6 $1 28. Qc4 Rf3 $1 $11 {[%cal Gf3g3] The threat is Rxg3!}) 27... Qb7 $1 28. Nc2 Bxe3 29. Qxe3 Qf3 30. Qxf3 Rxf3 31. Ne3 Kg8 32. Kg2 Rf6 $11 {[%cal Gf6a6] The game looks very balanced.}) (6. a4 {A quite popular move. White wants to gain more space on the queen's side.} Nc6 $5 {[%cal Ge7e5] Black has many other moves, but this one is the most direct. The point is to push e7-e5 as soon as possible.} ({The other moves are:} 6... a5) (6... Nbd7) (6... c6) 7. a5 {The most logical way to continue.} ({Black is completely fine after:} 7. Nc3 e5 8. e4 ({Or} 8. d5 Nb4 $132 {[%csl Gb4] Because of the pawn on a4,now the knight is untouchable on b4.}) 8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Nxe4 $1 {Immediately equalize.} 10. Nxc6 ({Also equal is:} 10. Nxe4 Nxd4 11. Bg5 f6 {Obviously the only move.} 12. Qxd4 fxg5 13. Qd5+ Kh8 14. Nxg5 Qf6 15. Rae1 c6 $11 {Black has no problems.}) 10... Nxc3 11. Nxd8 Nxd1 12. Nxb7 Bxb7 13. Bxb7 Rab8 14. Rxd1 Rxb7 15. c3 Re8 $11 {The endgame is just very equal.}) (7. Bf4 $5 $146 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge7e5] A new move,which makes some sense. The point is to prevent e5 at least for now.} Re8 8. a5 Bf5 {[%cal Ge7e5] Black still needs to prepare e5.} 9. d5 ({After:} 9. a6 {strong is} bxa6 $1 {[%cal Gc6b4]}) 9... Nb4 10. Nh4 Bd7 11. e4 {The game is very complex here. One of the possible ways to continue is:} Nh5 $5 12. Bc1 Nf6 13. c3 ({Of course White can repeat moves by} 13. Bf4 $11) 13... Na6 14. Re1 c6 $11 {Black is doing good.}) 7... e5 $1 8. dxe5 {The most logical plan for White is to open the position. The alternatives are:} (8. d5 Nb4 {[%csl Gb4]} 9. Ne1 c6 10. c4 cxd5 11. Bd2 Na6 12. cxd5 Bd7 $11 {Black has a good game.}) (8. a6 e4 9. Nfd2 Nxd4 10. c3 Ne6 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 c6 $132 {White should be more careful here.}) 8... dxe5 9. Qxd8 ({In case of} 9. Nc3 {Black can simply play} a6 10. e4 ({Or} 10. Be3 Qe7 $11) 10... Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Bg4 12. Be3 Rfd8 $11 {The position is just equal.}) (9. a6 e4 {Will transpose to the main line.}) 9... Rxd8 10. a6 e4 11. Ng5 Nd4 {The game is a bit more concrete here, but still very equal after:} 12. Nc3 Nxc2 13. Ra4 b5 $1 {Clearly the best move.} 14. Nxb5 Bd7 15. Rc4 ({Another option is:} 15. Ra5 Bxb5 16. Rxb5 Nd4 17. Rb7 Nxe2+ 18. Kh1 Nxc1 19. Rxc1 Bh6 20. h4 Ne8 $11 {[%cal Ge8d6] Looks equal.}) 15... Bxb5 16. Rxc2 Re8 17. Rxc7 Bxe2 18. Re1 Bxa6 $11 {The draw is near.}) (6. b3 {A popular set-up for White. The plan is to develop slowly by Bb2 and Nbd2.} e5 $1 {This is the best reaction in this move order. White will not have time to develop properly.} 7. dxe5 {The most principled continuation.} ({The other moves are harmless. For example:} 7. c4 e4 {Leads to an equal position after:} 8. Ng5 Bf5 9. Nc3 Nc6 {Putting more pressure on the d4 pawn.} 10. h3 h6 11. Ngxe4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxd4 {I believe Black has zero problems.} 13. Be3 Re8 14. Bxd4 Bxe4 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qd4+ Qf6 17. Qxf6+ Kxf6 $11 {The endgame is completely equal.}) 7... dxe5 8. Ba3 {By far the most popular move. White has some alternatives:} (8. Bb2 {Not very ambitious move. Black has no problems after:} e4 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. Ne5 Bf5 11. Nc3 Na6 $11) (8. Nxe5 $5 {There is only one game with this move, but actually I think is an interesting try.} Ng4 $1 {The point.} 9. Nxg4 Bxa1 10. Ne3 {[%cal Ge3d5,Gc2c3] White is an exchange down, but clearly he has good compensation. For now c3 is a serious threat.} Bg7 {Probably not the only move, but definitely the most logical.} 11. Ba3 {Winning a tempo.} Re8 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Nd5 {[%cal Gd5c7,Gd5e7]} Nc6 $1 {Black must give up another pawn.} 14. Nxc7 Rb8 15. c4 Bf5 {The game is very complex, but I believe Black has enough counterplay at least for an equal game.} 16. e4 ({If} 16. Nd5 {then strong is} b5 $1) 16... Be6 17. f4 Rd7 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Bh3 Re8 20. e5 {Looks promising for White, but I believe Black is having a lot of counterplay thanks to the control of the d file.} Bf8 {It is important to exchange the black squared bishops.} 21. Bxf8 Kxf8 22. Nc3 Rd3 $1 23. Ne4 Nd4 24. Nd6 Re7 $11 {The game is approximately level.}) 8... Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Re8 10. c4 ({The alternatives are:} 10. Nfd2 e4 11. Bb2 e3 {A very logical way to play.} 12. fxe3 Ng4 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 $11 {Black is doing great.}) (10. Bb2 e4 11. Nfd2 {Transpose to 10.Nfd2.}) (10. Nc3 {Another logical move.} e4 11. Nd2 ({Or} 11. Nd4 c6 ({Also good is:} 11... a6 $5 12. e3 Nbd7) 12. e3 h5 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7] The endgame is approximately equal.}) 11... e3 $1 {One again this typical motif.} 12. fxe3 Na6 13. Bb2 Rb8 $44 {Black has excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 10... a5 $1 {[%cal Gb8a6] I believe here this is the best move.} (10... e4 11. Nd4) 11. Nc3 Na6 12. Rac1 e4 13. Nd4 {This position occurred in the game Hakobyan, A (2588)-Vitiugov, N (2722) Chess. com INT 2020. Now Black could simply continue with} c6 $11 {With equal chances.}) (6. c3 {A passive way to play.} Nbd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] This simple plan already looks good enough for Black.} 7. Re1 ({Similar is:} 7. Nbd2 e5 8. e4 Re8 9. Re1 {Transpose to 7.Re1.}) 7... e5 8. e4 Re8 9. Nbd2 {The knight on d2 is quite passive.} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] A very natural plan here. I believe Black has no problems. For example:} 10. dxe5 ({The other possible moves are:} 10. Qc2 Bb7 11. b3 exd4 12. cxd4 c5 $132 {With a good counterplay.}) (10. a4 a5 11. b3 exd4 12. cxd4 Bb7 $132) 10... Nxe5 ({Also good is:} 10... dxe5 11. b4 a5 $11) 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Nc4 Qe7 $11 {The game looks very equal.}) (6. Nbd2 {Similar to 6.c3.} Re8 $5 {[%cal Ge7e5] In this case I prefer to start with this move.} ({There is nothing wrong with:} 6... Nc6) ({Or} 6... Nbd7) 7. e4 e5 8. dxe5 ({Worse is:} 8. d5 $6 a5 9. c4 Na6 $15 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Ga6c5,Gc8d7] The knight on d2 does not belong there.}) 8... dxe5 9. b3 ({Or} 9. Qe2 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6]}) 9... a5 10. a4 Nc6 11. Bb2 Qe7 $11 {Black has equal chances.}) 6... d5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] With the knight on c3 this move looks very logical.} ({More popular are:} 6... Nbd7) (6... c6) (6... Nc6) 7. Re1 {[%cal Ge2e4] White insisting on pushing e2-e4.} ({Also a normal move is:} 7. Ne5 c6 8. e4 ({If} 8. Bf4 {then} Nh5 $1) 8... dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 c5 {Black resolved all of his problems. For example:} 11. c3 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nd7 $11 {With an equal game.}) (7. Bf4 {Another popular move.} c6 {A good waiting move.} 8. Re1 ({Or} 8. Qd2 Bf5 {[%cal Gf6e4]}) 8... Bf5 9. Nh4 {To push e2-e4 is the only reasonable plan.} Be6 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Rxe4 Bd5 13. Re3 Bxg2 14. Nxg2 Nd7 $11 {Black's position is very solid.}) (7. a4 {This move does not bring anything special for White.} a5 8. Re1 Na6 9. Ne5 ({The alternatives are:} 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Rxe4 c5 {Looks good for Black. The game is about equal after:} 12. Bg5 Re8 13. dxc5 Qxd1+ 14. Rxd1 Bf5 15. Rxe7 Rxe7 16. Bxe7 Re8 17. Rd8 Rxd8 18. Bxd8 Bxc2 19. Bxa5 Bxb2 $11 {The draw is very near.}) ({If} 9. Bf4 {then} Bf5) 9... c5 $1 {Equalizes very easy.} 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. Be3 ({Or} 11. Nb5 Bf5 $11) 11... Nce4 ({Also possible is:} 11... Nfe4 $5) 12. Nb5 Be6 13. c3 Nd6 $11 {The game is equal.}) 7... c5 $1 {A rare move,which in my opinion equalizes.} ({More popular are:} 7... Bf5) (7... Ne4) (7... c6) 8. dxc5 {White has nothing better.} Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5]} 9. Nd4 {Probably the best try for White.} ({The alternative is:} 9. Be3 Ng4 $1 {The point of Black's plan.} 10. Nxd5 ({After} 10. Bc1 {Black can simply repeat the moves with} Nf6 $11) 10... Be6 11. c4 Bxd5 12. Qxd5 Qxd5 13. cxd5 Nxe3 14. fxe3 Nxc5 $44 {Black has excellent compensation for the pawn. The endgame is approximately equal.}) 9... Nxc5 10. Nb3 Nxb3 11. axb3 Be6 $146 {A good improvement.} ({A little worse is:} 11... d4 12. Na4 e5 13. c3 Re8 14. b4 a5 {Caille,H (2159)-Cornette, D (2384) Chartres 2022. Now White is slightly better after:} 15. Nc5 $14) 12. e4 {Leads to a lot of exchanges.} ({Or} 12. Be3 Qc7 $11 {with an equal chances.}) 12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Rfd8 15. Bg5 ({Also equal is:} 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bf4 Bxb2 17. Bxb7 Bxa1 18. Rxa1 a6 19. Bxa8 Rxa8 $11 {With an easy draw.}) 15... Bf5 $5 {I prefer this move.} ({Also possible is:} 15... Nxe4 16. Rxd8+ Rxd8 17. Bxe4 Bxb2 18. Rxa7 Bh3 19. Bd3 Bd4 20. Ra4 f6 21. Be3 e5 $11 {Black's position is quite safe.}) 16. Bxf6 ({Another option is:} 16. Nc5 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Rc8 18. Nxb7 Bxc2 19. Rc1 Bf5 20. Rxc8+ Bxc8 21. Be3 a6 $11 {With an equal endgame.}) 16... exf6 {For now is good to keep the pair of bishops.} 17. c3 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Re8 {I believe this line is a forced draw.} 19. Nd6 Rd8 {The point of Black's previous move.} 20. Rd4 Be6 21. Nb5 ({All other moves also are leading to a draw:} 21. Bxb7 f5 22. Rd2 Bh6 23. Rd4 Bg7 $11 {White can't escape from the repetition of the moves.}) (21. Nxb7 Rxd4 22. cxd4 f5 $1 {[%cal Gg7b2]} ({But not} 22... Bxb3 $2 {because of} 23. Bc6 $1 $18 {[%cal Gd4d8]}) 23. d5 Bd7 24. Nc5 Bb5 $11 {[%cal Gg7b2] The endgame is equal.}) 21... Rxd4 22. Nxd4 b6 23. b4 a5 24. bxa5 bxa5 $11 {The draw is very close.} *

