sting way to play for White.} ({More normal looks} 10. Ne5 c6 11. Nxc4 Be6 {Black developed very nicely, and I believe the chances are equal. For example:} 12. Ne5 ({Or} 12. b3 Nfd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bg5 Nc7 $11 {[%csl Rd4]}) 12... Nfd5 13. Bd2 c5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 $11 {With an equal game.}) 10... cxb3 11. Qxb3 Nbd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Be5 {White has good compensation. Now I believe the best way for Black to continue is:} Bh6 $1 ({In case of} 13... Bxe5 14. Nxe5 c6 15. Rfd1 $44 {White has a nice and easy game.}) 14. e4 {A risky, but very logical move. White fights for the initiative.} ({If} 14. Rcd1 {then after} c6 15. e4 Nf6 $132 {[%cal Gf6g4,Gf6e4] Black definitely has a good counterplay. An unpleasant threat is Ng4.}) 14... Bxc1 15. Rxc1 Nf6 16. Bxc7 Qd7 17. e5 Ne8 $1 {A bit unusual, but definitely the best.} ({Worse is:} 17... Nd5 $6 {in view of} 18. e6 $1 fxe6 {black are obligated to take with the pawn.} (18... Qxe6 $2 19. Ng5 $18 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb3d5]}) 19. Ne5 Qe8 20. h4 $36 {White's initiative is quite unpleasant.}) 18. Ba5 Ng7 $1 {[%cal Gg7f5]} 19. d5 b6 20. Bb4 Bb7 21. Nd4 Rad8 {[%csl Rd5] Black managed to get a nice counterplay. The game is equal. For example:} 22. Qa3 ({Or} 22. Nc6 Bxc6 23. dxc6 Qc7 $11) 22... Bxd5 23. Bxd5 Qxd5 24. Nc6 Nf5 25. Nxe7+ Nxe7 26. Bxe7 $11 {With an equal game.}) 7... Na5 8. b3 {The point of White's idea is to develop the knight before casting.} ({White has a couple of other moves, which are not leading to an advantage:} 8. Nd2 c6 $1 {Now Black can play without c5.} 9. O-O cxd5 10. cxd5 Bd7 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga8c8] Definitely Black is having a good play on the queen's side.} 11. Nb3 b5 $132) (8. Qd3 c5 9. O-O {This position occurred many times in the practice.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Soon or later Black must push b5.} 10. Nd2 ({In case of:} 10. e4 Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 11. Bf4 b5 12. b3 {Black is doing great after:} bxc4 13. bxc4 Rb4 14. Nd2 Ng4 $132 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gg4e5] With a very nice piece play.}) 10... b5 $5 {The most direct approach.} 