ove.} ({Here very interesting is:} 11. a4 $5 {White prevents b5 for now, but in some lines, the pawn on b3 can be a weakness.} e5 {I am convinced that closing the position is the best plan.} ({A little bit worse for Black is:} 11... e6 12. Nd2 exd5 13. Nxd5 ({After:} 13. cxd5 b5 14. axb5 axb5 15. e3 b4 16. Ne2 Ra8 $13 {[%cal Gc8a6] Black has a decent counterplay on the queen's side.}) 13... Nxd5 14. Bxg7 Ne3 {A nice trick, but not enough for full equality.} 15. fxe3 Kxg7 16. Ne4 Qe7 17. Qd2 b6 18. Rad1 {[%csl Rd6] White will win the pawn on d6.} Qe5 19. Qxd6 Qxd6 20. Nxd6 Be6 ({Black is just lost after:} 20... Nxb3 $2 21. Nxc8 Rbxc8 22. Rd7 $18 {[%cal Gg2d5]}) 21. Rd3 Rfd8 22. Kf2 Rd7 23. Rfd1 $14 {Probably will be not easy to win, but definitely White is pressing.}) 12. e4 ({Harmless is:} 12. dxe6 Bxe6 13. Ng5 Bf5 14. Ra2 Re8 $11 {[%csl Rb3] Black seems to be fine here.}) 12... Bh6 $5 {A typical move in this situation.} ({Probably also not so bad is:} 12... Bd7) 13. Qc2 b6 14. Bc1 {Soon or later White will need to exchange those bishops.} Bxc1 15. Raxc1 Nh5 16. Rb1 Bd7 $11 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gd8e7] The knight on a5 is out of the game, but also the pawn on b3 is a permanent weakness. Black's plan is very easy: Qe7-Rbe8 and push f5 at the right moment.}) 11... b5 12. Qc1 $5 {A very rare move, but I am sure this is the latest trend. Already played by some strong players, and also is the top suggestion of the strongest engines. The point is that in some lines the move Bf5 will be not so strong with the queen on c instead of the queen on c2.} ({Another big move is:} 12. Rb1 Bh6 $1 {Clealry the best move. The positions are a bit dangerous for Black, but the game is very dynamic, and White also must play accurate.} 13. Ba1 Bxd2 14. Qxd2 bxc4 {Black took a pawn, and hopes that the bishop on a will be not so dangerous.} 15. bxc4 ({Only a draw is:} 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 cxb3 17. Qh6 f6 18. Bxg6 hxg6 19. Qxg6+ Kh8 20. Qh6+ $11 {With a perpetual check.}) 15... Nxc4 16. Qf4 ({Or} 16. Qd3 Ne5 17. Qe3 Nc4 $11 {With a repetition of the moves.}) 16... Rxb1 17. Nxb1 ({Worse is:} 17. Rxb1 $6 {because of} Na3 $1 18. Rc1 Nb5 $132) 17... Nb6 {[%csl Rd5]} 18. e4 {The most logical move, but White has also other moves. For example:} (18. Rd1 Qd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7a4,Gd7f5] A nice move. Returning the pawn up, but definitely equalizing the game.} 19. Bxf6 {hite has nothing better now.} exf6 20. Qxf6 Qd8 21. Qxd8 Rxd8 $11 {With an equal endgame.}) (18. Qh6 e5 19. dxe6 fxe6 20. Rd1 d5 21. Qe3 Qe7 22. Nd2 Nbd7 $11 {White has compensation for the pawn, but nithing more.}) 18... Qc7 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7b5] The point of this move is to prepare the nice manoeuvre Bd7-b5.} 19. Nd2 (19. Bxf6 {Looks equal after:} exf6 20. Qxf6 Re8 21. Nd2 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7b5]}) 19... Ng4 $5 {[%cal Gg4e5] Looking for some counterplay.} ({After:} 19... Bd7 20. h3 Bb5 21. Rc1 $44 {The position is very complex, but somehow is difficult to find a useful plan for Black.}) 20. h3 ({Or} 20. Rc1 f6 {[%cal Gg4e5]}) 20... Ne5 21. Qe3 {[%cal Gf2f4] Prepares f4.} f6 22. f4 (22. Rc1 {Prevents Nc4.} Bd7 23. f4 Nf7 {Black's position is very solid. Now after} 24. g4 {very strong is} g5 $1 25. fxg5 Nxg5 26. h4 Nf7 27. g5 Ne5 $132 {[%csl Ge5] Black definitely has his chances here.}) 22... Nbc4 23. Nxc4 Nxc4 24. Qd3 Nb6 25. Kh2 $44 {Of course White has full compensation, but Black also has his play. For example:} Na4 $5 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gc4c3] Looking for some counterplay.} 26. Qe3 c4 27. Rc1 Bd7 28. e5 Bb5 {The game is very dynamic. Now after:} 29. Bd4 c3 30. Bxc3 Nxc3 31. Rxc3 Qb8 {The position seems very close to being completely equal.} 32. exf6 exf6 33. Qd4 Rf7 34. Qb4 Qd8 35. a4 Be8 $11 {Black is a bit passive,but very solid.}) (12. Qc2 {The main theoretical move.} e5 $1 {Clearly the best move in my opinion.} ({The old theory is:} 12... bxc4 $6 13. bxc4 Bh6 {but now after:} 14. Ncb1 $1 {[%cal Gb2c3] The theory proved that White has the advantage.}) 13. Rae1 {One of the main moves.} (13. dxe6 {Another main option for White.} Bxe6 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Nce4 {Here Black equalizes with} Bf5 $1 16. Nxf6+ ({Or} 16. Qc3 Ne8 $1) 16... Bxf6 17. Ne4 Bxe4 18. Bxe4 Rb6 $11 {The position is very balanced.}) (13. e3 {This move is very similar to the main move.} Ne8 $5 {[%cal Gf7f5] The most simple solution here. Black just wants to push f5 next.} 14. Rae1 f5 15. Nd1 Qe7 $11 {The position is very closed, and looks like neither of the sides can make big progress.}) (13. e4 {Here very good for Black is} Bh6 $1 14. Bc1 Bd7 15. Re1 Nh5 $132 {[%cal Gf7f5] With a nice counterplay.}) (13. Nd1 {With the rook still on a1 this move makes less sense.} Bd7 14. Kh1 h5 $13 {With a very complex game.}) 13... Nh5 ({SImilar is:} 13... Bh6 $5 14. Bc1 Nh5) 14. Nd1 ({Or} 14. e3 f5) 14... f5 15. e3 Nb7 $11 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gc8d7,Gb7d8,Gd8f7] The game is very closed and balanced.}) 12... Re8 $5 $146 {A very interesting improvement. The point is to wait for the White's response and to prepare e5.} (12... e5 {The point of 12.Qc1 is that now after} 13. dxe6 $1 Bxe6 ({Or} 13... fxe6 14. Rb1 $14) 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Nce4 Bf5 {White's queen is not attacked, and White can simply continue with} 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. h3 {[%cal Gg3g4]} Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Re8 19. Rfe1 $14 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7] With a small,but very stable advantage for White.}) ({Worse are:} 12... bxc4 $6 13. bxc4 Rb4 14. Nd1 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Rb4][%cal Gb2c3] White is much better.}) ({or} 12... Bh6 $6 13. e3) 13. Re1 {A good prophylactic.} ({In case of} 13. Rb1 e5 14. dxe6 Bxe6 15. Nd5 {The only way to keep fighting for the advantage.} (15. cxb5 {Now this is not a good idea, because of the rook on b1.} axb5 16. Nde4 ({Or} 16. Nce4 $6 Bf5 $132 {[%csl Rb1]}) 16... Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Bf5 {[%cal Gf5b1] Black will exchange a lot of pieces.} 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qf4 Rb6 20. Rbd1 Bxe4 21. Bxe4 Qf6 $11 {The game is very equal.}) 15... Bf5 ({The alternative is:} 15... Bxd5 $5 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Bxd5 Rxe2 18. Ne4 Qe5 $1 {The only move to keep the balance.} 19. Qa3 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ga3a5] Provokes some actions from Black.} ({Very unclear is:} 19. Re1 Rxa2 $13 {With the idea after} 20. Bxf7+ {to just play} Kh8) 19... Rxe4 $1 20. Bxe4 Qxe4 21. Qxa5 Bd4 {[%csl Gd4] This powerful bishop completely compensates for the exchange down.} 22. Qc7 Re8 23. cxb5 ({Or} 23. Qxd6 b4) 23... axb5 24. Qxd6 b4 $44 {Black has enough compensation.}) 16. e4 Bd7 17. f4 ({In case of} 17. Qc3 {Black has} Nh5 $1) 17... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4] Finally the knight comes into the game again.} 18. Bxf6 ({If} 18. cxb5 {then} Nd4 $1) 18... Bxf6 19. Nxf6+ Qxf6 20. e5 {[%cal Gd2e4]} Qd8 $1 {A necessary move.} 21. Ne4 Nd4 22. Rb2 dxe5 23. Nd6 bxc4 {Black still must play accurate.} 24. fxe5 Be6 {Black is happy to give up an exchange.} 25. Nxe8 Qxe8 26. bxc4 Rxb2 27. Qxb2 Bxc4 28. Rb1 Kg7 $44 {[%csl Gd4,Re5][%cal Ge8e5] It is clear that Black has more than enough compensation.}) 13... e5 14. dxe6 ({Unclear is:} 14. Nd1 h5 $13) 14... Bxe6 15. Nd5 {A very critical line, where if Black knows what to do, White also must be very careful.} ({In case of} 15. Nce4 Bf5 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {Black has no problems. For example:} 17. Bc3 ({Or} 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Bd5 bxc4 19. Nxc4 Nxc4 20. Qxc4 a5 $11 {With an equal chances.}) 17... bxc4 18. bxc4 Rc8 19. Qb2 Bxc3 20. Qxc3 Nc6 $11 {The game is level.}) 15... bxc4 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Ne4 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 cxb3 $1 {The whole point. Suddenly the game becomes extremely sharp.} 19. Nf6+ Kf8 20. Nxh7+ Kg8 21. Nf6+ Kf8 22. Nxe8 ({Of course White can continue with the checks.} 22. Nh7+ $11) (22. Nd5 {Leads to equality after:} Bxd5 23. Bxd5 Qg5 $1 24. e4 Qe5 25. Qxe5 dxe5 26. axb3 Nxb3 27. Rxa6 Nd4 $11 {Black is out of danger.}) 22... bxa2 $1 {The key move.} 23. Qh8+ Ke7 24. Bh3 Bb3 $1 {[%csl Ga2,Gb3] It is very important to keep the bishop and the strong a2 pawn.} 25. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] Looking for some way to attack black's king.} Qxe8 26. Qh4+ g5 $1 {The only defense.} ({The rest of the moves are just bad:} 26... Kf8 $2 27. e5 $18) (26... f6 $2 27. e5 $18) 27. Qxg5+ f6 28. Qh4 Qh8 {The endgame is in Black's favour.} 29. Qg4 Rb7 $1 {[%csl Rd7] A very calm and strong move. Just prevents Qd7+.} 30. f4 {[%cal Ge4e5]} ({Or} 30. Bg2 Rb6) 30... Nc6 31. e5 dxe5 32. Bg2 Rb6 33. Bxc6 Rxc6 34. Qf3 Rb6 35. fxe5 fxe5 36. Qc3 Kd6 $132 {[%csl Ga2,Gb3] The position is insane, but it seems that Black is in control.}) 6... Nc6 7. Nc3 {The main move.} ({Here also possible is:} 7. d5 Na5 {Now it is a bit different compared with the line with 6.Nc3. White cannot play b3 now.} 8. Na3 (8. Nbd2 {Looks harmless.} b5 $5 {An interesting way to play.} ({Also normal is:} 8... c5) 9. Nd4 ({Or} 9. cxb5 Nxd5 10. Nd4 e6 $132) 9... Nxc4 10. Nxc4 ({Or:} 10. Nc6 Qe8) (10. Nxb5 Nb6 $11) 10... bxc4 11. Qa4 a5 12. Qxc4 Ba6 13. Qa4 Qe8 14. Nc6 e6 15. dxe6 fxe6 $11 {Black is having a nice game.}) ({In case of} 8. Nfd2 {good is} c6 $1 $132 {[%cal Gc6d5,Gc8d7,Ga8c8]}) (8. Qa4 {A quite possible line.} c5 9. Bd2 b6 {The only way to defend the knight.} 10. Bc3 e6 {I prefer this move.} ({Also to an unclear position leads.} 10... Bd7 $5 11. Qc2 Nxc4 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Qxc4 Bxb2 14. Nbd2 Bxa1 15. Rxa1 b5 $13 {With a very sharp game.}) 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Nbd2 ({Or} 12. Ng5 Bd7) 12... d5 $5 {The easiest way to equalize.} 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. a3 Qe7 16. e4 Nc7 17. Rfe1 Rfd8 $11 {The position is approximately equal.}) 8... c5 9. Re1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} ({Or} 9. Nd2 a6 10. Rb1 Rb8 11. b3 b5 12. e4 Bd7 $11 {[%csl Ra3] Black has enough counterplay on both sides.}) 9... e6 $1 {Now Black must open the centre.} ({Worse is:} 9... a6 $6 10. e4) 10. e4 Re8 11. Bf4 exd5 12. exd5 Rxe1+ 13. Qxe1 {This is a strange Benoni with the knights on a5 and a3.} b6 {The most simple move.} ({Also an option is:} 13... a6 $5 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Qxa5 b6 16. Qd2 Ra7 $44 {[%cal Ga7e7] I believe Black is not worse here. The black squared bishop is too strong.}) 14. Qd2 Qf8 15. Re1 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8e8] Black should be fine.}) 7... e5 $5 {A very popular line in the last couple of years. Always the move 7...a6 was considered to be the main, nowadays definitely 7...e5 is taking over. I believe Objectively Black has a very good chance to equalize and to have a good chance to fight for the advantage.} ({The alternatives are:} 7... a6) (7... Rb8) (7... Bf5) 8. dxe5 {One of the most principled continuations.} (8. Be3 {A rare,but possible move.} exd4 ({White is a bit better after:} 8... Ng4 9. Bg5 f6 10. Bc1 $14) 9. Nxd4 Ng4 $1 {The best way to equalzie the game.} 10. Nxc6 {Next couple of moves are completely forced.} Nxe3 11. Nxd8 Nxd1 12. Rfxd1 Rxd8 13. Nd5 ({Also equal is:} 13. c5 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Kf8 $11) 13... Rd7 {A bit passive, but good enough for equality.} ({Also an option is:} 13... Bg4 $5 14. Nxc7 Rac8 15. Nd5 Re8 {[%csl Rc4,Re2]}) 14. Bh3 {The only way to create some problems.} f5 15. e4 c6 16. Nc3 Rf7 {With a couple of accurate moves Black will level the game.} 17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Bxf5 Rxf5 19. Rxd6 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Re8 21. Kf1 Kf7 $11 {[%csl Ra2,Rc3,Rc4][%cal Gf5c5,Gc5a5] Black is a pawn down,but the endgame is equal. White has too many weaknesses on the queen's side.}) (8. e3 {A passive way to play. This is a bit strange with the knight on f3 and not being on e2.} Rb8 $5 {A strange but good move. The point is to protect the pawn on b7 in some lines.} ({More popular are:} 8... Bf5) (8... a5) 9. d5 ({The alternatives also do not bring the advantage. For example:} 9. b3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1,Gg7a1]} 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 exd4 12. exd4 Nxd4 $1 {A nice tactical shot. This move is possible thanks to the diagonal a1-h8.} 13. Qxd4 Nd7 14. Qe3 ({Or} 14. Qd2 Qf6 {[%csl Rc3,Rf3]} 15. Bb2 Qxf3 16. Nd5 c6 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Nf4 Rbd8 $11 {The endgame is quite equal.}) 14... Re8 15. Be4 {There is nothing better.} Bxc3 ({Also interesting is:} 15... Nf6 $5) 16. Qxc3 Rxe4 17. Bb2 f6 18. Rae1 {White has compensation, but only for equality. The game now can continue:} Re7 $5 19. Rxe7 Qxe7 20. Qa5 b6 21. Qxa7 Qd8 {[%cal Gb8a8]} 22. Re1 Ra8 23. Qb7 Rxa2 24. Qd5+ Kf8 $11 {Black seems to be out of danger.}) (9. h3 {Stopping all plans connected with Bg4.} Re8 10. b3 {A typical way to develop the pieces.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Prepares b5.} 11. Bb2 exd4 12. exd4 ({Very equal is:} 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Ne4 14. Qd3 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Bf5 16. Qd2 Bxc3 17. Qxc3 Qd7 18. Kh2 Be4 $11 {Black simply has equalized.}) 12... b5 13. d5 Ne7 14. Nd2 Bd7 $11 {The game is complex, but it seems that Black is doing fine.}) 9... e4 $1 {An important move here.} 10. dxc6 ({In case of:} 10. Nd2 Ne5 11. Ncxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Bg4 13. Qc2 c6 $44 {Black has  excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 10... exf3 11. Qxf3 ({The alternative is:} 11. Bxf3 bxc6 12. Bxc6 Ng4 $1 {[%cal Gg4e5] Black has a nice piece play. It seems that the compensation is more than enough.} 13. Bg2 ({Or} 13. Qc2 Bf5 14. Be4 Bxe4 15. Nxe4 Re8 16. Rb1 d5 $44 {Black is doing very well.}) 13... Bxc3 $5 {An interesting and thematic way to play.} ({Also possible is:} 13... Ne5) 14. bxc3 Ne5 15. e4 Re8 16. Bh6 Bg4 17. f3 Be6 $11 {[%csl Rc4] Black has a good game.}) 11... Bg4 12. Qf4 bxc6 13. b3 ({Worse is:} 13. Bxc6 $6 {in view of} h5 $1 14. Bg2 Nd7 $15 {[%csl Rf4] White should be careful here.}) 13... c5 14. Bb2 Bd7 $11 {The game looks level.}) (8. h3 {Another way to play, which looks not so promising for White.} exd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Be6 11. Qd3 ({In case of} 11. Qh4 {interesting is} Nh5 $5 12. Bg5 ({The endgame after:} 12. Qxd8 Raxd8 13. Bg5 Bf6 $11 {Looks approximately equal.}) 12... f6 13. Bd2 f5 14. Qxd8 Raxd8 15. Rac1 c6 16. b3 Be5 $11 {Black's position is very solid.}) 11... a5 $5 $146 {An interesting improvement.} ({There is nothing wrong with the other moves as well:} 11... c6) (11... Nd7) 12. Be3 Bf5 13. Qd2 Re8 {[%cal Gf6e4] Black simply wants to exchange a lot of pieces by playing Ne4 next.} 14. Bd4 Ne4 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qd4+ Qf6 18. Qxf6+ Kxf6 19. f3 Bc6 20. Kf2 Re5 $11 {The endgame is just equal. Black has zero problems.}) (8. d5 {The other main move. This move leads to very closed and complex positions, where definitely White also must be careful.} Nb8 9. e4 {The most logical continuation after 8.d5.} ({The alternative is:} 9. c5 Na6 10. cxd6 cxd6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ga8c8] This position looks very playable for both sides. Black's plan is to start playing on the queen's side by Bd7-Rc8.} 11. Nd2 ({Similar is:} 11. a4 Bd7) 11... Bd7 12. a4 Rc8 13. Nb3 ({Another option is:} 13. Qb3 b6 14. Qa3 Ne8 15. b4 {This position looks very double-edged. I actually like Black's chances here.} e4 16. Bb2 f5 17. Rfc1 h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} 18. e3 h4 19. Ne2 Bxb2 20. Qxb2 Qf6 $11 {Black seems to be fine.}) 13... Ne8 14. Be3 {This position occurred in the game Kuzubov, Y (2643)-Onischuk, V (2633) Chess. com INT 2020. Here Black could have played} b6 15. Nb5 ({If} 15. a5 {then} Nc5) 15... Ra8 $1 {Black must play this.} 16. Nd2 f5 17. Nc4 Qe7 $11 {The game is very complex, but Black is doing very fine.}) 9... a5 {[%cal Gb8a6] A very natural move, preparing Na6.} 10. b3 $5 {[%cal Ga2a3,Ga1b1] A bit rare move, but in my opinion, this is the best way for White to fight for the advantage. White wants immediately to push a3-b4.} ({More popular are:} 10. h3 {[%cal Gc1e3] The idea of this move is to place the bishop on e3.} Na6 11. Be3 Nc5 12. Qc2 ({In case of} 12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. Nxe5 {Black is doing great after:} Nxe4 $1 14. Nxe4 Bxe5 15. Nxc5 b6 16. Na4 ({Or} 16. Nd3 Bd6 $44 {[%cal Gd8f6]}) 16... Bd7 17. Nc3 Qf6 18. Qd2 Rae8 $44 {[%csl Ge5] Black has excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 12... b6 {Already is good to prevent Bxc5.} 13. Rae1 Nh5 {[%cal Gf7f5] Black is ready to push f5 next.} 14. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} a4 $1 {A very typical pawn sacrifice. It is important to not allow b2-b4.} 15. Bxc5 bxc5 16. Nxa4 f5 17. Nc3 Bh6 18. a4 Nf6 $44 {Black has a very nice counterplay on both sides.}) (10. Ne1 {[%cal Ge1d3] The most played move, and the most typical plan.} Na6 11. Nd3 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gf7f5,Ga6c5] Black prepares f5 and Nac5.} 12. Be3 ({Another move is:} 12. a3 Nac5 13. Nxc5 Nxc5 14. Rb1 a4 {A very logical response.} ({Also good is:} 14... f5 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 fxe4 18. Be3 Bf5 $11 {I don't think Black can be worse here.}) 15. Be3 Bd7 16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. b4 axb3 18. Qxb3 Bc8 $11 {The game is quite level.}) ({Just bad is:} 12. f4 $2 {in view of} exf4 13. gxf4 f5 $17 {Black is clearly better.}) 12... f5 ({Also good are:} 12... Ndc5) (12... b6 $5 {[%cal Gd7c5]}) 13. Qd2 b6 {[%cal Gd7c5] Prepares to jump with some of the knights on c5.} 14. Kh1 Ndc5 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16. exf5 gxf5 17. f4 e4 18. Rg1 h5 19. Nb5 Ba6 $11 {The chances are equal.}) 10... Na6 11. Rb1 Nc5 12. Re1 Bd7 13. a3 ({White can also start with} 13. Qc2 Qe7 14. a3 a4 $1 {In this setup almost always after a3 Black is reacting with a4.} 15. b4 Nb3 16. Bb2 h5 {[%cal Gf6h7,Gf7f5] It is a very double-edged position. Black must create counterplay on the king's side.} 17. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2c1] White must exchange this knight from b3.} Nh7 18. Nc1 f5 $1 {The best decision. Black is even ready to sacrifice a pawn, but to take the initiative.} 19. Nxb3 axb3 20. Qxb3 Qf7 $44 {[%cal Gf7f2,Gf5e4,Gg6g5,Gg5g4] Black definitely has a lot of play now.}) 13... a4 $1 {A very important motif.} 14. b4 Nb3 15. Bb2 Bh6 16. Qc2 (16. Na2 {[%cal Ga2c1] This move was played in the game Ding, L (2778)-Grischuk, A (2747) Wenzhou 2016 Hereafter:} Bg4 $1 17. h3 Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Nd7 19. Qd3 f5 20. Rbd1 Qf6 $132 {Black could have an excellent counter-chances.}) ({Another move is:} 16. Qe2 Bg4 17. Rbd1 Qd7 ({Worse is:} 17... Nd4 $6 18. Qd3) 18. Qc2 Nh5 19. c5 f5 $132 {With a very double-edged position.}) 16... b6 {Already prevents c4-c5.} 17. Nb5 Ne8 18. Rbd1 f6 $13 {A bit awkward move, the point is to prevent some strikes on the e5 square. The game is extremely double-edged.}) 8... dxe5 ({A bit worse, in my opinion, is:} 8... Nxe5 9. b3 $5 $14) 9. Bg5 {The best move.} ({The alternatives are less dangerous for Black:} 9. Qb3 Nd4 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Rd1 Ng4 $132 {Black is doing very well.}) (9. Qa4 Bd7 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Rfd1 Rfd8 $132 {Black has an excellent game.}) (9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. Bg5 Be6 ({Here also good is:} 10... e4 11. Nd2 h6 12. Bxf6 Rxd2 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Bxe4 Rxb2 $11 {With equal endgame.}) 11. Nd2 h6 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. cxd5 Ne7 15. e4 c6 $11 {The endgame is very level.}) (9. Be3 $5 {This move gains some popularity lately.} Bf5 $5 {[%cal Gf6e4] A bit rare, but I believe a good move.} ({More popular is:} 9... Be6 10. Qa4) 10. Nd2 ({In case of} 10. h3 {good is} Ne4 11. Nd5 ({Or} 11. Nb5 Qe7 12. Nh4 a6 13. Nxf5 gxf5 14. Nc3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 e4 16. Qd5 Qf6 $11 {[%csl Rc3,Rg2] Black is doing very well here.}) 11... Re8 $5 {A quiet and a good move.} 12. Nh4 ({Or} 12. b4 Nd6) 12... Nd4 $1 13. Nxf5 gxf5 14. g4 Nd6 $1 15. c5 Nc4 $132 {Black has a lot of initiative.}) ({Or} 10. Rc1 Re8 $11 {Black is fine in the game Rukavina,J-Huebner,R Leningrad 1973.}) 10... Qc8 11. Nd5 h5 12. Rc1 Bh3 13. Nf3 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Re8 $11 {Black has no problems at all.}) 9... h6 $5 {The modern approach. I believe this leads to an easy position for Black.} ({The main theoretical move is:} 9... Be6) 10. Qxd8 {Next couple of moves are very forced.} Rxd8 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nd5 Kg7 13. Nxc7 Rb8 {Black lost a pawn but got a pair of bishops and nice control over the black squares.} 14. e4 ({The rest of the moves are less dangerous for Black.} 14. Rad1 e4 15. Nd2 Be5 {[%cal Gf7f5] The easiest way to continue.} ({Also good is:} 15... Bg4 $5 16. Nxe4 Be5 17. f3 Bf5 18. Rxd8 Rxd8 19. Nd5 Bxe4 20. fxe4 Bxb2 21. Rb1 Ba3 22. Rxb7 Na5 $11 {Looks fine for Black.}) 16. Nd5 f5 17. b3 b5 18. e3 Be6 $11 {Black is not worse at all.}) (14. Nd5 e4 15. Nd2 Bxb2 ({Interesting is:} 15... e3 $5) 16. Rab1 Ba3 17. Bxe4 ({Or} 17. Nxe4 Ne5 18. Ne3 b6 19. c5 Ba6 $44) 17... Bg4 $5 $146 {A good improvement.} ({There is nothing wrong with} 17... Ne5 $44 {Petrov,J (2403)-Zufic,M (2366) Mali Losinj 2021.}) 18. f3 ({Or} 18. Nf3 Re8 19. Bd3 b6 $44 {[%cal Ga3c5] Black has excellent compensation.}) 18... Bd7 19. Rfd1 b6 $44 {Black has  good compensation for the pawn.}) 14... Be7 {[%cal Ge7c5] The most played move in this position.} ({Black has several good alternatives. For example:} 14... Bg4 $5 15. Nd5 b5 16. c5 ({Or} 16. cxb5 Rxb5 17. b3 {Oparin,G (2655)-Mamedov,R (2654) Lichess.org INT 2021. Now after:} Nd4 $1 18. Nxd4 exd4 19. f3 Be6 20. Nxf6 Kxf6 $11 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ga7a5] Black should be able to equalize completely.}) 16... a5 17. Rac1 Rbc8 $44 {Black's compensation should be enough for equality.}) (14... g5 $5 {A bit strange, but a possible move.} 15. Nd5 Be6 $44) 15. Nd5 ({Or} 15. Rfd1 Be6 {[%cal Ge7c5]}) 15... Bc5 16. Rfd1 Be6 ({SImilar is:} 16... a5) 17. b3 ({If} 17. Ne1 {then} a5 18. Nd3 Bd4 $44 {[%csl Gd4]}) 17... a5 $44 {[%csl Gc5,Rd4] Black has an excellent compensation for the pawn, thanks to the strong black squared bishop..Giri,A (2780)-Dubov,D (2710) chess24.com INT 2021} *

