{[%evp 0,48,27,24,27,-16,60,-9,35,30,32,37,34,30,30,34,51,20,42,69,57,46,164,137,165,138,149,148,148,116,130,130,100,65,65,72,72,44,66,29,88,72,71,71,127,68,71,66,80,78,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {[%cal Ge2e4] This is one of the most aggressive tries against the Grunfeld and King's Indian defense. If White wants to play the Samisch variation against the Grunfeld, he has to do it on move 3 as 3. Nc3-d5 leads to the Grunfeld. White's idea is to push e4 next.} d5 {Black has other options too, but as a Grunfeld player, the choice is 3...d5.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 {This is one of the main positions and Black can play different plans.} Nc6 $5 {This is a fresh line that doesn't have many games played by strong players. In addition, I believe it's objectively good for Black. We want to play Nc6 immediately as White doesn't have time to castle as we are putting pressure on d4, which means that White should play either d5 or Bb5.} ({The main theory goes:} 7... O-O 8. Qd2 {This is a main position in which Black has 2 options: 8...Nc6 and 8...e5. Black needs to know a lot of theory in order to play these lines. I recommend a rarer move 7... Nc6!? which has fewer games than 7...0-0.} Nc6 (8... e5)) 8. d5 {This is the main theoretical move.} (8. Bb5 $5 O-O 9. Nge2 {This is the best move order. White is keeping an eye on the c4 square and is not playing Bxc6 yet, because if White captures Bxc6?!, it can give Black some tempi and some extra options, for example:} (9. Bxc6 $6 bxc6 10. b3 {Preventing Nc4.} (10. Nge2 $6 Nc4 $15 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gc8a6,Ge7e5] Black's idea is to play Ba6 and push e5 next.}) 10... Ba6 11. Nge2 e5 {[%cal Ga6f1,Gg7a1] Black is doing well and with this move, Black wants to open up the bishops.} 12. dxe5 Qe7 $1 {[%cal Ga8d8] Black could have captured on e5 but with Qe7! Black is playing for an advantage.} 13. f4 Rad8 14. Qc2 Rd3 15. Bf2 Rfd8 16. Rd1 f6 $15 {[%cal Ga6f1,Gg7b2] The idea is to open up some files and diagonals. Black has a very nice initiative.}) 9... e5 $1 10. d5 {This is the principled move.} (10. Bxc6 $6 bxc6 11. dxe5 Nc4 $15) 10... Na5 $1 {This leads to some complications, especially after Bxb6 and b4, which traps the knight, but Black has enough counterplay. I believe the position is still not known well and there aren't many games in it. It's an interesting possibility for Black even to fight for an advantage.} 11. Bxb6 (11. b3 {Is a safe way for White to play. White is not risking but Black is also not worse.} c6 12. dxc6 Nxc6 {This move is simpler than bxc6.} (12... bxc6 {Is also possible.} 13. Bd3) 13. Bxc6 {If White exchanged the queens, Black is fine.} (13. O-O Qe7 {Is similar.}) 13... bxc6 14. O-O Ba6 15. Qc2 Qe7 16. Rfd1 Rfd8 $11 {White has the better pawn structure, but Black has the bishop pair. Additionally, Black's bishop on a6 is very active and c5-c4 is an idea. Black can also choose to trade some pieces with Rxd1 and Rd8. The position is very close to being completely equal.}) (11. Bc5 {This line leads more or less to a forced draw. White is going for the exchange but Black is doing well after the move} c6 $1 12. Bxf8 Qxf8 13. Bd3 {White can open up the lines and take dxc6 first, but that will help Black, so it's better to return Bd3 immediately.} Nac4 14. Bxc4 Nxc4 15. Qb3 Ne3 $1 {We have a nice dark-squared bishop which will come to h6, White has very weak dark squares and can't castle. Black has an obvious compensation.} 16. Kf2 {White also needed to defend g2.} Qc5 17. Kg3 Bh6 $1 (17... Ng4 $6 18. Nd1 $1 {Protecting the f2 and e3 squares.} Nf6 19. Qe3 $16) (17... Qe7 $6 18. h4) 18. h3 {Is similar with h4 but safer.} (18. h4 Bf4+ $1 {The difference with 18.h3, Black can go Bf4!+} 19. Nxf4 exf4+ 20. Kh2 Qe7 $132 {And now the difference with a pawn on h3 and h4 is that now on h4 it's hanging.}) (18. Qa3 Qb6 {White can repeat with Qb3 but there is nothing more for White.}) 18... b5 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4] Black wants to go b4 next. The knight on e3 is strong and the White king is on g3, so Black has compensation.} 19. dxc6 (19. Kh2 b4 20. Rhc1 {For now if Black takes on c3, Rxc3 may be in White's favor, so Black can simply go} Ba6 21. dxc6 Qe7 $132 {Both White knights are under pressure and Qg5 is an idea.}) 19... Bf4+ $1 20. Nxf4 exf4+ 21. Kxf4 (21. Kh2 Qg5 $19 {Threatening moves such as Qxg2, Qg3+ or even Bxh3 sometimes.}) 21... Nc4 $1 {The White king is still in the center and Black has a lot of threats (Qe5 which is mate for example), so Black is okay.} (21... Nxg2+ $6 22. Kg3 Qg5+ 23. Kf2 Qd2+ 24. Ne2 Nf4 25. Qd1 Nd3+ 26. Kg3 Qg5+ 27. Kh2 Qe3 $14) 22. Qxb5 (22. Kg3 Qg5+ 23. Kf2 Qe3+ $11) 22... Qd6+ 23. e5 Qd2+ 24. Kg3 Qg5+ $11) (11. O-O $6 {This is not good for White because of:} c6 12. dxc6 bxc6 13. Bd3 Nbc4 {[%csl Rb2,Re3][%cal Gc4e3,Gc4b2] Black already has a good initiative.} 14. Bxc4 Nxc4 15. Bf2 Bh6 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Rfd1 Ba6 $15) 11... axb6 12. b4 c6 {The knight is trapped but Black has enough counterplay after 12...c6} 13. Bd3 b5 $1 {Threatening Nc4.} 14. bxa5 b4 {Next Black will take on d5 and a5, so Black will have 2 pawns, the bishop pair, and a lot of compensation for the piece. Still, the game will be quite sharp and White also has chances, it's a complicated game ahead.} 15. Nb1 {This is the best way for White to continue, with the idea to bring the knight to d2 eventually.} (15. Na4 Qxa5 16. Nb2 cxd5 17. O-O Be6 $44 {The knight on b2 is not doing anything.} 18. Kh1 (18. Nc1 dxe4 19. fxe4 Qc5+ 20. Kh1 Bh6 21. Nb3 Qc3 $44 {White has some problems with the knight on b2, and also, the bishop from h6 covers the c1 square.}) 18... Rfd8 19. Nc1 dxe4 20. fxe4 Qa3 21. Qe2 Bh6 22. Rb1 Qc3 $44 {White's pieces are passive while Black's pieces are active. Black has a very nice compensation.}) 15... cxd5 16. Nd2 (16. O-O $6 {Leads to a worse version for White.} dxe4 $1 17. fxe4 (17. Bxe4 Qxa5 $15) 17... Bh6 18. Kh1 Be6 $15 {It's tough for White to develop in this position as Nd2 is not possible because the bishop on d3 will be hanging. That's why Nd2 first is a better option for White.}) 16... Qxa5 17. O-O {[%cal Gc8e6,Gg7h6,Gf8d8,Gd5e4] It seems like Black's next moves are easier such as Be6 and Bh6. Sometimes Black opens up the position and captures on e4, sometimes Black simply waits like Rfd8, Rac8, and overall, Black has a very nice compensation.} (17. Nb3 $6 Qa7 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ga7g1]} 18. exd5 Rd8 $15 {The king is still in the center and it seems very dangerous for White.}) (17. exd5 b3 $1 18. O-O e4 $1 19. Nxe4 Qxd5 {For now, Black doesn't want to take on a1 as the king on g8 will be very weak.} 20. a4 b2 21. Rb1 Rd8 22. Bb5 (22. Bc4 Qxd1 23. Rfxd1 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Bf5 25. Kf2 Rxa4 26. Rd8+ Bf8 27. Bd3 Ra1 28. N2c3 Rc1 29. Nb1 $11 {Black has 2 pawns for the piece from which the pawn on b2 is very advanced and dangerous, the bishop pair, and White's pieces are passive as they have to defend the promotion square on b1. Black has enough compensation.}) 22... Qxd1 23. Rfxd1 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Be6 $11 {[%csl Gb2] The pawn on b2 is very strong. A potential idea for Black can be Ba2 and overall, Black is doing very well.}) 17... Rd8 18. Nc1 {Seems logical as White wants to bring the queen to e2 and perhaps the knight from c1 to b3.} (18. Nb3 Qa7+ 19. Kh1 dxe4 20. fxe4 Be6 21. Ng1 {Trying to bring the knight to a more active position.} Bh6 22. Qf3 Rdc8 $44 {[%cal Gc8c3]}) 18... Be6 19. Rb1 $1 {Is the best move according to the engines and from all the good moves that White can play, this one seems to be the best move order.} (19. Qe2 dxe4 20. Nxe4 (20. fxe4 $6 Bh6 $15) 20... Qa7+ 21. Kh1 b3 22. a4 Rac8 23. Rb1 Qxa4 24. Qe3 (24. Nd2 $2 {1/2-1/2 (49) Gholami Orimi,M  (2428)-Darini,P (2432) Teheran 2021} e4 $1 {An extremely strong positional move, opening the bishop on g7.} 25. Nxe4 Qa3 $17 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Gb3b2]}) 24... Rd4 $44 {The game is extremely sharp but Black already has 3 pawns for the piece and the b3 pawn is strong.}) (19. Ndb3 Qa7+ 20. Kh1 dxe4 21. fxe4 Rac8 $44 {With ideas such as Rc3 and Bh6.}) (19. Kh1 dxe4 20. Nxe4 (20. fxe4 Bh6 21. Ndb3 Qb6 22. Qf3 Rac8 $44) 20... f5 21. Ng5 (21. Nb3 {Doesn't change much.} Qa7 22. Ng5 Bd5 $44 {[%cal Gh7h6]}) 21... Bd5 22. Rb1 h6 23. Nh3 e4 24. fxe4 fxe4 25. Bc2 Bxa2 26. Nxa2 Rxd1 27. Rfxd1 {Qxa2 is not possible due to Bb3+.} e3 28. Ng1 Re8 29. Nc1 Qb6 $132) 19... h5 $5 {Taking some space on the kingside.} 20. Kh1 (20. Qe2 Bh6 21. Rd1 d4 $1 {This blocks the position and Black gets the e3 square for the bishop.} 22. Bc4 {It's probably a good idea for White to exchange the light-squared bishops.} (22. Ndb3 Qb6 {Now the knight on c1 is very passive.}) 22... Bxc4 23. Qxc4 (23. Nxc4 Qc5 $44) 23... Rdc8 24. Qf1 (24. Qd3 Rc3) (24. Qd5 Be3+ 25. Kh1 Qc7 26. Nd3 Ra5 27. Qb3 Ra3 28. Rbc1 Qxc1 29. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 30. Nxc1 Bxd2 31. Qb2 Bxc1 32. Qxc1 Rxa2 {Black is a queen down for a Rook, but the pawns are very powerful. This compensates for the queen and the position is just a draw.} 33. h4 d3 34. Qc8+ Kg7 35. Qc7 d2 36. Qxe5+ Kh7 37. Qd5 Ra1+ 38. Kh2 d1=Q 39. Qxf7+ $11) 24... Rc2 25. Ndb3 Qd8 $44 {With the rook on c2 and Bh6 active, Black has good compensation.}) (20. exd5 Qxd5 21. Ne4 Qd4+ 22. Kh1 Bh6 23. Be2 (23. Bc2 Qc4) 23... Qxd1 24. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 25. Bxd1 Bxc1 26. Rxc1 Bxa2 27. Nc5 Rc8 28. Kg1 Bd5 {The endgame is approximately equal. I still continued the endgame just to be sure and to show how it can develop further on, but already Black has enough compensation.} 29. h4 (29. Kf2 b6 {Black can also exchange the rooks.} 30. Nd3 Rxc1 31. Nxc1 h4 32. Ke3 Kg7 33. Nb3 Kf6 34. Nd2 Ke6 $11) 29... e4 30. f4 f5 31. Kf2 Kf7 32. Ke3 Ke7 33. Nd3 Rxc1 34. Nxc1 b5 35. Kd4 Kd6 36. Bb3 Bxb3 37. Nxb3 Kc6 $11 {The White king can't enter the Black's camp as the passed pawns are too dangerous and the Black king will also be able to enter on c4 if needed.}) 20... Bh6 21. Qe2 Rac8 22. exd5 (22. Rd1 Kg7 $44) (22. Ndb3 Qb6) 22... Qxd5 23. Ne4 Qd4 24. Bb5 {The idea is to go Nb3 next move.} Bxc1 25. Rfxc1 Rxc1+ 26. Rxc1 Bxa2 27. Nf2 (27. Qxa2 $2 Qd1+) 27... Bd5 28. Rd1 Qb6 $11) (8. e5 $6 Nb4 $15 {[%csl Rc2,Rd5][%cal Gc8f5] Bf5 is coming and we have firm control over the d5 square.}) (8. Nge2 {Defends the d4 pawn but allows} Nc4 {[%csl Rb2,Re3]}) 8... Ne5 9. f4 (9. Rc1 c6 10. Bd4 O-O $11) (9. a4 Nec4 $1 {Black had some options but this is the best move.} 10. Bc1 Na5 $5 {I like this move as it prevents a5, supports c6 and the weaknesses created by the a4 pawn can potentially matter later on.} (10... a5 {Leads to a playable position.} 11. Qb3 Nd6 $13) 11. Qc2 (11. Nge2 c5 $132) 11... c5 {Eventually Black likes to castle and play e6. Also, c4 is an idea that Black can play later on.} 12. Bb5+ (12. Be3 O-O {Black can give up the pawn in order to go Rc8. White will be lacking development and Black will be doing very well.} 13. Bxc5 Bd7 14. Bb5 Rc8 15. Bxb6 axb6 16. Bxd7 Qxd7 17. Nge2 Nc4 $36 {The Bg7 is very strong, so is the knight on c4 and it can jump to e3, so White should be careful.}) 12... Nd7 (12... Bd7 13. f4 $14) 13. f4 (13. Nge2 a6) (13. Be3 a6) 13... O-O 14. Nf3 c4 15. O-O a6 16. Bxd7 Bxd7 17. Be3 b5 18. axb5 axb5 $11 {Black is doing well. Nb3 can be played at some point and the c4 and b5 pawns are an asset.}) (9. Bd4 {White wants to go f4 next.} O-O 10. f4 Ng4 {There are a lot of games here but it seems like Black is equalizing.} 11. Bxg7 (11. h3 $2 e5 $1 {The idea is Qh4+ next.} 12. Bxb6 Qh4+ $1 13. g3 Qxg3+ 14. Kd2 axb6 15. hxg4 Bxg4 16. Qe1 exf4 17. Qxg3 fxg3 $17) (11. Be2 e5 $1 12. fxe5 Nxe5 13. Nf3 Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Qh4+ 15. Bf2 ({If} 15. g3 Qh6 {The point is to take with the queen on g7 in order to have nice control over the e5 square.} 16. Bxg7 Qxg7 $11) 15... Qh6 $11 {With ideas such as Be5, c6, and Bd7.}) (11. Nf3 e5 $1 $146 12. fxe5 (12. dxe6 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 (13. exf7+ Rxf7 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. Nxd4 Rxf4 $11 {Black has the e5 square under control which is a nice outpost that the knight from g4 can go to.}) (13. Nxd4 $2 Ne3 $17) 13... Qxd4 14. Nxd4 fxe6 15. h3 Nh6 (15... e5 {Is also equalizing.} 16. Ndb5 Ne3 17. Nxc7 Rb8 $11 {Black has a lot of counterplay as Nc2 is a threat, f4 is also hanging, but to keep it simple, Black can simply go 15...Nh6.}) 16. Nce2 e5 17. fxe5 Re8 $11 {Black has a comfortable position and can even try to fight for an advantage as after the pawn on e5 falls, the pawn on e4 will be weak.}) 12... Qe7 13. Be2 Nxe5 14. O-O Bd7 $11 {Black has an easy game as there are ideas such as c6 and Rae8 next.}) 11... Kxg7 {There are many moves for White, but in all of the variations Black is doing well.} 12. Nf3 {One of the main moves. This might be the best chance for White to fight for an advantage but Black is still fine.} (12. Qe2 $6 {Maybe the idea is to castle long, but after} e5 $132 {I prefer Black already.}) (12. Qf3 c6 13. h3 (13. dxc6 {This doesn't change much and it's similar.} bxc6 14. Rd1 Qc7) 13... Nf6 14. dxc6 bxc6 15. g4 (15. Rd1 Qc7 16. g4 Be6 $11) 15... h5 $5 (15... Qd4 16. Rd1 Qc5 17. Qf2) 16. g5 Nfd7 $13) (12. h3 Nf6 13. Qd4 $5 (13. g4 e6 14. dxe6 Bxe6 15. Qxd8 Raxd8 {The endgame is pretty safe for Black.} 16. Nf3 Rfe8 17. Kf2 Bd7 18. e5 Nfd5 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 {White has nice pawns on f4 and e5 but they can also be weak. Black is equalizing without much trouble.} 20. Kg3 Bc6 21. Be2 f6 $11) 13... e6 14. O-O-O ({If} 14. g4 $6 {, then} c5 $1 {is strong. Using that the queen on d4 is not protected.} 15. Qxc5 exd5 $15) 14... exd5 15. e5 Ne8 16. Nf3 (16. g4 f6) 16... f6 17. Bd3 Kh8 {The point is the knight to arrive on the e6 square via g7.} 18. Ne4 Qe7 19. Nc5 Nd7 20. Nxd7 Bxd7 21. Qxd5 Bc6 $11) (12. Be2 e5 $1 13. Bxg4 (13. dxe6 Bxe6 $11) 13... Qh4+ 14. g3 Qxg4 15. Qxg4 (15. fxe5 {Black will recover the pawn easily by going Re8 and Nc4 if needed.} Qxd1+ 16. Nxd1 Re8 17. Nf3 Nc4 $11) 15... Bxg4 16. h3 Bd7 17. Nf3 exf4 18. gxf4 Rad8 19. O-O-O Rfe8 $11 {It seems like White has the center but the pawns can also be weak. At some point Black can push c6, and also the h3 is under pressure. The endgame is fine for Black.}) (12. Qd4+ Nf6 13. O-O-O (13. a4 a5 {Doesn't change much.}) (13. Nf3 c6 $1 14. dxc6 Qxd4 15. Nxd4 bxc6 $11) 13... c6 14. h3 (14. dxc6 Qxd4 15. Rxd4 bxc6 16. Nf3 $11) 14... Qc7 15. Qe5 Qxe5 16. fxe5 Nfd7 17. Nf3 {1/2-1/2 (43) Mamedyarov,S (2725) -Kamsky,G (2720) Nalchik 2009} Nc5 $11 {After b4, Black can go Nca4. Black has enough counterplay.}) 12... c6 13. dxc6 bxc6 14. h3 Ne3 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Kf2 Nxf1 17. Rhxf1 c5 18. Rfd1 Be6 19. b3 f6 $11 {The bishop can go to f7 and c4 can be pushed at some point and additionally, a5-a4 is a possible plan. Black has a solid position.}) 9... Ng4 10. Bb5+ {The main try for White.} (10. Bd4 e5 $1 11. fxe5 (11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Bxb6 axb6 13. Qxg4 c6 {Black has this move to avoid being a piece down.} 14. Qe2 cxb5 15. fxe5 b4 $132 {A very complicated game ahead. Black is doing very well as the pawn on e5 will fall and Black has the bishop pair.}) 11... O-O {Black will eventually take on e5.} (11... Nxe5 12. Nf3 Qe7 $11) 12. Nf3 Qe7 $11) 10... c6 $1 {In my book that I wrote a couple of years ago, I already showed the line with 10...c6 and there are already several games on it, however, the move is still rare. It's very concrete and a very sharp line, but it seems that Black is equalizing.} ({Normally Black goes for} 10... Bd7 11. Bd4 Bxd4 12. Qxd4 O-O 13. Bxd7 Qxd7 14. h3 Nf6 15. Nge2 c6 16. a4 $1 Rad8 17. Rd1 $14 {Eventually after cxd5, a5 is coming. White has a nice center and Black will suffer a bit.}) 11. dxc6 O-O 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 {This is a critical position in which White has several moves.} 13. Bxb6 {The main move which I also suggested in my book.} (13. c7 Rf8 14. Bc5 {This move leads to a forced line:} (14. Bxb6 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 axb6 {Transposes to 13.Bb6.}) 14... Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Bd7 $1 16. Bxd7 Nxd7 17. Bxe7 Rfe8 18. Bd8 Rxe4+ 19. Ne2 {The problem for Black is that the pawn on c7 is very unpleasant, but we will take it soon.} Nc5 20. h3 Ne3 21. Kf2 Re8 22. Nd4 Nd5 23. c4 (23. Nb5 a6 24. Rad1 Ne3 25. Na7 Nxd1+ 26. Rxd1 Ne6 27. c8=Q Rxc8 28. Nxc8 Nxd8 29. Nd6 Re7 $11) 23... Nxf4 24. Rab1 Nfe6 25. Nxe6 Rxe6 $11 {The pawn on c7 is dangerous but it's very difficult to promote it. Eventually, we will take that pawn with moves such as Rc8, Rc6, and Ne6. The chances here are equal.}) (13. Bc5 bxc6 14. Bxc6 Rb8 (14... Nc4 $5 {Is an interesting try but there is nothing wrong with Rb8 instead.}) 15. Nge2 Nc4 16. e5 Rxb2 17. Bxe7 Rdd2 {It's clear that Black has enough compensation.} 18. O-O Nge3 19. Rfb1 Bf8 {Black can simply exchange the dark-squared bishops as the bishop on e7 is much stronger.} 20. Bxf8 Kxf8 21. Be4 Ba6 $44 {Black's pieces are very active, so this fully compensates the pawn.}) 13... Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 axb6 15. c7 Rf8 16. Nf3 {This is a bit better than Ne2.} (16. Ne2 Nf6 {Is similar.}) 16... Nf6 17. O-O {White needs to sacrifice the e4 pawn in order to win some time.} Nxe4 18. Rfe1 Nxc3 19. a4 {White sacrificed material and is a pawn down at the moment, but this allowed the c7 pawn to survive and even though White is a pawn down, White is pressing a bit. Now with two accurate moves, Black is equalizing.} Nxb5 20. axb5 Bf5 $1 21. Rac1 (21. Rxa8 Rxa8 22. Rxe7 Kf8 $11 {Black will play Re8 and attack the c7 pawn next. In addition, the Black king is close to the c7 pawn, so Black isn't in any danger here.}) 21... Rfc8 22. Nd4 (22. Rxe7 Kf8) 22... Kf8 23. Nxf5 gxf5 24. Red1 Ke8 $11 {The a8 rook is free to move whether to a5 or a4 in order to attack the White pawns. Black has a solid position and the endgame is equal.} *

