{[%evp 0,26,26,17,40,-14,58,19,29,28,22,-49,-34,-11,-25,-25,10,2,46,21,19,25,4,13,13,-21,0,-23,11]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 c6 {This is the best way to play the system with c6-d5 which I suggest. If Black starts with Bg7, after Bg2, c6 can be met by e4 from White.} 4. Bg2 d5 {This is the Grunfeld approach and it's also easy to learn.} 5. e3 {[%cal Gg1e2] This move is a bit rare. The idea is to bring the knight to e2.} Bg7 ({Black can also start with} 5... dxc4) 6. Ne2 {Now the main move is to take dxc4, but I don't prefer those positions as White can sometimes play with e4 or with b3. It can lead to sharp positions, instead, what I recommend is simpler and it's easy to learn.} O-O (6... dxc4) 7. O-O Re8 $5 {Again, Black could have captured on c4 but I prefer this move. The idea is that Black can play e5 at some point and also Black wants to see what White will do.} 8. b3 {This is probably the best try for White, trying to develop the b1 knight to c3.} (8. Nd2 {This is a bit passive. The knights on d2 and e2 are strangely placed.} Bf5 {[%csl Rd2]} 9. Re1 $6 Nbd7 10. Qb3 e5 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 $15 {½-½ (55) Grandelius,N (2649)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2788) Stavanger 2016}) (8. Nbc3 $6 {Here is a good example of when Black can take on c4 as after:} dxc4 9. e4 e5 $1 {Black is even taking over.} 10. dxe5 Ng4 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. f4 Bf8 $15 {[%cal Gf8c5]}) (8. cxd5 {White can also exchange on d5 but it leads to an equal position.} cxd5 9. Nbc3 Nc6 10. Nf4 e6 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7]}) 8... b5 $5 $146 {Black is putting pressure on the c4 pawn. With the knight on f3, White would have controlled the e5 square and could have jumped Ne5, but now, the knight on e2 is more passive.} ({Black has also tried 8...Bf5 in some games.} 8... Bf5 9. Bb2 (9. Nbc3 Na6) 9... Nbd7 10. Nd2 h5 (10... b5 {here is also possible.} 11. cxb5 cxb5 12. Nf4 e6 13. Qe2 Qa5 $11) 11. Nf4 e6 12. h3 a5 13. a4 Qb6 14. Rc1 Rad8 15. Qe2 Bf8 {Black is solid but it's still probably a bit better for White as the Bf5 is a bit awkwardly placed. White may have some potential ideas to push g4 in the future.} 16. Rfd1 $14 {1/2-1/2 (56) Carlsen,M (2862)-Giri,A (2764) chess24.com INT 2020}) 9. Nd2 {White is trying to protect the pawn on c4.} (9. cxb5 cxb5 10. Nf4 (10. Nbc3 b4 11. Na4 a5 12. Bb2 Nbd7 13. Nf4 e6 14. Qc2 Ba6 15. Rfc1 Qe7 $11 {Eventually a rook will come to c8, the bishop to b5, and maybe even Ne4. Black is doing well here.}) (10. Bb2 a5 $11 {[%cal Gc8a6] With the idea to place the bishop on a6.}) 10... Nc6 11. Nc3 {Looks tempting as White is attacking both pawns but Black can choose an aggressive approach now.} Bg4 $1 12. Qd2 (12. f3 b4 $1 {This was the point.} 13. Ncxd5 Nxd5 14. fxg4 Nc3 15. Qf3 Rc8 $44 {Black is a pawn down but Black's pieces are very active, e5 can also be an idea at some moment.}) 12... e5 $1 {Black sacrifices a pawn, but eventually Black will get it back.} 13. Nfxd5 exd4 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Nd5 dxe3 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. fxe3 Qxa1 18. Bb2 Qxf1+ 19. Kxf1 Rad8 {It's still a very sharp position but Black is fine.} 20. Bd5 {Now Black can choose whether to force a draw with Rxd5 or to continue the game with Be6, which is still approximately equal.} Rxd5 $5 (20... Be6 21. e4 $11) 21. Qxd5 Rd8 {White can't prevent the perpetual check.} 22. Qxc6 Rd1+ 23. Kf2 Rd2+ $11) (9. Nbc3 {This is a natural move but now Black can take the pawn.} bxc4 10. bxc4 Ba6 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Rb1 Nc6 (12... Bc4 $11) 13. Qa4 Na5 $11 {[%cal Ge7e6,Ga8c8] The bishop on a6 is active and eventually Black will play Rc8 and e6.}) 9... bxc4 10. bxc4 Bf5 (10... Nbd7 $5 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ge7e5] This is also possible with the idea to bring the bishop to a6 and to push e5.}) 11. Nc3 (11. Nf4 e6 12. h3 g5 13. Ne2 Bg6 $11 {The bishop on g6 is well-placed and Nbd7 will come next. The game is still very complicated so Black can try to fight for an advantage.}) 11... e6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd8a5]} 12. Bb2 Nbd7 13. Rc1 h5 $11 {Black wants to play Qa5 and Rb8 next. This is an equal position in which Black can also try to play for an advantage.} *

