{[%evp 0,34,40,40,30,-14,39,17,22,21,14,-41,0,-9,1,-7,1,-43,-11,-13,-17,-21,16,10,24,-11,-16,-15,-5,-15,10,5,9,9,11,-22,-11]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 c6 4. Bg2 (4. Qa4 Bg7 5. Bg2 d5 {Transposes to 4.Bg2.}) 4... d5 5. Qa4 {The idea of Qa4 is to take cxd5 and to deny Black the possibility to recapture with the pawn from c6. At some point, this line was popular for White because it's a bit rare, but Black still needs to know how to meet it.} Bg7 {The move Bg7 looks very simple and is my recommendation. Other moves such as 5...a6 or 5...Nfd7 are also good.} (5... a6 {The idea is after cxd5 to go b5.}) (5... Nfd7 {The idea is after cxd5 to go Nb6 and then recapture cxd5.}) 6. cxd5 Nxd5 {Black had to capture on d5 with the knight, but the White queen on a4 is also not well-placed.} (6... O-O {Is also a possible line, but I don't like it so much as Black is fighting for equality, so I prefer Nxd5.}) 7. Nf3 {Now Black can choose from several moves such as 0-0 or Nb6, but I prefer Bg4 which is an interesting idea, trying to put some pressure on the d4 pawn.} Bg4 $5 {Nb6 can be a possible idea for Black, targeting the pawn on d4.} 8. Nbd2 (8. Qd1 $6 Nb6 9. e3 {1/2 (50) Mamedyarov,S (2801)-Grischuk,A (2766)/Saint Louis USA 2018/The Week in Chess 1241 (50)} e5 $1 $15 {The endgame is definitely in Black's favor.}) (8. Nc3 {White is sacrificing the pawn on d4.} Nb6 9. Qb3 {Now the principled way is to take the pawn, but Black can also play Na6, 0-0, and then there is the idea to push c5.} Bxf3 (9... Na6 $5) 10. Bxf3 Qxd4 11. Be3 Qd7 $1 {Now Black is giving up a pawn on b6 but White doesn't really want to take it as the position will be in Black's favor with the strong bishop on g7. The point of Qd7 is after a4 to go Qe6.} (11... Qd8 12. a4 {This will give White a lot of initiative. That's why Qd7! instead of Qd8.}) 12. O-O (12. Rd1 Qc7 13. Bf4 Qc8 $132) (12. a4 Qe6 13. Qxe6 fxe6 14. Ne4 N8d7 $132 {White has compensation but Black is still a pawn up. Nd5 can be an idea and I don't think Black is in any danger here, perhaps Black can be better even.}) 12... Na6 13. Rfd1 Qe6 14. Qxe6 fxe6 15. Ne4 h6 {Preventing any Ng5 jumps.} 16. Rac1 Nd5 (16... Bxb2 $6 17. Rb1 {White will take on b6 next.}) 17. Bd2 Kf7 $132 {It's a sharp endgame where White has compensation, probably enough for equality but not for an advantage. Black has a solid position.}) (8. Ne5 Nb6 9. Qd1 (9. Qb3 Be6 {Is similar.}) (9. Qb4 Be6 {Black maybe has some ideas like Na6 and c5.}) 9... Bxe5 $1 10. dxe5 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 N8d7 (11... Na6 $5 {This move is also possible.}) 12. h3 (12. f4 O-O-O 13. Ke1 f6 $11) 12... Be6 13. f4 O-O-O 14. Kc2 {1/2 (58) Saduakassova,D (2472) -Lagno,K (2560)/St Petersburg RUS 2018/The Week in Chess 1260 (58)} f6 $132) (8. O-O $6 {In other lines it will be seen that the d4 pawn can be sacrificed and White will have some compensation, not in this particular case though.} Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nb6 $15 {[%csl Rd4]}) (8. e3 Nb6 $5 (8... O-O {This move is also good.}) 9. Qc2 Na6 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 (11. h3 Bd7 {With ideas such as Rc8 and c5.}) 11... Re8 $5 {[%cal Ge7e5] With the idea to push e5 is a typical plan in this kind of structure.} (11... Qd7 {Is also possible.}) 12. h3 (12. Rd1 e5 13. dxe5 Qe7 $11 {Eventually Black will get the pawn back.}) (12. Ne4 Bf5 {The pin is unpleasant for White and the idea is to push e5.}) 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 e5 14. dxe5 Qe7 $11 {Black will get the pawn back and play Rad8.}) 8... Nb6 9. Qc2 (9. Qa3 Na6 (9... Bxd4 $6 {The point is that now Bxd4 is not that good anymore as after} 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Nb3 $36 {With a nice initiative for White as Nc5 or Na5 are possible ideas for White, and Qc4 doesn't threaten a queen trade.}) 10. h3 (10. O-O {Here Black can castle but Black can also simply take the pawn.} Bxd4 $5 (10... O-O) 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Bxc6+ (12. Nb3 Qd6 {Now it's a bit different story as Black can go Qd6 and try to exchange the queens.}) (12. Ne4 f6 $132) 12... bxc6 13. Qxa6 O-O $11) (10. e3 Qd6 {Black is threatening c5 or simply to exchange the queens.}) 10... Be6 {Keeping the bishop.} 11. O-O (11. e3 Qd7 $132 {Now it's a bit difficult for White to castle as there is pressure on the h3 pawn.}) 11... Bxd4 (11... O-O $5 {[%cal Gc6c5] Is also possible, but taking the pawn is good enough.}) 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. b3 (13. Nf3 Qb4) 13... f6 {A typical move in these positions.} (13... Qxa1 $2 14. Bb2 Qxf1+ 15. Nxf1 f6 16. g4 $16 {White has a strong bishop pair and Ng3 and f4 are coming. With the weaker king, even though we have the 2 rooks here, the queen is stronger.}) 14. Nf3 Qd7 15. Kh2 Bd5 16. Rd1 Qc7 17. Bb2 Rd8 $132 {White has compensation but needs to be careful as still, a pawn is a pawn, and Black is going to castle next.}) (9. Qb3 $6 Bxd4 $1 (9... Na6) 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Ne4 (11. Nf3 Qc4 {Trading the queens.}) (11. O-O N8d7 {With the idea Nc5.}) 11... Na6 {Threatening Qb4+.} 12. O-O f6 $15) (9. Qd1 $6 {Is similar.} Bxd4 $1 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. O-O Na6 $15) (9. Qa5 O-O (9... Bxd4 $6 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Nb3 Qf6 12. Bh6 $40) (9... Na6 $5 {Is also possible.}) 10. O-O Na6 11. Nb3 Nc4 (11... Re8 $5 12. Qc3) 12. Qc3 Nd6 13. Rd1 Qb6 $11 {With ideas like Rad8 and Nb5.}) 9... O-O (9... Bxd4 $5 {Black can also take the pawn.} 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Nb3 (11. h3 Be6 12. O-O Na6) 11... Qc4 12. Qxc4 Nxc4 13. Nc5 Nd6 14. Bf4 Bc8 {Is a bit passive but good enough.} 15. O-O-O Nd7 $11) (9... Na6 10. Nb3 $14 {The queen on c2 is much better placed than a queen on a5 in comparison.}) 10. h3 (10. O-O Bxd4 $1 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Nb3 (12. e3 Qg7) 12... Qc4 $11) (10. Nb3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Bxd4 $11) (10. e3 Na6 $132 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc6c5]}) 10... Bxf3 $1 {Now Black needs to take the pawn on d4.} (10... Be6 {This is a bit better version for White and Black is a bit worse now.} 11. O-O $14) 11. Nxf3 Bxd4 {White has compensation but Black is doing well.} 12. Nxd4 (12. O-O Bg7 13. Rd1 Qc8 $132) (12. h4 Bg7 13. h5 Qd6 $132 {White doesn't have enough attacking chances. Qb4 will come, while the b8 knight can go to either d7 or a6.}) 12... Qxd4 13. O-O (13. Bh6 Qb4+ {Is unpleasant for White. That's why White should castle first.}) 13... Na6 (13... Qc4 $5 {Is also possible with the idea to exchange the queens.} 14. Qd2 Na6 15. b3 Qb4) 14. Bg5 f6 (14... Qe5 $5) (14... Rfe8 $5) 15. Bh6 Rfd8 16. Rac1 Kf7 {The king is safe on f7, being guarded by the f6 and e7 pawns.} 17. Qb3+ e6 $132 {0-1 (42) Duda, J (2738)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2778)/Baden Baden GER 2019/The Week in Chess 1272  (42)} *

