{[%evp 0,55,30,30,30,-14,36,36,32,8,21,14,14,14,14,14,24,11,43,27,42,-1,24,19,19,21,21,27,17,-12,8,8,8,3,3,3,38,19,21,15,4,0,0,0,0,-13,-2,1,11,13,22,0,0,0,0,0,0,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 c6 5. Bg2 ({White can also start with} 5. Nc3 d5 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. Ne5 O-O 8. Bg2 Bf5 {And this transposes to 5.Bg2.}) 5... d5 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. O-O (7. Nc3 O-O 8. Ne5 {White can also choose this move order and it's a bit different than 7.0-0 as Black can't go Ne4.} Bf5 $5 {[%cal Gf6e4] The idea is to place the knight on e4.} 9. Bf4 $5 (9. Be3 {With the idea to postpone castling, defending the d4 pawn, and maybe wanting to go Qb3 next. Black needs to remember the moves and ideas of going Qb6! and Rd8! and Black is equalizing.} Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rb2] And now there is no comfortable way to defend the b2 pawn, for example, Qc1 doesn't look great as it's standing on the only open file and Black can continue with something like Nc6 and then bringing a rook on the c-file later on.} (9... Nc6 10. O-O {This may be a bit better version for White.}) 10. Rc1 (10. O-O Qxb2 {Black can simply take the pawn and this will turn into an equal position.} 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nc6 14. Qb3 Qxe5 15. Bf3 (15. Bf4 Qf6 16. Rac1 e5 $11) 15... Qc7 16. Rac1 Rfd8 {White has compensation but it's enough to make a draw, Black is not worse.} 17. Bd5 e6 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Qa4 Bh3 $11) (10. Bxd5 Nxd5 (10... Qxb2 $2 {Now this is not good because of} 11. Rc1 $16) 11. Nxd5 Qa5+ 12. Nc3 Nc6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. O-O Rfd8 15. Qa4 Qb6 $11 {Black has enough compensation and sooner or later will return the sacrificed pawn.}) 10... Rd8 $1 {It's important to start with this move. Black is defending the d5 pawn and is still attacking the b2 pawn.} (10... Qxb2 $6 {Would lead to the same position after} 11. Bxd5 {which is better for White.}) (10... Nc6 11. Na4) 11. h3 (11. Qd2 Ne4) (11. O-O Qxb2 {This is not dangerous for Black anymore as the d5 pawn is defended well.}) 11... Qxb2 12. g4 Be6 13. O-O Ne4 {13...Nc6!? is fine but I prefer 13...Ne4 as it's more tricky and Black can also fight for an advantage.} (13... Nc6 $5) 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxe5 16. Rb1 Qxa2 17. Bxb7 Nc6 18. Bxa8 (18. Bxc6 Rac8 19. Bf3 a5 $11) 18... Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Rxd4 20. Qc1 Qxe2 21. Re1 Rxg4+ {Leads to a forced draw.} 22. hxg4 Qxg4+ 23. Bg2 Bd5 24. f3 Bxf3 25. Qd2 Bd4+ 26. Kf1 Bxg2+ 27. Qxg2 Qf4+ 28. Ke2 Qe3+ 29. Kd1 Qd3+ 30. Kc1 Qc3+ $11) (9. Qb3 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} 10. Be3 (10. Nxc6 $6 bxc6 {This is a better version for Black as the queen on b3 is not well-placed.} 11. O-O Nd7 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8b6]}) 10... e6 11. h3 {[%cal Gg3g4]} h5 {Preventing g4.} 12. Qxb7 {If White captures the pawn on b7, the game might end with a repetition of moves.} Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. f4 Rb8 15. Qxa7 Ra8 16. Qd4 (16. Qb7 Rb8 $11) 16... f6 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Qd1 Rb8 $132 {White is 2 pawns up but Black will capture the b2 pawn and there is enough compensation for at least equality.}) (9. O-O {Transposes to 7.0-0.}) 9... Qb6 $1 (9... Nc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. O-O $14 {I don't really like this for Black as simply the pawn structure is a bit worse and Na4 and Rc1 are coming.}) ({If Black plays} 9... Ne4 {now, it can lead to some problems after} 10. Qb3) 10. O-O {This is the main try for White.} (10. Qb3 Nc6 {The endgame is fine for Black.} 11. Qxb6 axb6 12. e3 e6 13. f3 Nh5 $11 {Black is at least not worse. The bishop has the c2 square if it's needed to escape.}) (10. Qd2 Ne4 11. Nxe4 (11. Nxd5 Qd8 12. Qe3 Qxd5 13. g4 e6 $132) 11... Bxe4 12. O-O Bxe5 13. Bxe5 Nc6 $11) (10. g4 Qxb2 11. Rc1 Be6 12. O-O Nc6 13. Nd3 Qb6 {It's even a bit strange that White has compensation as Black has an easy game now.} 14. e3 Bxg4 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Qxg4 Nxf4 17. Qxf4 Rac8 $132 {Thanks to the strong bishop on g2, Nd3, and the central pawn structure that White has, White has enough counterplay to not be worse, but Black is doing well.}) 10... Qxb2 $1 (10... Nc6 {Is worse here due to} 11. Nxc6 bxc6 (11... Qxc6 12. Qb3) 12. Na4 Qb5 13. Rc1 $14) 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Nc6 $1 13. Bxc6 (13. e4 Bh3 {And here White should be very careful.}) (13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bxc6 Rac8 $15 {The pawn on d4 is about to fall.}) 13... Bxe5 $1 (13... bxc6 14. Nxc6 Rfe8 $14) 14. Bxe5 (14. dxe5 bxc6 15. Re1 c5 $11 {1/2 (21) Mchedlishvili,M (2609)-Ragger,M (2658)/Muelheim GER 2014/The Week in Chess 1044 (21)}) 14... bxc6 15. Re1 f6 16. Bc7 Rfc8 17. Ba5 Rab8 (17... c5 {Leads to a slightly worse position for Black because it allows the sequence:} 18. e4 Bh3 19. d5 $14) 18. e4 Bh3 $11) 7... O-O 8. Nc3 (8. Ne5 {Is similar.} Bf5 {[%cal Gf6e4]} (8... Ng4 $5 {Many players have tried this move which is also good, however, Black can simply play Bf5 instead.}) 9. Qb3 (9. Nc3 {Transposes to 8.Nc3.}) 9... Nc6 10. Rd1 Qb6 $11) 8... Ne4 $1 {I prefer to start with this move, because after 8...Bf5 White can play 9.Qb3. In addition, 8...Ne4! equalizes immediately.} 9. Ne5 (9. Bf4 Nc6 10. Rc1 Bf5 $11) (9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Ne5 Qd5 11. Be3 Nd7 12. Qb3 Qxb3 13. axb3 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxe4 a6 $11) (9. Qb3 Nc6 $11 {[%csl Rd4]}) (9. Ng5 Nxc3 10. bxc3 h6 11. Nh3 {White wants to reroute the knight to f4.} Nc6 12. Nf4 e6 13. e4 dxe4 14. Bxe4 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8] The position is objectively equal but Black has the tendency to be better. With the pawn structure being better for Black, Rc8, and ideas such as Ne7 or Na5-Nc4 coming, Black can try to take over.}) (9. Nd2 Nxd2 {Black doesn't need to go back, there is nothing wrong with taking Nxd2.} (9... Nf6 $5 {There are many games that ended in a draw with a repetition.}) 10. Bxd2 e6 11. e3 Nc6 12. Rc1 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8]}) 9... Bf5 10. Bf4 (10. g4 Be6 $1 ({The point of g4 is that if Black takes} 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 (11. e4) 11... Be6 12. f4 $14 {This is slightly better for White.}) 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Bxe4 Nc6 $1 {Black is doing well.} 13. Nxc6 (13. d5 Bxd5 14. Qxd5 Bxe5 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 $11) 13... bxc6 14. Bxc6 (14. e3 Qd7 15. f3 Rac8 16. b4 Bd5 $44 {[%cal Ge7e5] White's king is weak and the White's pawn structure is compromised, so Black has enough compensation for the pawn.}) 14... Rc8 15. Bf3 Qxd4 16. Qxd4 Bxd4 $11 {[%csl Ra2,Rb2,Gd4,Ge6]}) (10. Nxe4 Bxe4 $11) (10. Qb3 Nc6 $1 11. Nxc6 (11. Qxd5 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Qxd5 13. Bxd5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bxe5 $11) (11. Rd1 Nxd4 12. Rxd4 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Bxe5 14. Rxd5 Qc7 $11 {White can become worse easily so White needs to be careful.}) 11... bxc6 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Rd1 Qb6 14. Qxb6 axb6 15. Be3 Rfd8 $11 {0-1 (43) Santos Latasa,J (2582)-Cheparinov,I (2683) Skopje 2019}) 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Nc6 {This is a theoretical position and there are a lot of games, but nobody has proven an advantage for White.} 12. Nxc6 (12. Qb3 e6 {Protecting the d5 pawn, which is much more important than the pawn on b7.} 13. Qxb7 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Qa5 16. Qb4 (16. c4 $2 Rab8 $17 {And eventually Black will capture the pawn on c4.}) 16... Qxb4 17. cxb4 Rfb8 18. a3 a5 19. bxa5 Rxa5 $11 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Gb8a8] 1/2-1/2 (44) Howell,D (2696) -Jones,G (2682) London 2018}) (12. Qa4 Na5 $5 {This is an extra option that Black has in this position.} (12... e6 {Leads to the main line.}) 13. c4 Bxe5 14. dxe5 Nxc4 15. Qb5 Be6 16. Qxb7 Re8 $11 {[%cal Gd8a5]}) 12... bxc6 13. Qa4 e6 14. Qxc6 (14. Rfc1 Qd7 15. e3 Rac8 {Black is fine in this position as it's almost fully symmetrical. The bishop on f5 is good because it controls the b1 square and White can't play Rb1.} 16. c4 Rfd8 17. cxd5 ({If} 17. c5 {Black can always go} Re8 $11 {[%cal Ge6e5] and then e5.}) 17... exd5 18. Rc5 Qe7 $11 {[%cal Gg6g5] Threatening g5 and creating some counterplay.}) 14... Rc8 15. Qa4 Rxc3 16. Rfc1 Qc8 $1 {This is proven to be completely fine for Black, there are also correspondence games with this move, so Black has equalized immediately.} 17. Qxa7 h5 $1 {Giving some space to the king. The idea can be seen after 18.h4.} 18. a4 (18. h4 Rxc1+ {Black can simply trade pieces.} 19. Rxc1 Qa8 20. Qxa8 Rxa8 $11 {[%csl Ra2,Rd4] Both pawns on d4 and a2 are hanging so Black is fine.}) 18... Rxc1+ 19. Rxc1 Qa8 20. Qxa8 Rxa8 21. e4 Bxe4 22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. Rc4 Kf8 24. Kf1 {1/2-1/2 (24) Kruse,H (2506)-Larwinski,P (2506) FICGS email 2021} Ke8 25. Ke2 Bf8 26. Kd2 Kd7 {[%cal Gf8d6]} 27. Rc7+ Ke8 28. Rc4 $11 *

