{[%evp 0,38,30,30,32,5,32,32,31,19,38,14,14,24,11,-12,1,-31,-28,-34,-50,-84,-46,-58,-47,-86,-44,-25,-17,-32,-24,-24,8,8,27,27,17,-58,-38,-55,-8]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 c6 5. Bg2 d5 6. O-O O-O {Here, White has 3 main moves: Qb3, b3, and Nbd2 (which is similar to b3). In this chapter, the rarer moves will be analyzed.} 7. a4 {This move is popular nowadays. After dxc4, White wants to play Na3 in order to put pressure on the c4 pawn.} (7. Na3 {[%csl Ra3] The knight on a3 is misplaced.} Bf5 (7... Qb6 $5 {Is also possible, putting pressure on b2 and not allowing Bf4.}) 8. Bf4 Qb6 9. Qb3 Nbd7 $11) (7. Nc3 {For many years this move wasn't considered as a very good move since Black can capture on c4, but in the last couple of years, it was played by Magnus Carlsen several times. It makes sense as after dxc4 White wants to go e4 with a typical Catalan compensation, but the arising positions are very sharp and Black also has good chances.} dxc4 $1 8. e4 (8. Ne5 $6 Ng4 $1 9. Nxg4 Bxg4 {And now there is no good way to protect the d4 pawn.} 10. d5 cxd5 11. Qxd5 Qxd5 12. Bxd5 Nc6 13. Bxc4 Rac8 $13 {This may be already slightly better for Black as Nd4 is coming.}) (8. a4 $6 {If White starts with a4 instead of e4, it allows:} Nd5 $1 9. e4 Nb4 {[%csl Rd3]} 10. Be3 N8a6 $15) 8... b5 9. Qe2 {This is the most logical way to continue with White, bringing the rook to d1. White wants to play slowly and the next moves can be some Be3, Ne5, maybe even h3 and g4.} (9. e5 $6 {This gives away the d5 square for the Black knight.} Nd5 10. Bg5 Bf5 11. Qd2 b4 12. Na4 {1/2-1/2 (28) Andreikin,D (2724)-Dubov,D (2711) Chess.com INT 2022} Qa5 $17) (9. Re1 a5 $132 {After this White wants to bring the queen to e2 anyway, so it's better for White to start with 9.Qe2.}) 9... a5 (9... b4 $5 {I prefer a5 but this is also possible.} 10. Nd1 (10. Na4 $6 Qa5 {[%csl Ra4]}) 10... Ba6 11. Re1 e6 {1-0 (34) Carlsen,M (2861)-Petrosyan,M (2609) Chess.com INT 2022} 12. e5 Nd5 13. Ne3 c3 14. Qc2 Qa5 $13) 10. Rd1 Nbd7 {The knight is heading for the b6 square.} 11. d5 (11. Bf4 Nb6 12. Ne5 Bb7 $132 {Black is a pawn up and has very good chances to fight for an advantage.}) 11... cxd5 12. e5 b4 $1 {Is the whole point, Black sacrifices a piece.} 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Nb5 e6 $44 {Black has 3 pawns for the piece and a very nice pawn structure.} 15. a4 Ba6 (15... Bd7 $5 {This move is probably better than Ba6.}) 16. Nfd4 Bxb5 17. axb5 a4 $1 (17... Re8 $2 18. b3 $1 cxb3 19. Ra4 Nd7 20. Nxb3 Nb6 21. Rxa5 Rxa5 22. Nxa5 Na4 23. Nc6 Nc3 24. Qd3 Qb6 25. Re1 Qxb5 26. Qxb5 Nxb5 27. Bxd5 $18 {1-0 (35) Carlsen,M (2859)-Mamedyarov,S (2741) chess24.com INT 2022}) 18. Nc6 Qb6 19. Nxb4 Qxb5 20. Bd2 Rad8 $44) (7. Ne5 dxc4 8. Nxc4 (8. Na3 Be6 {This is the easiest for Black, although Ng4 was also possible.} (8... Ng4 $5) 9. Naxc4 (9. Nexc4 Bd5 {It's always good to exchange the light-squared bishops for Black.} 10. f3 Nfd7 $132 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd7b6]}) 9... Nfd7 10. e4 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 c5 {Breaking the center.} 12. d5 Bxe5 13. dxe6 Qxd1 14. exf7+ Kxf7 15. Rxd1 Nc6 16. Bh6 Rfd8 $11 {[%csl Rb2,Ge5] The endgame is a bit more comfortable for Black because the bishop on e5 is very strong, the pawn on b2 is hanging, and d4 is a good square for the knight.}) 8... Be6 9. b3 (9. Ne5 Qc8 $5 {[%cal Gf8d8]} 10. Nc3 Rd8 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5] 1/2-1/2 (30) Van Foreest,J (2671)-Salgado Lopez,I (2593) Los Cancajos 2020}) 9... Bd5 10. Bb2 Na6 11. Nc3 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Nd5 13. Ne4 Qd7 $11 {Black's position is very solid, next move is Rad8.}) (7. Qa4 {It's not clear what the point of Qa4 is. Maybe White wants to provoke dxc4 but Black is going to capture on c4.} Nbd7 $5 (7... Nfd7 {[%cal Gd7b6] This is the main move with the idea 8.cxd5 and then Nb6, but I wouldn't like to put this knight on b6, so simply 7...Nbd7.}) 8. cxd5 Nb6 9. Qb3 (9. Qd1 cxd5 10. b3 (10. Nc3 Ne4 $11) 10... Ne4 11. Bb2 Bf5 12. Nc3 Rc8 13. Rc1 {The knight may seem a bit strange on b6 since it can't jump forward due to the b3 pawn, but Black just wants to exchange some pieces and trades are likely to happen on the c-file.} Qd7 $11 {1/2 (18) Vidit,S (2695)-Shankland,S  (2725)/Wijk aan Zee NED 2019/The Week in Chess 1263 (18)}) (9. Qa3 cxd5 $11) 9... Qxd5 $1 (9... cxd5 10. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gc1f4] This is more pleasant for White since the knight is not well-placed on b6.}) 10. Qb4 (10. Nc3 Qxb3 11. axb3 Be6 $132 {[%csl Rb3] This can become very tricky for White.}) (10. Nbd2 Qxb3 11. Nxb3 a5 12. Nc5 a4 $11) (10. Qd1 Qh5 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gc8h3]}) (10. Qa3 Qd6 $11 {Qd6 can be played, going for the endgame and Black is doing very well.}) 10... Qd6 (10... Qb5 $5 {Is also interesting to play the structure with the pawn on b5, but there is no need for that as Qd6 is good enough.}) 11. Qe1 Bg4 12. Nbd2 {1/2-1/2 (38) Oparin,G (2657)-Xiong,J (2712) Saint Louis 2019} c5 $1 $146 {Black simply wants to open up the position as White's pieces are not ideally placed.} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Nxf3 Nfd5 {[%cal Gg7a1,Gb6c4]} 16. a3 Nc4 17. e4 Ndb6 18. Rb1 Rac8 $11 {White should be a bit more careful here as the bishop on c1 is passive and Black has the more active pieces.}) 7... Be6 $5 {Black also had other good moves but I prefer this move as it puts pressure on the c4 pawn.} (7... a5) (7... Bf5) 8. Nc3 $5 {This may be a bit better version for White than 7.Nc3 as Black can't play b5.} (8. Na3 {[%csl Ra3]} Na6 $11 {The knight on a3 is passive and Black has the b4 square to jump to eventually.}) (8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nc3 (9. Qb3 Nc6 10. Qxb7 Na5 11. Qa6 Ne4 $44 {Only Black can be better here as Black's pieces are more active and there are ideas such as Nb3 or Rc8.}) 9... Nc6 $11 {[%csl Rb4]}) (8. Ng5 Bf5 {This is more ambitious than going back to c8 which is also possible.} (8... Bc8) 9. Nc3 h6 (9... dxc4 10. h3) 10. Nf3 dxc4 11. Ne5 Be6 12. f4 Nbd7 $132 {It's a complicated position but Black is doing well.}) 8... dxc4 9. e4 {This is the best try from White. The idea is that White wants to go Be3, Qe2 and Ne5. There is compensation for the pawn but if Black knows the plans, Black can try to fight for an advantage.} (9. a5 Na6) (9. Ng5 {Here Black can simply retreat to c8.} Bc8) 9... Na6 10. h3 Nb4 11. Be3 Ne8 {[%cal Ge8d6] Bringing the knight to d6, or sometimes even to c7.} 12. Qe2 {1-0 (71) Keymer, V (2693)-Saric,I (2668) chess24.com INT 2022} a5 {This is an interesting move and the rest is an illustrative line of how Black is fighting for an advantage.} 13. Rad1 {White wants to play Ne5 and f4 next.} Rb8 {Supporting b5.} 14. g4 Nc7 15. Ne5 b5 {After axb5, Black should also consider recapturing with the knight on b5.} 16. f4 Bd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7e8] This is a plan given by the computer, but if you know it, it makes a lot of sense.} 17. f5 Be8 {[%cal Gf7f6] The idea is to go f6 and Bf7.} 18. Kh1 f6 19. Nf3 Bf7 $132 {White doesn't have a clear way to improve the position. The bishop on g7 is passive but Black is still a pawn up and there may be some counterplay for Black on the queenside as the b file can open up and the knight can jump to d3.} *

