{[%evp 0,62,30,30,33,-8,32,38,42,19,7,7,31,8,8,-2,7,-16,-22,-8,-9,18,-7,-12,9,8,7,-16,10,-1,5,0,0,28,26,23,13,19,52,52,25,-14,6,-166,72,68,0,0,0,0,0,-2,-25,-13,36,24,47,36,82,74,73,52,34,29,47]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 c6 6. O-O d5 7. b3 {This is one of the main moves for White. The idea of b3 is to play Bb2 and to bring the knight to c3 eventually, so the pawn on c4 is defended. The knight from b1 can also go to d2 in some lines, depending on what is Black doing.} dxc4 $1 {The simplest way for Black, although Black had also other moves to choose from, such as:} (7... a5) (7... Bf5) (7... Ne4) 8. bxc4 c5 {This is the point of dxc4! Black wants to open up the bishop from g7 and damage White's pawn structure.} 9. Bb2 (9. e3 cxd4 (9... Nc6) 10. exd4 Nc6 11. Bb2 Qb6 12. Qe2 Bg4 13. d5 Na5 {e5!? is playable but there is no need to complicate matters unnecessarily.} (13... e5 $5 {Is also interesting, but the idea is after} 14. dxc6 {to go} e4) 14. Na3 e6 $11) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Qb6 {There were other options for Black such as Nc6, but Qb6 is the best move. Black is attacking the bishop on b2 and the next moves can be Rd8 or Bd7 with Nc6.} 11. Qc1 (11. Qc2 {This is not a very popular move.} Rd8 12. c5 Qa6 13. Nd2 (13. a4 Nc6 14. Nb5 {1/2 (40) Laznicka,V (2668)-Deac,B (2501)/Gjakova KOS 2016/The Week in Chess 1124 (40)} Bg4 $1 {Is putting pressure on the e2 pawn, preparing against Nc7.} 15. h3 Bf5 16. e4 Be6 17. Nc7 Qc4 $132) 13... Nc6 14. Nxc6 (14. e3 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bd7 16. Rab1 Bc6 $11) 14... bxc6 15. Nb3 Qa4 {This is important as it pins the knight and doesn't allow the move Nd4.} 16. Rfc1 Be6 $11 {Next is Bd5 or Rab8.} 17. Nd4 Rxd4 $1 18. Qxa4 Rxa4 19. Bxc6 Rb4 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Bxa8 Bxa1 22. Rxa1 Rc4 23. c6 Bd5 24. Rd1 Bxc6 25. Bxc6 Rxc6 26. Rd7 Ra6 $11) (11. Qb3 Nfd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c5] This is important, the knight is heading to c5.} 12. e3 (12. Rd1 Nc5 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. Nc3 Na4 $11 {1/2 (65) Ivanchuk,V (2726)-Wang Hao (2709)/Huai'an CHN 2017/The Week in Chess 1206 (65)}) 12... e5 $1 {Because after 12...Nc6 13.Nc3 White may want to go Nd5.} (12... Nc6 13. Nc3) 13. Nb5 Nc5 14. Qa3 Be6 15. Nd2 (15. Rd1 {Now Black can simply take the pawn.} Bxc4 16. N1c3 (16. Nd6 Rd8) 16... Bxb5 17. Nd5 Qd6 18. Nc3 $11 {And the game can end in a draw with repetition.}) 15... Rd8 16. Bc3 Rd7 $1 (16... Nc6 $6 {Is not very accurate as there is} 17. Rab1 {with better prospects for White.}) 17. Rab1 (17. Ba5 Qa6 18. Qxc5 Qxa5 19. Qc8+ Bf8 20. Nb3 (20. Ne4 $6 Re7 $17) 20... Qb6 21. a4 (21. Nc3 Kg7) 21... Re7 22. a5 Qxb5 {This leads to an approximately equal position.} (22... Qa6 {This is a draw with repetition as the White queen can't escape.} 23. Qd8 Rd7 24. Qc8 Re7 $11) 23. Qxe6 Qxb3 24. Qc8 e4 {Blocks the diagonal for the White bishop.} 25. Rfd1 Kg7 26. Rd8 Nc6 27. Qxa8 Nxd8 28. Qxd8 Qxc4 $11) (17. Bb4 $6 Bf8 $15 {[%cal Ga7a5] Black is simply better here as the pawn structure is also in Black's favor.}) (17. Nb3 Bf8 18. Nxc5 Bxc5 19. Qa4 Nc6 20. Rfb1 Bf5 21. Rb2 Qd8 $11 {White can easily become worse because of the pawn structure.}) 17... Bf5 $1 18. Ba5 (18. Nb3 Bf8 {Is good for Black.}) (18. e4 $6 Bg4 19. f3 Be6 20. Nd4 Qa6 21. Qxa6 Nbxa6 22. Nxe6 Nxe6 $17 {Black is much better due to the control over the central dark squares and the better pawn structure.}) 18... Qa6 19. Qxc5 Qxa5 20. Qc8+ Bf8 (20... Rd8 {May not be so clear after} 21. Nb3) 21. Ne4 (21. Nb3 Qb6) (21. Be4 Be6 {Doesn't change much.} 22. Nb3 Qb6 23. a4 Re7 24. a5 Qa6 25. Qd8 Rd7 $11) 21... Re7 22. Nf6+ $11 Kg7 23. Nh5+ Kg8 24. Nf6+ $11 {1/2 (24) Arutinian,D (2536) -Andersen,M (2605)/Batumi GEO 2018/The Week in Chess 1220}) 11... Bd7 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] Black wants to play Nc6 but also to recapture with the bishop on c6! That's why Bd7.} 12. Nd2 (12. e3 Nc6 13. Na3 (13. Rd1 Rac8) (13. Nd2 {Transposes to 12.Nd2.}) 13... Rac8 $11) (12. c5 Qc7 13. Na3 Nc6 $11 {1/2 (43) Mikhalevski,V (2565)-Guseinov,G (2667)/Porto Carras GRE 2018/The Week in Chess 1249 (43)}) 12... Nc6 {Black's idea is to bring the rook from a8 to c8 and in some way to put the bishop on c6.} 13. Nc2 {This is probably the best try for White. The idea is to bring the knight to e3 and eventually to d5.} (13. c5 Qc7 14. Nc4 Nxd4 (14... Rfd8 {Is also fine for Black.}) 15. Bxd4 Bc6 16. Bxc6 Qxc6 $11 {1/2 (20) Efimenko,Z (2647)-Areshchenko,A (2682)/Lviv UKR 2015/The Week in Chess 1100 (20)}) (13. e3 {Black has several options to choose from:} Rad8 (13... Qc7) (13... Rac8) 14. Bc3 (14. Rb1 Qc7) 14... e5 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Rb1 Qc7 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Qc2 Rfe8 $11) (13. N2b3 {Here Black has several options to choose from:} Nxd4 (13... Rac8 14. Rd1 Rfd8 15. Rb1 Qc7 $11 {1/2 (48) So,W  (2778)-Caruana,F (2816)/Leuven BEL 2018/The Week in Chess 1232 (48)}) (13... Rfd8) 14. Bxd4 Qc7 15. c5 Bc6 16. Bxc6 Qxc6 $11 {1/2 (25) Oparin,G (2613)-Giri, A (2783)/St Petersburg RUS 2018/The Week in Chess 1260 (25)}) 13... Rac8 14. Rb1 Qa6 $5 {This is more aggressive.} (14... Qc7 {Is also good enough.} 15. Ne3 b6 $11) 15. Ne3 Rfd8 16. Bc3 b6 (16... Be6 $5 {This is also interesting, with the idea on} 17. Qb2 {to play} Qa4) 17. Qb2 Qa4 $1 {This is a strong move which equalizes for Black.} (17... Be6 $6 18. Nd5 Ne8 19. Bxg7 Nxg7 20. Rfc1 $16 {Giri,A (2785)-So,W (2815)/chess.com INT 2017}) 18. Rfc1 (18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Bxg7 f6 20. Bh6 Nc5 $132 {The bishop on h6 is not well-placed and Black has counterplay and ideas such as Be6 and Ne5.}) 18... Be6 19. Nd5 Nxd5 20. Bxg7 Nc7 (20... Ndb4 $5 {Is also playable.} 21. a3 Na6) 21. Rc3 Na5 22. Bh6 Ne8 23. Ra3 Qd7 24. Rd3 Qa4 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. c5 Qxa2 27. Qxa2 Bxa2 28. Rb4 f6 29. cxb6 axb6 30. Rxb6 Bf7 31. h4 Nc4 $11 {1/2-1/2 (32) Korn,H (800)-Wiaderek,P (800) LSS email 2021} *

