{[%evp 0,28,33,33,23,5,42,42,41,7,14,14,14,8,8,-16,15,2,20,23,23,13,24,2,24,34,49,43,36,9,27]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 c6 5. Bg2 d5 6. O-O O-O 7. Nbd2 {This move was popular 10-15 years ago. Nowadays, it's considered to be harmless. The idea is to play b3 and Bb2 or Ba3.} a5 $1 {There are many moves for Black but this move anticipates White's plan.} 8. b3 a4 $1 (8... Bf5 {This is also a big move but I prefer 8...a4 directly in order to create threats on the queenside.}) 9. Ba3 {White's idea is after ...axb3 to recapture axb3.} (9. b4 {Is a bit suspicious after} Ne4 $132 {and White is in an unpleasant position since Nc3 is a potential idea and after Bb2 White needs to be careful of the move ...a3.}) (9. bxa4 Qa5 10. Bb2 (10. Ba3 Re8) 10... Qxa4 $11 {Only Black can be better here.}) (9. Bb2 Ne4 $1 {White is starting to have some problems as ...a3 can be played sometimes.} 10. bxa4 (10. Qc1 Bf5 11. Rd1 Nd7 $11 {Black has a bit more active pieces and Qa5 may come, developing the queen and potentially threatening a3.}) 10... Nc5 $1 {A strong move, using the pin on the long diagonal.} 11. a5 (11. Ba3 Nxa4 12. Qb3 dxc4 13. Nxc4 b5 14. Nce5 Be6 15. Qe3 Bd5 16. Rfc1 Nb6 $11 {The bishop is very strong on d5 and Black is doing very well.}) 11... Qxa5 12. Nb3 Qb4 13. Nxc5 Qxb2 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. a4 Bf5 16. e3 {1/2-1/2 (16) Vinchev,S (2507)-Krivic,D (2508) GER email 2017} Na6 $11) 9... Re8 {The rook is stepping away from the a3-f8 diagonal, and eventually can support e5 if needed.} 10. e3 {This is a typical move in these pawn structures. If White goes with the queen on c2, it can get hit by Bf5, so after e3, the best square for the queen is on e2, in order to connect the rooks.} (10. bxa4 $6 Qa5 {[%csl Ra4]}) (10. Re1 Bf5 {Is similar.} 11. Nh4 Be4 12. Nhf3 (12. f3 Bf5 13. Nxf5 gxf5 {The structure is now different as the bishop on g2 is blocked.} 14. e3 Nbd7 $11 {And eventually e6. Black is very solid.}) 12... Bf5 $11) 10... Bf5 11. Qe2 (11. Re1 e6 (11... Nbd7 {Starting with this move will be similar.}) 12. Ne5 (12. bxa4 Qa5 13. Qb3 Nbd7 $11) (12. Nh4 Bd3 {[%csl Gd3] The bishop is kind of untouchable as the queen and knight on d2 are a bit stuck.}) (12. h3 Nbd7 13. Qe2 h5 14. Nh4 Be4 $11) (12. b4 Nbd7 13. Rc1 Ne4 $11 {The bishop on a3 is kind of blocked and Black has a very solid position.}) 12... Nbd7 13. Bd6 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 (14. dxe5 $6 Ng4 15. f4 f6) 14... Bf8 $132 {[%csl Ra3,Rb2,Rb4,Rc3,Re5][%cal Gf8b4] The bishop will come to b4 and there are a lot of dark-squared weaknesses on the queenside. In addition, Ng4 or Nd7 in order to take the bishop is an idea, so White should be a bit careful.}) 11... Ne4 $5 {This is simpler and Black is equalizing immediately.} (11... Nbd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] This is also a good move and the idea is to push e5.}) 12. Rfc1 (12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Bh3 {With the idea to play Nd2 or Ng5 next, targeting out light-squared bishop.} e6 14. Nd2 Bf5 {g4 is not dangerous as Black has the move Qh4.} 15. Bxf5 exf5 $11) (12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Qb5 Qd7 15. Qxd7 Nxd7 $11 {Black has counterplay down the a-file and also Black can play Rec8 later on, perhaps e6 first.}) 12... Nxd2 {The point is that Black can simply capture the knight on d2.} 13. Qxd2 (13. Nxd2 $2 {This recapture is bad for White because of} e5 $17) 13... Be4 14. Qe2 e6 $11 {Black will play Nd7, and eventually, the light-squared bishops may be exchanged. The pawn structure is extremely solid and the position is equal, but Black can even fight for an advantage because Black is kind of controlling the a-file as it's on Black to decide when to open it up. A potential plan can be to play Qa5 or double the rooks on the a-file at some point. Overall, Black has a good position.} *

