{[%evp 0,44,33,23,23,5,41,41,37,7,15,11,11,8,8,9,22,-16,-22,-4,10,-24,2,-40,-9,-47,0,-15,-15,-5,6,-17,-14,-1,5,-23,-21,-14,-17,-15,-15,5,27,22,43,9,51]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 c6 5. Bg2 d5 6. O-O O-O 7. Qb3 {This is one of the main moves for White. Here Black has 2 options, one is 7...Qb6 and the other one is the move 7...a5!? which in recent years became very popular.} a5 $5 {Black wants to use the queen's placement on b3 and push a4 with tempo. This is a rarer move in comparison to 7...Qb6.} (7... Qb6) 8. Rd1 {This has been the main move lately.} (8. Nc3 a4 {If White captures Nxa4, then follows dxc4, and Qxc4 runs into b5, forking the queen and knight.} 9. Qb4 dxc4 (9... a3 $5 {Giving up the pawn is also interesting, but there is no need for that.}) 10. Qxc4 Bf5 11. Bf4 Nbd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7b6] The knight is coming to b6 and the queen's placement is a bit awkward on c4.}) (8. cxd5 a4 9. Qd1 (9. Qa3 $6 {The queen is awkwardly placed on a3.} cxd5 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Bf4 Bf5 12. Rac1 Qa5 $15 {[%csl Ra3] Black's idea can be Rfc8, e6, and Bf8 to target the White queen on a3.}) 9... cxd5 10. Nc3 Ne4 {If White captures Nxa4, the idea is to play Qa5 and later on play b5 if needed.} 11. Nd2 Nxc3 (11... Bxd4 $5 12. Ndxe4 dxe4 13. Bh6 Re8 {This is also okay for Black.}) 12. bxc3 Nc6 13. Ba3 {1-0 (50) Svidler,P (2723)-Ding Liren (2791) chess24.com INT 2020} (13. e4 Be6 $11) 13... Be6 $1 14. e3 b5 {e4 is not really a threat, however, preventing c4 is important.} 15. Qe2 Qd7 {Qxb5 is not possible due to a Nxd4 tactic!} 16. Rab1 Rab8 $11) (8. Bf4 a4 9. Qb4 Nbd7 {With the idea to bring the knight to b6 or first capture on c4.} 10. Nc3 (10. Rc1 $6 dxc4 11. Qxc4 Nb6 12. Qc5 Bf5 {The White queen is potentially in some trouble, as Black may want to play Ne4.} 13. Rd1 Nbd5 14. Be5 Bh6 $15 {1/2-1/2 (48) Dreev,A (2662)-Narayanan,S (2611) Douglas ENG 2019}) 10... dxc4 11. Qxc4 Nb6 12. Qd3 Nfd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bd2 Qb6 $11 {The queen is putting pressure on b2 and the next moves can be Be6 or Bg4, and then playing Rd8. Black is doing well.}) 8... a4 9. Qb4 dxc4 10. Qxc4 {Black has different plans now:} Bf5 {A typical move for this variation.} (10... Be6 {There are a lot of games with this move.} 11. Qb4 Qa5 12. Qxa5 Rxa5 13. Nc3 $14 {The endgame may be more pleasant for White.}) (10... b5 $5) 11. e3 {Making a safety square for the queen on e2.} (11. Bf4 Nbd7 12. Qc1 {It's not easy for White to play Nc3 with the queen still on c4, as the queen would have been in some danger.} Qb6 $11) 11... Qd5 $5 $146 {This is the best way to proceed with Black.} (11... Nbd7 12. Qe2 $14 {Black is a bit more passive but it's still a playable position. A potential idea can be Qa5 and then Qa6.}) 12. Qb4 (12. Nfd2 Qxc4 13. Nxc4 {White spent some tempi with the knight.} Nbd7 14. Nc3 b5 $5 (14... Be6 {This is also possible.}) 15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nd7 17. Bxc6 Nxe5 18. Bxa8 Rxa8 {Black sacrificed an exchange but all of Black's pieces are perfectly placed.} 19. f4 Nc4 20. e4 a3 $1 21. exf5 axb2 22. Bxb2 Nxb2 23. Rdc1 Na4 24. Nxb5 Bxa1 25. Rxa1 gxf5 $11) (12. Qxd5 cxd5 13. Nc3 Nc6 14. Bd2 Rfc8 $11) (12. Na3 Be4 $11) (12. Nbd2 Rd8 $5 13. Qe2 (13. Ne5 Qxc4 14. Ndxc4 Ng4 $11 {Black exchanges some pieces.}) 13... Qb5 $1 {Black provokes White to capture on b5 and to create doubled pawns.} 14. Qxb5 cxb5 15. Ne5 Bc2 16. Rf1 Nd5 $132 {The bishop on g2 is strong but the whole White queenside is passive. There is enough counterplay and I already prefer Black here.}) (12. Qe2 {If White retreats with the queen, Black can take the pawn.} Bxb1 $1 13. Rxb1 Qxa2 14. Qc2 Nbd7 15. Bd2 (15. e4 Rfc8 $132) 15... Qe6 16. Bb4 Rfe8 $132 {White has some compensation, but a pawn is a pawn. Black is also very solid.}) 12... Qd6 {Is a bit easier as Black is trying to exchange the queens.} (12... c5 $5 13. Qa3 Rd8 14. Nc3 Qc4 15. Ne5 Qb4 {Is also possible.}) 13. Qe1 (13. Bd2 Nbd7 $11 {Black can simply develop.}) (13. Qc4 Qd5 $11) 13... Bc2 $1 {Black is disturbing White's rook.} 14. Rd2 Bf5 15. Nc3 {If White wants to play on, Black can exchange the knights.} (15. Rd1 Bc2 $11) 15... Ne4 16. Rd1 Nxc3 17. bxc3 (17. Qxc3 $6 e5 $15) 17... Bc2 $1 18. Rd2 Be4 19. Nh4 (19. Qe2 b5 {Taking control over the light squares.}) 19... Bxg2 20. Nxg2 b5 {It's important to prevent c4.} 21. e4 e5 22. Rb1 Re8 $132 {Black wants the knight to eventually reach the c4 square with Nd7-Nb6-Nc4. It's a complicated game ahead and Black is doing well.} *

