{[%evp 0,34,23,23,23,4,37,6,6,-4,-3,2,-3,6,76,70,58,24,49,49,92,35,34,17,38,-4,-4,-4,25,14,28,19,59,9,18,18,13]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 {This move became popular lately. The point is that Black can't play 3...d5 now as there is 4.cxd5-Nxd5 and 5.h5. I believe the best way for Black is to go for the Benoni set-up.} Bg7 4. Nc3 c5 $1 5. d5 (5. dxc5 {Doesn't seem dangerous for Black.} Na6 {Trying to take the pawn back.} 6. g3 (6. Be3 $6 Ng4 7. Bd2 (7. Bd4 $2 e5 $17) 7... Nxc5 8. Nh3 d6 9. e3 Nf6 10. Nf4 Nfe4 $15 {1-0 (57) Ivanisevic,I (2645)-Neubauer,M (2413) Plovdiv 2012}) (6. e4 Nxc5 7. f3 (7. e5 $6 Nfe4 $15) 7... d6 $132 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gc8e6,Gd8a5] It's a playable position with Be6 and Qa5 to be played next. The pawn on h4 doesn't make much sense in this set-up.}) 6... Nxc5 7. Nh3 {[%cal Gh3f4]} d6 8. Nf4 Bf5 $5 {With the idea to control the e4 square and to play Rc8 and Nfe4 quickly.} 9. Bg2 Rc8 10. h5 Nfe4 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Bxe4 Nxe4 13. Qd5 Nc5 $11 {Black has a solid position and the trade hxg6 hxg6 doesn't lead to anything for White.}) 5... d6 (5... e6 {Not 5...e6 immediately because White is not obliged to go e4, instead, White can capture on e6.} 6. dxe6 $5 dxe6 (6... fxe6 7. e4 $14 {Looks a bit unpleasant as e5 is a potential idea for White.}) 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1] This endgame is more pleasant for White.}) 6. e4 e6 7. Be2 {[%cal Gh4h5] This is the main move, trying to push h5 next.} (7. h5 {This has been played by some players but it's too much in my opinion and White is just losing a pawn.} Nxh5 8. g4 Nf6 9. g5 Nh5 10. Be2 exd5 (10... Bxc3+ $5 {This is also possible, giving the knight a retreat square on g7.} 11. bxc3 Ng7 12. Be3 Qe7 $13) 11. Nxd5 (11. cxd5 {0-1 (56) Goldsmith,A (2130) -Cowley,R (2110) Adelaide 2004} Qe7 $1 12. Bxh5 gxh5 13. Qxh5 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 Qxe4+ 15. Qe2 Bf5 $15) (11. Bxh5 d4 $5 {This is an extra option that Black has with this move order.} (11... gxh5 12. Nxd5 Nc6 {Transposes to 11.Nd5.}) 12. Nd5 gxh5 13. Ne2 {White wants to capture the h-pawn with the knight.} (13. Qxh5 Be6 $15) 13... Bg4 14. Qb3 Nc6 15. Nef4 Ne5 16. Nxh5 Bxh5 17. Rxh5 Qd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7g4,Ge8c8] Next Black wants to play moves like 0-0-0 or Qg4, with a sharp position.}) 11... Nc6 12. Bxh5 gxh5 13. Bf4 (13. Rxh5 Be6 $132 {[%cal Gc6d4]}) 13... Be6 14. Qd2 Qd7 15. O-O-O O-O-O 16. Ne2 Bg4 17. Qe3 Bxe2 {f3 was a threat, so it's best to capture the knight on e2.} 18. Qxe2 Qe6 19. Rxh5 h6 $11 {Black has no problems and is at least equal in this position.}) 7... exd5 8. exd5 (8. cxd5 $6 Qe7 {[%csl Re4] Black immediately puts pressure on the pawn on e4.} 9. Qc2 Na6 $132 {[%cal Ga6b4]}) 8... Nbd7 $1 {This is a better move-order as it's good for Black to postpone castling short because if Black castles short, the king can get under attack. The main idea is after h5 that Black can capture the pawn with Nxh5.} (8... O-O $6 9. h5 Re8 10. h6 $1 Bh8 11. Bg5 $36 {[%csl Gg5,Rh8]}) 9. Nf3 {The main move.} (9. Bf4 Ne5 10. Nf3 (10. Qd2 $6 O-O 11. Kf1 Re8 12. b3 {1-0 (39) Maghsoodloo,P (2699)-Abdusattorov, N (2661) Chess.com INT 2022} a6 13. h5 b5 $17 {[%cal Gg7a1,Gb5b4] White's attack isn't as fast as Black's counterplay.}) 10... Neg4 $1 {Putting the knight on g4 is a recurring idea in this variation.} 11. O-O O-O $132 {[%cal Gf8e8,Gf6h5] It seems very good for Black as Nh5 is coming and the knight on g4 is perfectly placed.}) (9. h5 Nxh5 $1 10. Bxh5 (10. g4 $6 Nhf6 11. g5 Ng8 $15 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7e5]}) 10... gxh5 11. Qe2+ (11. Qxh5 $6 Ne5 {The knight is well-placed on e5 and there can be moves such as Nd3+ or Nxc4.}) 11... Qe7 12. Qxe7+ (12. Bg5 $6 {This is not very accurate because Black can take} Bxc3+ $1 13. bxc3 f6 14. Bf4 {1/2-1/2 (30) Fernandez,D (2492)-Kuybokarov,T (2587) Canberra 2022} Ne5 $1 {This gives Black the better chances.} 15. Qxh5+ Kd7 16. Bxe5 fxe5 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4] The king will be safe on c7 and White has a lot of weaknesses.}) 12... Kxe7 13. Bg5+ Kf8 14. Ne4 (14. Kd2 Rg8 15. Bf4 Be5 16. Bh6+ Bg7 $11) 14... h6 $1 {It's important to start with h6! in order to prevent any Bh6 checks.} (14... Bxb2 $6 {This may be a bit too much.} 15. Rb1 Be5 16. Bh6+ Ke7 17. Rxh5 $36 {This is a bit unpleasant for Black.}) 15. Bf4 Ne5 $132 {It's a sharp position which is okay for Black. Nd3 is a threat now.}) (9. Kf1 $5 $146 {This is a novelty and it's the computer's suggestion. Black needs to know the h6 idea which is important.} Ne5 $1 {It's important to start with Ne5 as castling will be similar to the other line where Black castles on the previous move.} (9... O-O 10. h5 Re8 11. h6 Bh8 12. Bg5 $14 {[%csl Gg5,Rg7,Gh6,Rh8]}) 10. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2] White wants to play Kg2 next.} (10. h5 h6 $1 {Black hasn't castled yet so h6! is a very interesting idea.} 11. Nf3 ({The point of h6 can be seen in this line:} 11. f4 Neg4 12. hxg6 fxg6 13. Bd3 Bf5 $132 {And this is good for Black.}) (11. hxg6 fxg6) 11... Nxf3 12. Bxf3 g5 $132 {0-0 is next and Black can even try to take over.}) 10... O-O 11. Kg2 (11. h5 $6 h6 $1 {Trying to play g5. After a trade on g6 with hxg6 and fxg6, the pawn on h6 is never hanging due to Nfg4 ideas.}) 11... a6 12. a4 Re8 13. f3 {[%cal Gg1h3,Gh3f2] White wants to place the g1 knight to f2, via the h3 square.} b6 {[%cal Ga8a7,Ga7e7] Black wants to include the rook through the 7th rank in the game.} 14. Nh3 Ra7 15. Nf2 Rae7 $11) 9... Ng4 $1 {The knight is very well placed on g4.} (9... O-O 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rd6]} Qb6 11. Qd2 $14) 10. h5 (10. O-O Ndf6 $132 {We already saw something similar.}) (10. Ng5 Ndf6 11. Bxg4 (11. f3 Ne5 12. Kf2 a6 13. a4 h6 14. Nh3 Bxh3 15. Rxh3 Qd7 16. a5 O-O-O $132 {This position is dangerous for White as White's king is much weaker. A typical plan for White would be Na4, Rb1, and b4, but it seems to be too slow.} 17. Na4 $6 Kb8 18. b4 cxb4 19. Rb1 Rhe8 20. Rxb4 Re7 $15 {[%cal Gd8e8] White doesn't have clear threats. Rde8 is next and White has problems with the coordination of the pieces.}) 11... Nxg4 {[%cal Gg4e5] Is better with the idea Ne5.} (11... Bxg4 $6 12. f3) 12. Qe2+ Qe7 13. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {The endgame is approximately equal.} 14. Bf4 Ne5 15. O-O-O h6 16. Nge4 f5 17. Nxc5 Nxc4 18. Rde1+ Kf7 19. Ne6 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8] The knight seems to be well placed on e6 but it doesn't do much. The knight on c4 is good and Rac8 is coming.}) 10... O-O $1 {It's committing the king to the kingside but it's the best move. The main idea is that after h6, Black can take Bxc3.} (10... Qe7 {1/2-1/2 (88) Ding,L (2805)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2767) Ekaterinburg 2021 CBM 202 [Edouard, Romain]} 11. Qc2 $14) 11. Ng5 (11. h6 Bxc3+ $1 12. bxc3 Qe7 13. O-O Nde5 14. Re1 f6 $11 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4] The pawn on h6 isn't dangerous, the queen can potentially come to f7 and White's pawns are very weak. Black can consider playing g5 later on.}) (11. Bg5 Bxc3+ $1 12. bxc3 Ndf6 $1 {It's an unusual idea to go under a pin voluntarily, but it's good in this position.} 13. Qd2 Re8 14. hxg6 (14. O-O $6 Ne4) 14... fxg6 15. O-O Ne4 16. Qf4 Nxg5 17. Nxg5 Qf6 $11 {Black is doing well.}) (11. Bd2 {Preventing Bxc3.} Re8 12. Kf1 (12. hxg6 {Doesn't do much for White.} fxg6) (12. h6 Bh8 {Is not the same as in the previous cases, now Black will quickly jump Nde5.}) 12... Ndf6 13. h6 Bh8 14. Ng5 Bf5 15. Rh4 Qd7 $11 {There are a lot of Black pieces on the kingside and it's difficult for White to get rid of them. For example, f3 can be met with Ne3+. Black can also double the rooks on the e-file, and overall, Black has enough counterplay here.}) 11... Re8 12. Kf1 Ndf6 {Provoking an exchange on g6.} 13. hxg6 hxg6 14. g3 (14. Kg1 {Is similar but a bit slower.} a6 15. a4 b6 {[%cal Ga8a7,Ga7e7] The idea is to bring the rook into the game through the 7th rank.} 16. g3 Ra7 17. Bf4 Rae7 $11) 14... Bf5 15. Rh4 Qd7 16. Kg2 (16. Bf4 Re7 {Will lead to the same thing.}) 16... Re7 17. Bf4 Rae8 $132 *

